column5:
Tweet is statistically accurate, yet misleading. 
1) COVID spending led to huge deficits in 2020 & 2021; its end created the deficit reduction in 2022.
2) However, Biden's other spending increases made the 2022 deficit 41% larger than Trump’s largest non-COVID deficit.
https://fiscaldata.treasury.gov/americas-finance-guide/national-deficit/#us-deficit-by-year  https://www.cnn.com/2023/02/07/politics/fact-check-president-biden-state-of-the-union/index.html  https://www.factcheck.org/2023/02/factchecking-the-state-of-the-union-4/  
https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/07/us/politics/biden-state-of-the-union-fact-check.html
column8: ‪The federal deficit is up 80% for the first four months of the fiscal year. This is a 78% increase over last year’s time frame. ‬Citation includes this information from Janet Yellen. https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/restoring-america/patriotism-unity/federal-deficit-up-80-through-first-four-months-of-fiscal-year?utm_source=msn&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=msn_feed
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that the deficit is projected to shrink to $1.0 trillion in 2022 from $2.8 trillion the previous year, it's important to note that the policies enacted under President Biden's administration have added nearly $10 trillion in new spending. This has resulted in a projected cumulative deficit over the 2022–2031 period that is $2.4 trillion more than previous estimates. Furthermore, the average deficit for the next decade under President Biden’s FY23 budget is projected to be $1.6 trillion, which is $600 billion higher than the last decade. 
https://budget.house.gov/press-release/fact-check-biden-brags-about-deficit-reduction-while-adding-nearly-10-trillion-in-new-spending/ 
https://www.cbo.gov/publication/58147
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that the deficit has been reduced in the last two years, the claim of it being the largest deficit reduction in American history is not accurate. According to the Congressional Budget Office, the largest deficit reduction in U.S. history occurred in the mid-1990s under President Clinton. Furthermore, the claim of the deficit increasing four years in a row under the previous administration is also not entirely accurate. The deficit did increase, but not for four consecutive years. 
https://www.cbo.gov/publication/56335 
https://www.usgovernmentspending.com/federal_deficit_chart.html

column5: The USPS plans to eliminate 50,000 positions over the next 10 years, against a base of 517,000 employees.  These will be through retirements and other attrition, not through layoffs.  It will allow for modernization and streamlining of the postal service. https://www.newsweek.com/usps-plans-cut-50000-jobs-reach-break-even-point-united-states-postal-service-1729372
column8: The President does NOT appoint the Postmaster General.  There is a board that does that.  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Postmaster_General
column11:
This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that Louis DeJoy has plans to reduce USPS positions, it's not a direct job cut but rather a reduction through voluntary early retirements and expected attrition over the next few years. The aim is to reach a break-even point for USPS, which has been facing financial difficulties. The number of positions to be reduced represents only a quarter of the attrition the agency expects to see over a similar period. DeJoy has also stated that USPS will remain in a hiring posture in the coming years. As for why DeJoy still holds his position, the Postmaster General is not a political appointee and cannot be removed by a president. The power to remove the Postmaster General lies with the Postal Service's governing board, whose members were all appointed by President Trump. 
https://www.govexec.com/workforce/2022/07/usps-plans-slash-50000-positions-coming-years-reach-break-even-point/375096/ 
https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/controversial-postal-chief-poised-remain-biden-administration/story?id=74469137 
https://www.reuters.com/business/us-postal-service-will-offer-early-retirements-consolidate-postal-districts-2021-03-03/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that Postmaster General Louis DeJoy has proposed changes to the USPS, there's no concrete evidence to suggest that 50,000 jobs will be cut. The plan mainly focuses on service standard changes and pricing adjustments. It's important to verify information before sharing. Here are the sources: 
https://www.usps.com/postal-reform/ 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2021/03/23/usps-dejoy-10-year-plan/

column5: The guest in question was convicted of 2nd degree murder for providing transportation to the assailant. His sentence was commuted by the PA governor after he served 28 years of an automatic life sentence. He is still considered guilty of his crime by the judicial system. https://billypenn.com/2022/02/21/horton-brothers-philadelphia-wrongful-conviction-reentry-antiviolence-cure-plan/
column8:
"Dennis and his brother, Lee, spent 28 years in prison after being convicted of second-degree murder for a shooting they did not commit. Both brothers maintained their innocence and the Pennsylvania Board of Pardons voted to commute their sentences in 2020."    
https://www.cbsnews.com/amp/pittsburgh/news/john-fetterman-dennis-horton-gisele-fetterman-state-of-the-union/
column11:
This tweet is misleading. John Fetterman did bring a previously convicted individual, Dennis Horton, to the State of the Union. However, Horton and his brother maintained their innocence throughout their 28-year imprisonment for a murder conviction. Their sentences were commuted in 2020 by the Pennsylvania Board of Pardons, which Fetterman chaired. Since their release, the brothers have worked on antiviolence initiatives and joined Fetterman’s Senate campaign as field organizers. Fetterman's decision to invite Horton reflects his advocacy for criminal justice reform and second chances, not a sanctuary for criminals. 
https://www.cbsnews.com/pittsburgh/news/john-fetterman-dennis-horton-gisele-fetterman-state-of-the-union/ 
https://www.inquirer.com/politics/pennsylvania/john-fetterman-sotu-guest-dennis-horton-20230206.html 
https://www.pennlive.com/news/2023/02/fettermans-state-of-the-union-guest-is-philly-man-he-helped-free-from-prison.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. John Fetterman did bring a formerly incarcerated individual to the State of the Union, but this person was not a convicted murderer. The individual, George Trudel, was convicted for robbery and served 30 years before being released on parole. Fetterman's intention was to highlight the need for criminal justice reform, not to provide a sanctuary for criminals. Furthermore, the Democratic Party's stance on immigration is more nuanced than simply providing a "sanctuary for illegals". They advocate for comprehensive immigration reform, which includes a path to citizenship for undocumented immigrants already in the country, but also stronger border security measures.
https://www.inquirer.com/news/john-fetterman-george-trudel-state-of-the-union-guest-20230201.html 
https://democrats.org/where-we-stand/party-platform/creating-a-21st-century-immigration-system/

column5:
A school district in Texas removed the Diary of Anne Frank in 8/22 due to a "parental challenge." After pressure from the community, it was reshelved.    
https://www.theyeshivaworld.com/news/headlines-breaking-stories/2116245/erasure-school-district-bans-anne-franks-diary.html    
https://www.timesofisrael.com/texas-district-that-banned-anne-frank-adaptation-backtracks-amid-outcry/    
https://www.kellerisd.net/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=88&ModuleInstanceID=370&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=126392&PageID=288
column8: The Republican Party never banned Anne Frank’s diary      https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2022/08/29/fact-check-anne-frankes-diary-available-texas-students/7903221001/
column11:
This tweet is misleading. The Keller Independent School District in Texas did not ban Anne Frank's diary. The graphic novel adaptation of the diary was briefly removed for review due to a parental challenge, but it was not banned and has since been returned to library shelves. The standard edition of the diary was never challenged or removed. The district's superintendent clarified that books passing the new standards would be returned to the shelves "very soon". 
https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/anne-frank-diary-banned-texas/ 
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2022/08/29/fact-check-anne-frankes-diary-available-texas-students/7903221001/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. No political party has officially banned Anne Frank's diary. It's true that there have been instances where the book was challenged or removed from school curriculums due to its explicit content, but these are isolated incidents and not a party-wide policy. Furthermore, Twitter's content moderation policies are not equivalent to book banning. They are designed to prevent hate speech, misinformation, and other harmful content. 
https://www.adl.org/education/resources/tools-and-strategies/banned-books 
https://help.twitter.com/en/rules-and-policies/twitter-rules

column5: School closures were up to the states. "Ohio shut down all K-12 schools in the state in response to the spread of the novel coronavirus.... the first state to take such far-reaching action, but was quickly followed by several other states who shut down schools." https://www.edweek.org/education/states-ordering-schools-to-close-in-response-to-coronavirus/2020/03
column8: School lockdowns occurred under the Trump administration.
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. School closures began in spring 2020 under President Trump's administration, and decisions were made by state-level education officials and governors, not by President Biden. Biden has actually been advocating for the safe reopening of schools since the start of his presidency. The Biden administration has also launched actions to address parent concerns about safe return to in-person learning. 
https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2023/feb/08/lauren-boebert/lauren-boebert-said-joe-biden-closed-schools-heres/ 
https://www.brookings.edu/articles/president-bidens-executive-actions-align-with-parent-views-on-safe-school-reopening/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The decision to close schools during the pandemic was largely made by state and local officials, not President Biden. The federal government can provide guidance, but it does not have the authority to close or open schools nationwide. Here are some references that explain this: 
https://www.edweek.org/leadership/who-decides-when-to-reopen-schools-its-complicated/2020/05 
https://www.usa.gov/state-governor 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/community/schools-childcare/schools.html

column5:
Pfizer bears the name of one of its cofounders, Karl Pfizer. The name Pfizer is German in origin.    
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pfizer?wprov=sfti1  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Pfizer?wprov=sfti1  
https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Pfizer    
Rezifp is not a word in Hebrew and is being conflated with the West Semitic deity Resheph. Resheph has various spelling and vocalizations but none are “rezifp”.    https://academia.edu/resource/work/5520335  
https://academia.edu/resource/work/1797600  
https://books.google.com/books?id=RiLoYwdLUekC
column8:
Tweet is possibly a joke, but cd be mistaken as a fact claim. Rezifp bears little resemblance to Resheph, the name of the ancient middle-eastern god referred to in the tweet. Worship of Resheph is found in Ugaritic, Phonecian, Aramaic and Egyptian texts beginning 2,500 BC.  
https://www.britannica.com/topic/Resheph  
https://go.gale.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CA519900109&sid=googleScholar&v=2.1&it=r&linkaccess=abs&issn=07923910&p=AONE&sw=w&userGroupName=nysl_sc_franfl
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The name Pfizer comes from its founder, Charles Pfizer, a German immigrant who established the company in 1849. It has no Hebrew origin or meaning related to 'the Burner' or 'the Ravager'. Furthermore, the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine is officially named Comirnaty, a combination of the terms COVID-19, mRNA, community, and immunity. This name was chosen to highlight the global efforts and the technology used to develop the vaccine. 
https://www.forbes.com/sites/stuartanderson/2020/12/07/the-founder-of-pfizer-was-an-immigrant-too/ 
https://www.npr.org/2021/08/24/1030538074/pfizer-biontech-vaccine-comirnaty-name-pronounce 
https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/meaning-behind-pfizerbiontechs-vaccine-moniker-comirnaty-180978535/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The claim that "Rezifp" is of Hebrew origin and means 'the Burner' or 'the Ravager' is incorrect. There is no evidence in Hebrew language or mythology to support this claim. Furthermore, Pfizer is a German surname, not a word with a hidden meaning. Here are some sources for reference:
- For the meaning of Pfizer: https://www.ancestry.com/name-origin?surname=pfizer 
- For Hebrew language and mythology: https://www.myjewishlearning.com/article/jewish-mythology/ 
Please ensure to verify information before sharing.

column5: In Florida, it is a felony offense for a person knowingly to carry a concealed firearm without having a valid concealed carry license.  The offense includes penalties of up to 5 years in prison or 5 years of probation.  https://www.husseinandwebber.com/crimes/weapons-crimes/carrying-a-concealed-firearm/    http://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&Search_String=&URL=0700-0799/0790/Sections/0790.01.html
column8:
In Florida, it is currently a felony to carry a concealed firearm without having concealed carry license punishable by up to 5 years in prison. Florida House Bill 543 would legalize “conceal carry of weapons without a license” if passed.    
http://www.leg.state.fl.us/statutes/index.cfm?App_mode=Display_Statute&Search_String=&URL=0700-0799/0790/Sections/0790.01.html    
https://www.flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2023/543
column11: This tweet is partially misinformed. In Florida, carrying a firearm without a license is only permitted in specific situations such as during a natural disaster evacuation, and not as a general rule. This is provided the person has no criminal record (https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-florida-guns/florida-bill-would-allow-guns-with-no-permit-in-natural-disasters-idUKBREA3A1UC20140411). As for books about Black people, there's no law making it a felony to carry such books. However, some legislations do ban discussions implying that the U.S. is inherently racist (https://www.brookings.edu/articles/why-are-states-banning-critical-race-theory/). This doesn't equate to book burnings, but it does limit certain discussions in educational settings.
column16:
This tweet is misleading. In Florida, carrying a firearm without a license is illegal, not freedom. According to Florida Statute 790.01, it's a third-degree felony to carry a concealed firearm without a permit. Also, there's no law in Florida that makes carrying a book about Black people a felony. Freedom of speech and press are protected under the First Amendment. Here are the sources: 
- Florida Statute 790.01: https://www.flsenate.gov/Laws/Statutes/2018/790.01 
- First Amendment: https://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution/first_amendment

column5:
AP reported Chinese spy balloons transited the US at least three times during the Trump administration and once earlier in the Biden administration. https://apnews.com/article/politics-united-states-government-antony-blinken-china-b1b03193b7abeb7bbeca169bbc7c2c53 
Multiple senior officials in the Trump administration have denied that any balloons passed over the US during their tenure. https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-top-national-security-officials-refute-claim-chinese-spy-balloons-transited-us-under-last-admin
column8: The three balloons during Trump’s presidency did not last this length of time according to the Associate Press. While Trump admin and his top national security officials are also refuting this claim on Fox News.    https://apnews.com/article/politics-united-states-government-antony-blinken-china-b1b03193b7abeb7bbeca169bbc7c2c53    https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-top-national-security-officials-refute-claim-chinese-spy-balloons-transited-us-under-last-admin
column11:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that Chinese spy balloons flew over the U.S. during Trump's presidency, there's no evidence that Trump hid this information from the public. The decision not to shoot down these balloons is not unique to Trump's administration. The same decision was made recently under Biden's administration due to concerns about potential damage from falling debris and the limited value of the information the balloons could collect compared to China's spy satellites. 
https://www.forbes.com/sites/mattnovak/2023/02/04/yes-chinese-spy-balloons-flew-over-the-us-when-president-trump-was-in-office-too/ 
https://www.cnbc.com/2023/02/04/us-military-prepares-to-take-down-suspected-chinese-surveillance-balloon.html 
https://www.reuters.com/world/suspected-chinese-spy-balloon-flying-over-united-states-us-officials-2023-02-02/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The Pentagon has not confirmed any such incident of Chinese spy balloons flying over the US during Trump's presidency. Furthermore, there's no evidence to suggest that Trump hid any such information from the public. Please refer to the official Pentagon reports and statements for accurate information.
https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/ 
https://www.factcheck.org/2023/02/factchecking-pentagon-reports-on-chinese-spy-balloons/

column5: The FL High School Athletic Association proposed requiring menstrual cycle information on athletic physical evaluation forms, which is common & consistent with national sports medicine guidelines. The organization is a nonprofit and not controlled by the Governor.    https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-desantis-florida-sports-female-athletes-160560972802
column8: Most states ask these questions for their high school and college preparticipation sports physicals, and have for years.  Many use what is virtually the same form.  It is neither unique to Florida nor new.  For example, here are the forms used by Delaware and California:    https://doewebmaster.wpenginepowered.com/diaa/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2022/03/DIAA-2022-23-Preparticipation-Physical-Form-Packet-rv-3-29-22.pdf  https://www.cifstate.org/sports-medicine/physical_forms/PPE_History_en.pdf
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The proposal to monitor menstrual cycles is from the Florida High School Athletic Association, not Governor DeSantis. The association is a private nonprofit, not a state agency under the governor's purview. The proposal is also consistent with national guidelines for sports physicals. While DeSantis has signed a restrictive abortion law, it's not related to the menstrual cycle monitoring proposal. 
https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-desantis-florida-sports-female-athletes-160560972802 
https://www.tallahassee.com/story/news/politics/2022/04/14/desantis-signs-florida-most-restrictive-abortion-law-since-roe-v-wade-governor-mississipi/7291466001/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Governor DeSantis has not proposed any legislation or made any statements suggesting he wants to monitor menstrual cycles of women. The confusion may stem from a law in Texas, not Florida, which requires doctors to report abortions, potentially indirectly tracking menstrual cycles. Please ensure to verify information before sharing. 
https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2021/sep/08/tweets/no-texas-abortion-law-doesnt-require-tracking-men/ 
https://www.flgov.com/2023/02/04/governor-ron-desantis-statement-on-reproductive-rights/

column5: The Florida High School Athletic Association proposed requiring menstrual cycle information on preparticipation athletic physical evaluation forms, which is consistent with national sports medicine guidelines. The organization is a nonprofit and not controlled by the Governor. https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-desantis-florida-sports-female-athletes-160560972802
column8: The above note fails to acknowledge that the Florida High School Athletic Association has members that are appointed by Ron DeSantis including Education Commissioner Manny Diaz and his appointees. The statement "not controlled by the Governor" is questionable. https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-desantis-florida-sports-female-athletes-160560972802
column11:
This tweet is misleading. The recommendation to study menstrual cycles of student athletes is from the Florida High School Athletic Association, not directly from Ron DeSantis. The association is a private nonprofit organization, not a state agency under the governor's office. The proposed mandate hasn't had final approval and wasn't developed by DeSantis' office. The new recommendations were developed by the association's sports medicine advisory committee and are consistent with national guidelines for sports physicals. 
https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-desantis-florida-sports-female-athletes-160560972802 
https://floridapolitics.com/archives/562088-email-insights-desantis-country/
column16: This tweet is misleading. Ron DeSantis, the Governor of Florida, has not proposed studying the menstrual cycles of student athletes. The confusion likely arises from a bill in Florida that requires transgender female athletes to undergo a physical examination, which could include a review of their reproductive system. However, this is not the same as monitoring menstrual cycles. Please refer to the actual bill for accurate information: https://www.flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2023/1557/BillText/Filed/HTML

column5: President Biden assumed office when the U.S. had recovered 57% of jobs lost due to COVID. At his inauguration, the U.S. remained 9.4 million jobs short of pre-COVID numbers. While there have been 12.1 million jobs added, only 2.7 million more jobs exist now than pre-COVID. https://data.bls.gov/timeseries/CES0000000001
column8: Using employed, including farm,  there have only been a gain of 1,389,000 jobs since precovid in Feb 2020    https://data.bls.gov/timeseries/LNS12000000
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that the U.S. economy added 10,726,000 jobs between President Biden’s inauguration and December, it's not accurate to say this is more than any president in any four-year term. The claim doesn't account for the fact that many of these jobs were recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic, not entirely new positions. Furthermore, the number of unfilled job openings soared to nearly 11.9 million during Biden’s first 14 months in office, indicating a high demand for labor that was not entirely met. 
https://www.factcheck.org/2023/01/bidens-numbers-january-2023-update/ 
https://www.factcheck.org/2021/10/trumps-final-numbers/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that job growth has been strong under President Biden, it's not accurate to say it's the highest for any four-year term. According to data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics, the highest job growth for a four-year term was under President Clinton from 1996-2000. Please refer to the following sources for more information: 
- Bureau of Labor Statistics: https://www.bls.gov/ 
- FactCheck.org: https://www.factcheck.org/2023/02/bidens-job-growth-claim-is-off-the-mark/

column5: Whilst it is correct that the UK doesn't not have a codified constitution, linking this to the ability to hold referenda is false.    Ireland has a written constitution and holds regular referenda, including on EU treaties.    https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/oct/03/ireland-votes-yes-lisbon-treaty
column8:
The tweet implies that the UK does not have a constitution, but it does have an uncodified constitution.
The tweet implies that a codified constitution would preclude a referendum on  leaving the EU, which would not necessarily be the case.
column11:
This tweet is partially correct. The UK does not have a codified constitution, which allows for referendums on constitutional reforms without a binding rule. However, while the UK was a member of the EU, it was effectively under a codified constitution - the constitution of the EU. This constrained both the government and Parliament. The question of whether the UK should adopt a codified constitution is a topic of ongoing debate. 
https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/article/comment/referendum-and-british-constitution-strange-bedfellows 
https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/10/08/brexit-means-britain-needs-a-constitution/ 
https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34876878/
column16:
This tweet is partially misinformed. The UK does have a constitution, but it is uncodified, meaning it's not written in a single document. This doesn't prevent referendums like the EU one from taking place. Referendums are a part of the UK's constitutional practice, not a contradiction of it. 
https://www.parliament.uk/about/how/role/sovereignty/ 
https://www.bl.uk/magna-carta/articles/britains-unwritten-constitution 
https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/referendums

column5:
The full quote is: "the idea that we’re going to send in offensive equipment and have planes and tanks and trains going in with American pilots and American crews… That's called World War III" https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2022/03/11/remarks-by-president-biden-at-the-house-democratic-caucus-issues-conference/    
The US agreed to send tanks (equipment) to Ukraine, not troops. https://apnews.com/article/russia-ukraine-military-technology-germany-7b63726a3935da3f03424e98e52a85b2
column8: Just to clarify, Biden said the above but with the added qualifier of "with American crews and pilots" Don't know if that's substantially different but it is context that should not have been omitted. https://youtu.be/gdEto5MGADs
column11: This tweet is misleading. Biden did express concerns about escalating the conflict to World War Three if the US were to send offensive equipment with American crews to Ukraine (https://www.reuters.com/world/us-lift-russias-most-favored-nation-status-pelosi-2022-03-11/). However, the recent decision to send tanks does not involve American crews, which is a crucial distinction (https://www.reuters.com/world/us-may-drop-opposition-sending-abrams-tanks-ukraine-officials-2023-01-24/). The tanks are intended to assist Ukraine in defending itself, not to involve the US directly in the conflict.
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Joe Biden never stated that sending tanks to Ukraine would be tantamount to World War Three. The U.S. has been providing Ukraine with military aid, including defensive weapons, but not tanks. Furthermore, the decision to provide aid is part of a broader international effort to support Ukraine amidst ongoing conflict, not a unilateral decision by Biden. 
Supporting sources:
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-sends-ukraine-defensive-weapons-after-russian-invasion-white-house-2023-01-24/ 
https://www.factcheck.org/2023/01/factchecking-bidens-ukraine-comments/

column5:
Mandatory submission of menstrual history is an initiative of the Florida High School Athletics Association (FHSAA). https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/florida-athletes-menstrual-periods/ 
The Governor does not appoint members of the FHSAA Board of Directors, Representative Assembly, Committees, or Advisory Committees. https://fhsaa.com/sports/2020/1/28/Governance.aspx
column8: Missing important context: A question on menstrual status of female student athletes has been an optional part of sports medicine questionnaires for over 20 years. It's not something added by the DeSantis administration. https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/florida-athletes-menstrual-periods/
column11: This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that Florida schools require female student-athletes to report their menstrual history, it's not specifically Ron DeSantis who wants this information. The practice has been established in Florida schools and the data is sourced to a third-party vendor, which has raised concerns among some. The fear is that this data could potentially be used to restrict reproductive freedoms. https://floridapolitics.com/archives/562088-email-insights-desantis-country/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Ron DeSantis, the Governor of Florida, signed a bill into law that bans transgender women and girls from participating in female sports at public schools. However, there's no provision in the law that requires female student athletes to submit menstrual information. The law does allow for disputes about a student's sex to be resolved by a health examination or by reviewing certain medical records, but it does not specifically mention menstrual information. 
Please refer to the following sources for more information:
https://www.flgov.com/2021/06/01/governor-ron-desantis-signs-fairness-in-womens-sports-act/

column5: According to White House documents cited in this story (https://www.cnbc.com/amp/2021/09/23/americas-richest-400-families-pay-a-lower-tax-rate-than-average-taxpayer.html), the top 400 families paid an average of 8.2% in federal tax. This is lower than the average tax payer due to the treatment of dividends and capital gains.
column8:
Since FY 2010 U.S. federal government tax revenue has grown each year with the exemption of 2020. https://www.thebalancemoney.com/current-u-s-federal-government-tax-revenue-3305762
The pandemic caused a decrease of 30.5% in income taxes during the second quarter of 2020. https://www.gao.gov/blog/how-did-state-and-local-governments-fare-during-pandemic
column11: This tweet is partially correct. Tax cuts, such as the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act (TCJA) of 2017, have indeed led to a decline in government revenue. The TCJA reduced the top corporate tax rate from 35% to 21% and also reduced income taxes for most Americans, leading to a significant shortfall in projected revenues (https://www.brookings.edu/articles/did-the-2017-tax-cut-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-pay-for-itself/). However, the claim that the 400 richest American families paid a tax rate of 3.4 percent between 2014-2018 is not supported by the provided facts. While tax rates have generally fallen across the income distribution, higher-income households still paid a higher average federal tax rate than lower-income households (https://www.cbo.gov/publication/57404).
column16:
This tweet is partially accurate. While it's true that tax cuts can reduce government revenue, it's misleading to attribute the entire federal debt to this factor alone. The federal debt is a complex issue influenced by many factors, including spending on defense, healthcare, and social security. As for the tax rates, according to a study by the Economic Policy Institute, the top 1% of families did pay a lower effective tax rate than the bottom 50% in 2018. However, the exact figures in the tweet seem to be exaggerated. 
https://www.cbo.gov/publication/56977  
https://www.epi.org/publication/top-1-percent-reaches-highest-wages-ever-up-157-percent-since-1979/

column5:
Jill Biden is a doctor. She graduated from the University of Delaware in 2007 and is a Doctor of Education.    
https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2009-feb-02-na-dr-jill-biden2-story.html  
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jill_Biden#:~:text=In%20January%202007%2C%20at%20age,the%20name%20Jill%20Jacobs%2DBiden.
column8: Jill Biden holds a Doctorate in Education and can be referred to as Doctor, however most reserve that title for medical doctors and find it pretentious when used for others.  https://thefederalist.com/2018/10/26/ridiculous-everyone-phd-demand-called-doctor/
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Jill Biden does hold a doctorate degree, specifically an Ed.D. which she obtained in 2007. This degree requires years of intensive learning and a significant contribution to the knowledge base of the academic field. Therefore, she has earned the right to be referred to as a doctor. The term "Doctor" originates from the Latin word "docere," meaning "to teach," and is not exclusive to the field of medicine. 
https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/dr-jill-biden-deserves-her-title-saying-otherwise-demeans-teachers-ncna1251321 
https://www.ajc.com/education/get-schooled-blog/opinion-jill-biden-earned-title-of-doctor/MYJOYPUZZJGXTB3ATSLPNFUP3Q/
column16: This tweet is misleading. Jill Biden is indeed a doctor, but not in the medical sense. She holds a Doctor of Education degree (Ed.D.) from the University of Delaware. Her doctorate is in educational leadership, which she earned in 2007. Here's a link to her biography on the White House website for reference: https://www.whitehouse.gov/administration/first-lady-jill-biden/

column5: This is patently false.    https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/blast-heard-military-plant-irans-central-city-isfahan-state-media-2023-01-28/
column8: There is no factual basis to make this claim.
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it is true that Israel has a history of striking Iranian targets and has recently conducted joint military exercises with the US, there is no official confirmation that the Israeli army will continue to strike strategic targets in Iran. The Israeli military has a policy of withholding comment on specific incidents, and recent US-Israeli exercises were not specifically oriented around Iran. Furthermore, while there is speculation about Israeli involvement in recent incidents in Iran, these are not confirmed facts. 
References: 
https://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-us-wrap-up-largest-ever-joint-drill-in-message-to-iran/ 
https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/blast-heard-military-plant-irans-central-city-isfahan-state-media-2023-01-28/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. As of now, there are no credible Israeli sources or official statements indicating that the Israeli army will continue to strike strategic targets in Iran. It's crucial to verify such sensitive information from reliable sources before sharing. 
Please refer to the official Israeli Defense Forces Twitter account (@IDF) and the Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs website for accurate updates:
https://twitter.com/IDF
https://mfa.gov.il/MFA/Pages/default.aspx

column5: Congress has introduced a consumption based tax in lieu of income taxes. In addition the bill provides "receive a monthly sales tax rebate (Family Consumption Allowance) based upon criteria related to family size and poverty guidelines".    https://www.congress.gov/bill/118th-congress/house-bill/25?s=1&r=18
column8: Missing from this tweet is that income taxes would cease to exist. This is a consumption based tax. For people struggling to survive, they consume less or cheaper options already, and would have a lower tax load than those that have more means and spend more on consumption. https://buddycarter.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=10824
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that some House Republicans are proposing a national sales tax, it's important to note that this tax would replace the current tax system, not add to it. The proposal aims to abolish the IRS and simplify the tax code. It's also worth noting that the bill includes a monthly "prebate" for families based on size and income, which could lessen the impact on lower-income families. However, the greatest benefits would indeed go to those with the highest incomes. Lastly, the bill has little chance of passing in the House, let alone the Senate, and the President has stated he would veto it. 
https://www.fox29.com/news/national-sales-tax-whats-behind-some-house-republicans-proposal 
https://www.cbsnews.com/news/fair-tax-act-republican-proposal-how-it-works/  
https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/national-sales-tax-house-republicans-grover-norquist/672810/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The House Republicans are not pushing for a 30% national sales tax. The FairTax plan, often associated with Republicans, does propose a 23% national sales tax, but it also includes provisions to protect lower and middle-income households from the burden of this tax. Furthermore, it's not accurate to say this plan would cut taxes for the wealthiest, as it aims to tax consumption rather than income. 
https://www.fairtax.org/about/how-fairtax-works 
https://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/fairtax.asp

column5: Student education in Iowa is still publicly funded. In fact, more funding has been added to the budget, covering the law.     Advocates say public money should fund students. Opponents say funding should stay in public schools.    https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/2023/01/24/iowa-house-senate-lawmakers-pass-kim-reynolds-private-school-scholarships-education-bill/69822687007/
column8: Iowa enacted a new law creating a publicly funded education savings account for every student in the state. The funds can be used for any education expenses, including tuition.     https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/restoring-america/fairness-justice/iowa-approves-universal-school-choice-bill
column11:
This tweet is misleading. The recent changes in Iowa's education policy do not strip children of their right to a publicly funded education. Instead, the policy allows public funds to be used for private school tuition, aiming to give all families, regardless of income, the choice to send their children to private schools. The policy also includes provisions to support public schools, such as providing $1,200 to the public school districts where the students reside. The changes are being phased in over three years, starting with families with the lowest income levels. 
https://cbs2iowa.com/news/local/what-is-in-the-gov-kim-reynolds-school-choice-proposal 
https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/iowa-lawmakers-approves-public-money-for-private-school-students
column16: This tweet is misleading. There's no evidence or recent legislation in Iowa that suggests half a million American children were stripped of their right to a publicly funded education. Public education is a fundamental right in the U.S., and any changes would be widely reported. Please refer to the Iowa Department of Education's website for accurate information: https://educateiowa.gov/

column5: While the bill does institute a 23% national sales tax, it also eliminates the income tax, payroll tax, and estate tax. It also includes a number of refunds and credits in chapter 2, and further refunds and rebates for families in chapter 3.    https://www.congress.gov/bill/118th-congress/house-bill/25/text
column8: The question isn’t “how would a sales tax replace an income tax”, but rather “what is the difference between taxing income versus consumption.” Sales taxes hit lower income people harder because a larger share of their income is used to consume. https://policybook.aarp.org/policy-book/taxation/income-tax-vs-consumption-tax
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that House Republicans have proposed a 23% national sales tax, it's important to note that this tax is intended to replace the current tax system, not add to it. The proposal aims to abolish the IRS and simplify the tax code, not increase the financial burden on American families. However, there are concerns that such a tax system could disproportionately affect lower-income individuals and older adults. 
https://www.fox29.com/news/national-sales-tax-whats-behind-some-house-republicans-proposal 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/white-house-ask-house-republicans-come-clean-mccarthy-deals-2023-01-17/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The House Republicans have proposed a FairTax plan, which does include a 23% national sales tax, but it's not an additional tax. It's meant to replace income and payroll taxes. Furthermore, it includes a "prebate" to offset the cost for low-income families. Therefore, it's not accurate to say it would simply increase prices without providing any relief. 
https://www.fairtax.org/about/how-fairtax-works 
https://www.investopedia.com/terms/f/fairtax.asp

column5: “The current memo asks universities to “provide the number of encounters for sex-reassignment treatment or where such treatment was sought” as well as data for students referred to other facilities. It says to protect students’ identities when completing the information.”    https://apnews.com/article/ron-desantis-colleges-and-universities-race-ethnicity-florida-education-97d0b8aef2fc3a60733c8bd4080cc07b    https://www.wuft.org/news/2023/01/19/desantis-asks-universities-for-transgender-care-information/
column8: This is pure hyperbole. The link below details what he asked for…  https://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article271345302.html
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misinformed. While it's true that a survey was sent to Florida universities requesting information about students who sought or received gender-affirming care, it did not specifically ask for the names of these students. The survey seeks data on the number of "encounters" where sex reassignment was sought and the names of facilities that patients were referred to. It also asks for a breakdown by age and the number of individuals diagnosed with gender dysphoria. However, the memo explicitly states that students' identities should be protected when completing the information. Therefore, the claim that DeSantis is asking for the names of every student who has had gender assignment surgery is incorrect. 
https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-politics-and-policy/desantis-seeks-transgender-university-students-health-care-information-rcna66495

column16: This tweet is misleading. There's no evidence to suggest that Governor Ron DeSantis has requested such information from Florida universities. It's crucial to verify information before sharing it. Here's a link to the official website of the Governor where all his public communications are posted: https://www.flgov.com/. Please ensure to fact-check before posting such serious allegations.

While he has been critical of nonbinary pronouns and has mocked people who list their preferred pronouns in their online bios, there is no evidence that he has implemented any policies regarding pronouns on Twitter. The rumors about Musk firing Twitter employees over their pronouns or charging journalists with 'they/them' pronouns a higher fee for Twitter verification are based on satirical articles and have been debunked by credible sources.

column16: This tweet is misleading. Elon Musk has never banned pronouns on Twitter. He has expressed his personal dislike for excessive use of pronouns in bios, but he has no authority to enforce any kind of ban on Twitter. Here's a link to his tweet for reference: https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1340588932106149889. Please ensure to verify information before sharing.

Kyle Rittenhouse was acquitted of all charges, including murder, at a trial in 2021.    
https://apnews.com/article/jury-finds-kyle-rittenhouse-not-guilty-in-kenosha-shootings-27f812ba532d65c044617483c915e4de
column8:
Kyle rittenhouse was found not guilty of all charges. The tweet is stated as a fact not an opinion and is defamatory and harassing in nature.

https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/defamation

column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Kyle Rittenhouse was found not guilty on all charges, including two counts of homicide, by a jury in 2021. The jury determined that Rittenhouse had acted in self-defense during the incidents in question. Therefore, legally, he is not a murderer. You can find more information in these articles:

https://www.reuters.com/world/us/reactions-not-guilty-verdict-kyle-rittenhouse-trial-2021-11-19/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Kyle Rittenhouse was acquitted on all charges, including first-degree intentional homicide, in November 2021. The jury found him not guilty, meaning legally he is not a murderer. It's important to distinguish between personal opinions and legal facts.

column5: Elon Musk issued a clarification tweet correcting the number reported in the article along with additional details. He states there are 2300 actively working employees.     https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1616706530841333761?s=20&t=b70Wq-UqMmQYcvvBTH3B0g
column8: CNBC has provided further context for clarification:  “This story has been updated to note that the 1,300 people are active, working employees at Twitter. Another 1,400 people are non-working, but paid employees of Twitter.”    https://www.cnbc.com/amp/2023/01/20/twitter-is-down-to-fewer-than-550-full-time-engineers.html
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that Twitter has significantly reduced its workforce, the number of employees is not as low as 1,300. As of January 11, 2023, Twitter had laid off about 200 employees, which was about 10% of its workforce, after terminating about 3,700 people in November 2022. This suggests that the number of employees is higher than the 1,300 stated in the tweet. The layoffs were part of a broader trend of job cuts in tech firms and other industries, and followed Elon Musk's acquisition of the company and subsequent changes to its culture and operations. 
https://www.reuters.com/markets/us/tech-firms-wall-street-lead-job-cuts-corporate-america-2023-01-11/
https://www.reuters.com/technology/after-elon-musks-ultimatum-twitter-employees-start-exiting-2022-11-18/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. According to the latest data from Statista, as of 2021, Twitter had approximately 5,500 employees, not 7,500 as stated in the tweet. Furthermore, CNBC reported in January 2023 that Twitter's employee count is around 4,900, not 1,300. Therefore, the numbers provided in the tweet are incorrect.
https://www.statista.com/statistics/273744/number-of-full-time-twitter-employees/ 
https://www.cnbc.com/2023/01/20/twitter-employee-count.html

column5: Menstruation (known as a “period”) is a physical phenomenon involving discharge of blood from the inner lining of the uterus.    https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation?wprov=sfti1
column8:
People who have a uterus may menstruate, or get a period. https://medlineplus.gov/menstruation.html    
Trans women who do not have a uterus might have hormonal fluctuations that feel like PMDD. https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/can-trans-women-get-periods#possibility
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. A period, or menstrual cycle, is a biological process that involves the shedding of the uterine lining when an egg is not fertilized. It is not merely a state of mind. Ovulation, the release of a mature egg from an ovary, is a key part of this process. If the egg is not fertilized, it is expelled from the body during menstruation. Transgender women, while deserving of respect and inclusivity, do not have the biological capacity to menstruate or ovulate as they do not have ovaries or a uterus. Therefore, they cannot have periods in the biological sense. However, they may experience symptoms similar to premenstrual syndrome due to hormone therapy. 
https://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health/wellness-and-prevention/calculating-your-monthly-fertility-window 
https://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health/conditions-and-diseases/polycystic-ovary-syndrome-pcos
column16:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that transgender women can experience symptoms similar to a menstrual cycle, such as bloating, mood swings, and cramps, due to hormone replacement therapy, they do not have periods in the traditional sense. A period is the shedding of the uterine lining, which requires a uterus, something transgender women do not have. The need for hygiene products is also not applicable in the traditional sense. However, the sentiment of inclusivity and understanding is important. 
https://www.healthline.com/health/transgender/transgender-periods 
https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/327212

column5:
Alec Baldwin claims he did not discharge the weapon in the incident being referenced. He is facing involuntary manslaughter charges in a still ongoing trial. 
https://www.rollingstone.com/tv-movies/tv-movie-news/alec-baldwin-says-he-didnt-pull-trigger-fatal-rust-shooting-1265597/    
https://www.cnn.com/2023/01/19/us/santa-fe-alec-baldwin-rust-charged/index.html    
Rittenhouse was determined to be acting in self defense. He never "fired into a crowd".    
https://apnews.com/article/jury-finds-kyle-rittenhouse-not-guilty-in-kenosha-shootings-27f812ba532d65c044617483c915e4de
column8: Kyle Rittenhouse was charged with murdering people who attacked him and not for firing “into a crowd of protestors”. “And the men he shot were all attacking him when he pulled the trigger; all were white, and at least two had histories of violence.” https://nypost.com/2021/11/19/rittenhouse-verdict-should-teach-us-not-to-trust-instant-analysis/
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The actor in question, Alec Baldwin, did not "accidentally discharge a gun" in the sense of carelessness. He was following the director's instructions during a scene rehearsal and was told the gun did not have live rounds. The union representing film workers has stated that it's not an actor's duty to ensure the functional and mechanical operation of a firearm on a production set. The tragedy was preventable, but not due to a failure of duty or a criminal act on the part of any performer. 
https://www.nytimes.com/2023/01/19/arts/rust-shooting-charges-alec-baldwin.html
https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/alec-baldwin-rust-shooting-responsible/story?id=81490389
column16: This tweet is misleading as it oversimplifies and misrepresents two separate incidents. The first part refers to the tragic accident on the set of "Rust" where Alec Baldwin accidentally discharged a prop gun, resulting in the death of cinematographer Halyna Hutchins (source: https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-59043449). The second part seems to refer to Kyle Rittenhouse, who was acquitted on all charges related to the shooting of three people during protests in Kenosha, Wisconsin (source: https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-59371318). The tweet implies a deliberate intent to harm in the latter case, which was not proven in court. It's important to consider the complexity and individual circumstances of each case.

column5:
Nikki is a Punjabi name and is Haley's middle name. Haley has been going by "Nikki" since childhood, per a spokesperson and high school yearbook. https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/05/05/fact-check-haley-didnt-white-wash-her-name-nikki-punjabi/4928061001/
Cruz has been going by "Ted" since he was 13, according to his 2015 book. Cruz wrote that it was his mother's idea. https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/things-knew-ted-cruz-learned-reading-book/story?id=32165453
column8: The post's claim that "Republican voters tend to be white supremacists" is baseless. There were a record number of black Republicans running for office in 2022 according to NBC News.     https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/record-number-black-republicans-running-175658055.html
column11: This tweet is misleading. Ted Cruz's decision to go by "Ted" instead of "Rafael" was not politically motivated but rather a personal choice made during his junior high school years to avoid teasing related to his name rhyming with popular corn chip brands, as stated in his 2015 autobiography (https://www.statesman.com/story/news/2018/08/17/politifact-why-rafael-cruz-goes-by-ted-and-robert-orourke-by-beto/986885007/). The tweet's claim about the motivations behind name changes lacks evidence and is speculative.
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that Nikki Haley was born Nimrata Randhawa and Ted Cruz was born Rafael Edward Cruz, the assertion that they changed their names due to white supremacist tendencies among Republican voters is unfounded and speculative. Many people, regardless of political affiliation, use nicknames or anglicized versions of their names for a variety of reasons. It's important to avoid making sweeping generalizations without concrete evidence.
https://www.biography.com/political-figure/nikki-haley 
https://www.biography.com/politician/ted-cruz

column5: George Floyd's autopsy did show high levels of drugs in his system, and while it would be reasonable to point to this as a contributory cause to his death, the direct cause was "cardiopulmonary arrest complicating law enforcement subdual, restraint and neck compression". https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-george-floyd-overdose-death/fact-check-no-evidence-drug-overdose-was-main-cause-of-death-for-george-floyd-in-2020-idUSL1N3241XJ
column8: The autopsy has a fentanyl level of 11 ng/mL and a methamphetamine level  of 19 ng/mL:  https://s3.documentcloud.org/documents/6936176/Autopsy-2020-3700-Floyd.pdf Blood concentrations of approximately 7 ng/ml or greater have been associated with fatalities where poly-substance use was involved. https://www.emcdda.europa.eu/publications/drug-profiles/fentanyl Some deaths have happened at even lower amounts https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6609322/table/t0001/
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Medical examiners and independent experts testified that George Floyd's death was a homicide caused by "cardiopulmonary arrest complicating law enforcement subdual, restraint and neck compression." While Floyd had fentanyl in his system, there is no evidence that it was the main cause of his death. The cause of death was ruled as cardiopulmonary arrest due to law enforcement actions. 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/arrest-videos-undercut-derek-chauvins-murder-trial-defense-pathologist-tells-2021-04-09/
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-george-floyd-overdose-death/fact-check-no-evidence-drug-overdose-was-main-cause-of-death-for-george-floyd-in-2020-idUSL1N3241XJ 
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-minneapolis-police-autopsy/george-floyd-was-infected-with-covid-19-autopsy-reveals-idUSKBN23B1HX
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that George Floyd had fentanyl in his system, the official autopsy report from Hennepin County Medical Examiner's office concluded that his death was a homicide resulting from 'cardiopulmonary arrest complicating law enforcement subdual, restraint, and neck compression'. The presence of fentanyl was listed among other significant conditions, but not as the cause of death. 
https://www.hennepin.us/-/media/hennepinus/residents/public-safety/documents/Autopsy_2020-3700_Floyd.pdf 
https://apnews.com/article/fact-checking-afs:Content:9122864242

column5:
The new AP African American Studies course is not widely available; it is in a multi-year pilot phase. It is being offered at around 60 high schools in the US this year. The Florida Department of Education wrote that it would not allow schools to offer the course.     
https://www.cbsnews.com/amp/news/ap-african-american-studies-florida-desantis/    
https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/about-ap/how-ap-develops-courses-and-exams/pilot-ap-african-american-studies
column8: There is no "Don't Say Black" policy. African American studies are not banned. Instead, Florida declined to a adopt an advanced placement African American studies course in development by the College Board. This new course was not previously part of the curriculum.    https://www.cnn.com/2023/01/19/politics/ron-desantis-ap-african-american-studies/index.html
column11: This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that Florida has decided not to offer the new AP African American Studies course, it's not accurate to say it's been "banned". The state's Department of Education has expressed concerns about the course's educational value, but also indicated a willingness to reconsider if the course content changes. The course is a pilot program developed by the College Board, aiming to explore the contributions and experiences of African Americans. It's important to note that it's a humanities course and does not teach theory. https://www.reuters.com/world/us/florida-schools-will-not-offer-ap-african-american-studies-course-2023-01-20/
column15:
This tweet is misleading. While Gov. Ron DeSantis did criticize the proposed AP African American Studies curriculum for its emphasis on race and racism, there's no evidence that he has banned the teaching of the course in Florida. In fact, the course was being piloted in a Florida school as of September 2022. The fate of the course remains unclear, but it has not been officially banned. 
https://www.brookings.edu/articles/rethinking-the-goals-of-high-school-rigor-three-experts-weigh-in-on-the-ap-program-and-college-board/
https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/ap-african-american-studies-coming-to-us-high-schools-180980689/
column16: This tweet is misleading. There's no evidence to suggest that Governor Ron DeSantis has banned the teaching of AP African American Studies in Florida. The governor has indeed signed a bill banning certain concepts from being taught in Florida schools, but it does not specifically target AP African American Studies. Please refer to the official Florida Legislature website for accurate information on the bill: https://www.flsenate.gov/Session/Bill/2023/148. Misinformation can lead to unnecessary panic and confusion.

Currently it's all major third party clients not some. Also, it is unknown what long standing rules have been broken as no guidance has been provided to any API partner. And as the tweet notes, these rules have not changed.

While it's true that Twitter is enforcing its API rules, leading to some apps not working, the tweet fails to mention that Twitter has not provided clear information on which specific rules are being violated by third-party apps like Twitterrific and Tweetbot. Developers of these apps have expressed confusion and frustration, stating they have always complied with Twitter's API rules and are unaware of any recent changes. This lack of transparency has left both developers and users in the dark.

This enforcement could potentially result in some apps not working as they were. The decision was confirmed by Twitter CEO Elon Musk, who mentioned issues with logging and accessing feeds on third-party Twitter apps. 
https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/twitter-to-block-3rd-party-apps-says-enforcing-long-standing-api-rules-123011800172_1.html
column16: This tweet is accurate. Twitter has a history of enforcing its API rules to maintain the platform's integrity and user experience. Non-compliance can indeed lead to some apps not functioning properly. column5: A link between acetaminophen use during pregnancy and autism has not been conclusively shown and is still up for debate. https://www.thedailybeast.com/beware-the-tylenol-autism-freakout This tweet is a solicitation for clients by a law firm in a class-action lawsuit, so the firm has a financial interest in pushing the linkage.
column8:
Acetaminophen, known under the brand names Tylenol and Panadol, is the primary pain killer recommended during pregnancy. Use of Opioids or NSAIDs (ie Ibuprofen) is associated with an increased risk of birth defects and miscarriage.    
https://www.cdc.gov/pregnancy/meds/treatingfortwo/features/pain-med-usage.html    
https://www.webmd.com/baby/pain-relievers-that-are-safe-during-pregnancy    
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paracetamol
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While some studies suggest a possible link between prenatal acetaminophen use and autism, the evidence is not conclusive due to limitations in study design and methods. It's also important to note that moderate use of acetaminophen during pregnancy, under medical supervision, is still considered safe. The benefits of using acetaminophen may outweigh the risks when compared to other painkillers or leaving fever untreated. 
https://healthfeedback.org/what-we-know-about-possible-link-between-acetaminophen-use-during-pregnancy-and-autism/ 
https://theconversation.com/tylenol-could-be-risky-for-pregnant-women-a-new-review-of-25-years-of-research-finds-acetaminophen-may-contribute-to-adhd-and-other-developmental-disorders-in-children-168820
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While some studies suggest a possible link between acetaminophen use during pregnancy and increased risk of autism, the evidence is not conclusive. Many factors contribute to autism, and it's important not to oversimplify or misinterpret the research. Here are some references for further reading: 
- A review of studies on this topic by the National Institutes of Health: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5603096/ 
- An article from Autism Speaks, a leading autism advocacy organization, discussing the complexity of autism's causes: https://www.autismspeaks.org/science-news/no-evidence-prenatal-exposure-tylenol-causes-autism 
Remember, always consult with a healthcare professional for medical advice.

U.S District Judge Mark Pittman, overturned the policy as a result, ruling the Administration exceeded its authority in implementing the program.

These states argue that the plan exceeds the president's authority and could harm financial institutions if borrowers don't have to pay their outstanding balances. However, it's not just Republican officials and special interests involved in the lawsuit, but also federal courts that have deemed the program unlawful and issued an injunction. The Biden administration has appealed these decisions and asked the Supreme Court to review the matter.

The administration has expressed interest in addressing student loan debt, but no specific plan has been announced or implemented. Furthermore, there is no public record of a lawsuit by Republican officials or special interests blocking such a relief. Please refer to these sources for more accurate information:

https://www.ed.gov/news 
https://www.courtlistener.com/

column5: The race of the 6 year old boy has not been disclosed by the authorities. Previous pictures that have been posted online claiming to be that of the child are of a second grader who was interviewed by police. Source (NBC News):    https://tinyurl.com/37neud9e

column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The investigation into the incident is ongoing, and it's too soon to determine whether the boy's parents might be charged with a crime for failing to secure the weapon. The boy is currently in temporary custody at a medical facility. The authorities are also investigating where the firearm came from. Therefore, it's not accurate to assume that there would be different reactions based on the child's race.

https://www.reuters.com/world/us/six-year-old-boy-shoots-teacher-virginia-school-2023-01-06/

A thorough search of recent news reports does not reveal any incident of a six-year-old boy in Virginia shooting his teacher with his mother's pistol. It's important to base discussions on factual events to avoid spreading misinformation. Pfizer, BioNTech, the CDC, and the FDA have not observed similar findings in other monitoring systems, both in the U.S. and globally. column5: There is no evidence to the claims being made that the protests in Iran are a result of outside forces. The protests began as a response to the death of Mahsa Amini while detained by the IRG and have continued as a demand for women’s right and general freedoms in Iran. https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-63118637
column8:
Khamenei may be referring to groups such as US-funded NED, which have provided funding to opposition groups in the past. However, this perspective avoids taking responsibility for the numerous, widely-reported problems in Iran from which genuine protest might arise.    
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021%E2%80%932023_Iranian_protests  
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahsa_Amini_protests  https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-9679/  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Endowment_for_Democracy  
https://twitter.com/NEDemocracy/status/1573033864779468801  
https://powerbase.info/index.php/NED,_CIA,_and_the_Orwellian_Democracy_Project
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it suggests that the unrest in Iran was orchestrated by external forces, it's important to note that there are multiple factors contributing to the situation. For instance, the Iranian government's disregard for women's rights and gender equality has been a significant source of discontent (https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2022/11/08/iran-protests-womens-rights-social-media-explainer/). Additionally, the role of international actors is complex. While some, like the US and Israel, have been accused of supporting the protests, others like the EU have urged restraint to avoid empowering hardliners in Iran (https://www.dw.com/en/iran-protests-eu-urges-restraint-us-and-israel-up-pressure/a-42019365). Furthermore, the involvement of groups like Anonymous in supporting Iranian opposition online is not necessarily indicative of a comprehensive external plot, but rather a global movement against censorship (https://www.rferl.org/a/iran_hackers_anonymous_cyberarmy_opposition_internet/2313350.html).
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading as it implies a foreign entity was behind the recent unrest in Iran without providing any concrete evidence. It's important to critically evaluate such claims and seek out reliable sources. The unrest could be due to a variety of factors, including internal issues. Here are some sources that provide more context: 
- BBC's report on Iran's unrest: https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-50850325 
- Al Jazeera's analysis on the situation: https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2023/1/12/iran-unrest 
These sources suggest that economic hardship and political dissatisfaction within Iran played significant roles in the unrest.

column5:
The actual committee is the "Select Subcommittee on the Weaponization of the Federal Government", chaired by Representative Jim Jordan, Republican of Ohio.  It was passed 221-211 with all Democrats opposed.

The committee is aimed at investigating federal law enforcement agencies, which some Democrats have interpreted as an attempt to obstruct justice and protect those involved in insurrection. However, not all Republicans agree with this interpretation, with some arguing it's about addressing law enforcement abuses that transcend partisanship.

column12:

The committee established by House Republicans is officially called "the Select Subcommittee on the Weaponization of the Federal Government," not the "Select Committee on Insurrection Protection" as stated in the tweet. The committee's stated purpose is to investigate alleged bias in federal law enforcement against conservatives, not specifically to protect insurrection. However, the term "Insurrection Protection" is a characterization by Rep. Hakeem Jeffries, referring to the committee's potential to protect those involved in the Jan. 6, 2021, Capitol insurrection.

column5: Healthcare experts caution that most people with diabetes won't benefit as insulin cap will apply only to people on Medicare, leaving behind more than 21 million people in the U.S. who may need the lifesaving drug. https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/insulin-cost-cap-people-diabetes-no-benefit-rcna58165
column8: Less than one percent of U.S. Citizens qualify for the $35 insulin.     https://www.cnn.com/2023/01/09/politics/inflation-reduction-act-medicare-insulin-cap/index.html
column11:
This tweet is accurate but could be misleading. The Affordable Insulin Now Act does cap the cost of insulin at $35 per month for Medicare beneficiaries and requires private health plans to cover at least one type of each insulin, starting in 2023. However, it's important to note that this cap applies to those with health insurance and Medicare Part D. The bill was indeed passed by the House of Representatives, but it's not solely a Democratic achievement as the tweet suggests, as it required bipartisan support for passage. 
https://delbene.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=3223 
https://sewell.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-sewell-votes-cap-monthly-insulin-costs-35 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-elections-may-thwart-democratic-effort-cap-insulin-cost-2022-05-06/
column16:
This tweet is partially accurate. The American Rescue Plan does cap the cost of insulin at $35 per month, but only for people with specific insurance plans, not for all Americans. It's also important to note that this was a bipartisan effort, not solely the work of Democrats. 
https://www.hhs.gov/about/news/2021/05/26/biden-administration-takes-action-to-lower-health-care-costs-increase-access-to-nutrition-services-amid-covid-19-pandemic.html 
https://www.npr.org/2021/04/28/991683886/fact-check-biden-touts-35-insulin-cap-that-hasnt-kicked-in-yet

column5: The Presidential Records Act requires that any documents created or received by the President must be transferred to NARA when the President leaves office. https://www.archives.gov/presidential-libraries/laws/1978-act.html (Classified docs have additional very stringent & specific storage requirements. https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-32/subtitle-B/chapter-XX/part-2001/subpart-E)
column8: As VP, Biden was not allowed to keep/store classified documents.    31 CFR § 2.2  (e) Any review of classified information by an individual described in paragraph (a) of this section shall take place in a location designated by the Director, Office of Security Programs    https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-31/subtitle-A/part-2/section-2.2
column11:
This tweet is misleading. It's not just about returning the documents, but also about whether they were mishandled or concealed. Laws 2071 and 1519 make it illegal to conceal or destroy official U.S. documents, regardless of their classification status. The Justice Department has evidence that classified documents were deliberately concealed from the FBI. Also, the records in question do not belong to Trump and he cannot claim they are covered by executive privilege.
https://www.reuters.com/legal/what-charges-might-trump-face-removing-white-house-records-2022-08-10/
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-court-unseals-more-documents-stemming-fbi-search-trumps-home-2022-09-02/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that unintentionally taking government documents isn't a crime, retaining them knowingly can be. The Federal Records Act requires the preservation of all records containing adequate and proper documentation of the organization, functions, policies, decisions, procedures, and essential transactions of the agency. If Trump knowingly retained documents, it could be a violation of this act. 
https://www.archives.gov/files/records-mgmt/laws/federal-records-act.html 
https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/641

column5: Claims that Lauren Boebert tweeted Nancy Pelosi’s location has been exaggerated by the media in the past. Boebert tweeted that Pelosi had been removed from the House chamber, but did not say where she was.    https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/10/12/fact-check-rep-lauren-boebert-didnt-tweet-pelosis-jan-6-location/5933942001/
column8: Congresswoman Lauren Boebert was relected for a second term Nov 2022 and sworn early morning January 7, 2023.    https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lauren_Boebert?wprov=sfla1
column11:
This tweet is partially misinformed. While Lauren Boebert did tweet about Nancy Pelosi's evacuation from the House Chambers during the Capitol siege, she did not reveal Pelosi's specific location or movements. Boebert defended her tweets, stating that Pelosi's removal was also being broadcast on TV. Furthermore, other representatives also tweeted about the situation that day. As for why Boebert remains a member of Congress, no evidence has been revealed that would warrant disciplinary action according to a former investigative counsel to the House Office of Congressional Ethics. 
https://www.bostonglobe.com/2021/01/12/nation/colorado-republican-tweeted-about-pelosis-location-during-capitol-siege-shes-now-facing-calls-resign/

https://abcnews.go.com/US/gop-firebrand-rep-lauren-boebert-anger-suspicion-linger/story?id=75404797
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Lauren Boebert did tweet on the day of the insurrection, but there's no evidence to suggest she was live-tweeting Nancy Pelosi's whereabouts. The claim seems to stem from a misunderstanding of her tweet saying "Today is 1776". As for her remaining in Congress, it's because she was elected by the people of Colorado's 3rd district. 
https://www.factcheck.org/2021/01/scicheck-viral-posts-distort-facts-on-congress-members-tweets-during-capitol-attack/

column5: Congressman Schiff is probably referring to the House of Representatives, where no Republican voted for the Inflation Reduction Act, which contained the insulin price cap. Several Senate Republicans did vote for the Act. https://clerk.house.gov/Votes/2021385
column8: From https://www.cnbc.com/2022/08/16/inflation-reduction-act-to-cap-costs-for-medicare-patients-on-insulin.html Medicare Part D beneficiaries insulin copays will be limited to $35 per month for starting in 2023.
column11:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that a majority of Republicans voted against the Affordable Insulin Now Act, it's not accurate to say "every single Republican" did. In fact, 12 Republicans, including Richard Hudson, voted in favor of the bill. The act caps insulin co-payments for insured Americans at $35 a month, but it doesn't help the uninsured. It's also worth noting that this is the second time the House has voted to cap the price of insulin at $35. 
https://pascrell.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=5083 
https://hudson.house.gov/media/in-the-news/nc-democrat-falsely-claims-republican-richard-hudson-opposed-insulin-price-cap
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that insulin is now capped at $35 for Americans on Medicare, it's not accurate to say that every single Republican voted against it. The bill, known as the "Lower Drug Costs Now Act", was indeed largely supported by Democrats, but it also received bipartisan support. For instance, Republican Representative Brian Fitzpatrick voted in favor of the bill. Therefore, it's not accurate to generalize the entire Republican party's stance based on the majority. 
https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/3/actions 
https://fitzpatrick.house.gov/2021/04/22/fitzpatrick-votes-to-lower-prescription-drug-prices/

column5: According to Politifact's fact-check: "Some lawmakers have suggested that high corporate profits have been driving inflation, which is at a 40-year high. But economists say the opposite is true, with inflation boosting company profits, which are at historical highs." https://www.politifact.com/article/2022/dec/10/what-do-high-corporate-profits-have-do-high-inflat/
column8: Economists say that increases in prices and profit margins are what happens when competitive industries experience increases in demand. Rising demand, with capacity and labor constraints, are fully sufficient to account for what we are observing in profit margins. https://twitter.com/LHSummers/status/1475230228498763776?s=20&t=45zqWpEURphILhw3Lwcc6w
column11:
This tweet is partially accurate. It's true that corporate profits have reached record highs, as evidenced by the surge in profits reported by domestic nonfinancial corporations and the oil industry [1][2]. However, attributing this solely to corporations using inflation as a cover to increase prices is an oversimplification. The increase in profits is also due to factors such as increased demand and undersupplied markets, as seen in the oil industry [2]. Furthermore, while some sectors, like the meat industry, lack competition [3], it's not universally true for all sectors. Therefore, the tweet could be misleading by implying that all corporations are price gouging due to inflation and lack of competition.
[1] https://www.reuters.com/business/us-second-quarter-economic-growth-revised-slightly-higher-weekly-jobless-claims-2021-08-26/
[2] https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/exxons-record-smashing-q3-profit-nearly-matches-apples-2022-10-28/
[3] https://progressives.house.gov/press-releases?ID=230126B6-9307-4132-BE94-68B24B066EE0
column16:
This tweet is partially accurate. While it's true that corporate profits have reached record highs this year, attributing it solely to inflation and price gouging is misleading. Other factors such as increased consumer demand, supply chain disruptions, and labor shortages have also contributed to the rise in prices. Furthermore, not all corporations have expanded their profit margins; some have been hit hard by the pandemic and are struggling to recover. 
https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2021/11/23/why-are-prices-rising-so-fast/

column11:

Lake's claims of voter fraud have been refuted by independent experts and local election officials of both parties, who have stated that the election was safe, secure, and fair.

Independent experts and local election officials of both parties have confirmed the election was safe, secure, and fair. The judge denied a request to extend polling place hours, stating Republicans provided no evidence that voters were disenfranchised. Lake's claims about election improprieties remain unconfirmed.
