column5: None of the current Supreme Court justices were appointed in the 1980’s. The oldest, Clarence Thomas, was appointed in 1991. https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States
column8: Constitution of the United States, which is the basis of US Supreme Court rulings, was written in 1787. Its most recently written amendment is from 1971. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constitution_of_the_United_States Currently the earliest appointment to Supreme Court is that of Clarence Thomas, in 1991. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States
column11:
This tweet is accurate in expressing a concern about the longevity of Supreme Court justices' terms and the potential for imbalance in the Court's representation. The U.S. is unique among modern constitutional democracies in allowing justices to serve for decades without term or age limits. This has led to some presidents appointing no justices and others appointing a significant portion of the Court. The Supreme Court TERM Act proposes 18-year term limits for justices, which would create a regular appointment process and ensure each president the opportunity to nominate two justices per four-year term. This could make the Court more representative of the nation and restore a constitutional balance to the three branches of the federal government. A majority of Americans are in favor of term limits. However, it's important to note that Khanna's bill would only apply to justices approved after its passage, and current justices would be exempt from the term limits. 
http://hankjohnson.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-johnson-introduces-supreme-court-justice-term-limit-measure-restore 
http://khanna.house.gov/media/press-releases/release-rep-ro-khanna-proposes-supreme-court-term-limits-appointments-schedule 
https://www.brookings.edu/articles/term-limits-a-way-to-tackle-the-supreme-courts-crisis-of-legitimacy/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. Supreme Court justices are appointed for life to ensure independence from political pressures. The idea of term limits has been discussed, but it's not a simple issue and would likely require a constitutional amendment. Also, the justices' decisions are based on their interpretation of the law, not their appointment date. 
https://www.uscourts.gov/faqs-filing-case#faq-Why-are-judges-appointed-for-life 
https://www.history.com/news/supreme-court-justices-term-limits-proposal 
https://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution-conan/article-3/section-1/judicial-tenure

column5: Forbes has verified that Trump donated at least 14/16 of his quarterly salaries, or about $1.4 million after tax, to different federal agencies.   https://www.forbes.com/sites/adamandrzejewski/2021/02/27/president-donald-trump-probably-donated-his-entire-16m-salary-back-to-the-us-government--here-are-the-details/amp/
column8: Media organizations at the time verified that former President Trump did in fact donate to federal agencies each quarter an amount representing his after-tax paycheck. https://www.wtol.com/article/news/local/verify-yes-trump-has-never-taken-a-presidential-paycheck/512-31053f37-6add-418b-86d9-043ce905185c
column11: This tweet is partially correct and partially misleading. It's true that Donald Trump charged the Secret Service to stay in his hotels, as confirmed by the House Oversight Committee (https://oversightdemocrats.house.gov/sites/democrats.oversight.house.gov/files/2022-10-17.CBM%20to%20Cheatle-USSS%20re%20Exorbitant%20Charges%20at%20Trump%20Properties.pdf). However, it's incorrect to say that Trump did not donate his yearly salary. He did donate his salary, but not to one specific cause or in one lump sum. Instead, he donated it in quarterly increments to various government initiatives (https://www.factcheck.org/2018/08/false-stories-revive-claim-about-trump-salary-donation/). The tweet does not provide sources for the claims about Trump's and his family's earnings, so these cannot be verified.
column16: This tweet is partially misinformed. Donald J. Trump did donate his yearly salary as president, as confirmed by multiple sources (https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-trump-donated-salary-idUSKBN22J2MJ). However, it's true that Trump's properties charged the Secret Service for accommodations (https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-properties-secret-service-spending/2021/01/22/3c9b874e-5c5f-11eb-a976-bad6431e03e2_story.html). The claim about Trump making $1.6 billion as President is misleading without context; this figure likely refers to revenue, not profit, of his businesses during his presidency (https://www.forbes.com/sites/danalexander/2021/01/20/donald-trump-has-not-given-up-his-billion-dollar-businesses/?sh=4e4b3c1b6a63). The claim about Jared and Ivanka making $2 billion is not substantiated by any reliable source.

column5:
Donald Trump did indeed donate all 4 years of his salary back to the US Government. The total of all 4 years is $1.6million. Donald Trump's Charitable contributions do appear on his taxes.  
https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/21/trump-income-tax-returns-detailed-in-new-report-.html 
https://www.forbes.com/sites/adamandrzejewski/2021/02/27/president-donald-trump-probably-donated-his-entire-16m-salary-back-to-the-us-government--here-are-the-details/?sh=74b99b561a8d
column8: A careful search https://www.google.com/search?q=trump+salary+donate&client=safari&sxsrf=ALiCzsbOcCEDklXBAtfND8KgZZdMsbIpKQ%3A1671829159654&source=hp&ei=pxamY7KyJZar0PEPu4WosAc&oq=trump+salary+donate&gs_lcp=ChFtb2JpbGUtZ3dzLXdpei1ocBADOgcIIxDqAhAnOgQIIxAnOhEILhCABBCxAxCDARDHARDRAzoLCC4QgAQQsQMQgwE6CwgAEIAEELEDEIMBOg4ILhCABBCxAxDHARDRAzoICC4QsQMQgwE6CAgAELEDEIMBOggIABCABBCxAzoFCAAQgAQ6CAguEIAEELEDOgsIABCABBCxAxDJAzoFCC4QgARQyxRY9Gtg2m5oAXAAeACAAXmIAcQOkgEEMTEuOJgBAKABAbABDw&sclient=mobile-gws-wiz-hp#ip=1 does not support this claim. The Committee report https://waysandmeans.house.gov/sites/democrats.waysandmeans.house.gov/files/documents/jctreport.pdf does not address the issue. The report mentions substantial charitable donations, but no detail; if money went to federal agencies, I suspect it wouldn’t be considered a charitable contribution.
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While President Trump's tax returns may not show specific donations, it has been confirmed that he has donated nearly his entire presidential salary to various federal government operations. These donations include contributions to the Department of Veterans Affairs and HHS for COVID-19 research. However, it's important to note that these donations were not directed to one specific cause or to repair military cemeteries. 
https://www.factcheck.org/2018/08/false-stories-revive-claim-about-trump-salary-donation/
https://waysandmeans.house.gov/faqs-on-claims-regarding-president-trumps-tax-returns/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While tax returns don't specifically itemize presidential salary donations, Trump's team provided proof of these donations each quarter. The White House often issued press releases detailing the recipient of the donation. Here are some examples: 
https://www.npr.org/2017/07/31/540579282/trump-donates-second-quarter-salary-to-education-department 
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-salary/trump-donates-quarterly-salary-to-help-fight-coronavirus-idUSKBN21P3HJ 
https://apnews.com/article/donald-trump-archive-betsy-devos-8e7403e97db848ed8a6a8d8f9b9d3616 
Remember, tax returns don't provide a complete picture of someone's charitable giving.

column5:
US assistance to Ukraine is 5.6% of the defense budget. There is no direct correlation between taxes deducted from paychecks and the defense budget. Payroll taxes fund Social Security, Medicare and unemployment. State income tax rates vary: some states have none.     
https://cepa.org/article/its-costing-peanuts-for-the-us-to-defeat-russia/  
https://www.adp.com/resources/tools/tax-guides-and-forms/state-and-local-tax-guides/state-tax-guide.aspx  
https://taxfoundation.org/state-income-tax-rates-2022/
column8: Personal income taxes account for about half of US Revenue which exceeds $2Trillion. Aid to Ukraine is at most $50B which is 5% of annual  Federal Income tax, not 20-40% as the tweet suggests. https://taxfoundation.org/us-tax-revenue-by-tax-type-2022/
column11:
This tweet is misleading. The U.S. aid to Ukraine is a fraction of the total U.S. federal budget. The total aid to Ukraine, if the new request of $37.7 billion is passed, would be $105.5 billion, while the total U.S. federal budget outlays are estimated to reach $5,872 billion in FY2023. This means that the aid to Ukraine represents less than 2% of the total U.S. federal budget. Furthermore, the U.S. economy was estimated to have reached $25.66 trillion in current dollars as of October 2022, making the aid to Ukraine a negligible part of the U.S. economy. Therefore, it's incorrect to claim that 20-40% of the taxes taken from your paycheck go to Ukraine. 
https://www.csis.org/analysis/aid-ukraine-explained-six-charts 
https://www.csis.org/analysis/united-states-aid-ukraine-investment-whose-benefits-greatly-exceed-its-cost
column16: This tweet is misleading. The U.S. foreign aid budget, which includes aid to Ukraine, is less than 1% of the total federal budget. Therefore, it's incorrect to suggest that 20-40% of your taxes are going to Ukraine. Here's a source that breaks down U.S. spending: https://www.nationalpriorities.org/budget-basics/federal-budget-101/spending/ And here's a source that specifically addresses aid to Ukraine: https://www.foreignassistance.gov/explore/country/Ukraine

column5: The $4.4 million for Lakewood Church where Osteen is pastor went to support the salary and benefits of approximately 350 employees. Neither Osteen nor his wife directly benefited. After criticism, the church is repaying the loan. https://nypost.com/2021/10/10/joel-osteens-lakewood-church-to-repay-4-4m-in-ppp-loans/
column8: Loans under the Paycheck Protection Program (PPP) were designed to be forgivable if recipients met certain requirements (including maintaining pre-loan employment numbers and spending proceeds on payroll). https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/covid-19-relief-options/paycheck-protection-program/ppp-loan-forgiveness
column11: This tweet is partially accurate. It's true that Marjorie Taylor Greene had $183,504 in PPP loans forgiven (https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/white-house-shines-light-republicans-are-criticizing-student-debt-canc-rcna44904). However, the claim about Joel Osteen is misleading. His church did receive a PPP loan, but it was fully repaid (https://www.nydailynews.com/2021/10/10/multimillionaire-joel-osteens-lakewood-church-returns-44-million-in-ppp-loans/). The tweet doesn't provide sources for the claims about Lauren Boebert and Tom Brady. It's important to note that PPP loans were intended to help businesses keep employees on payroll during the pandemic and could be forgiven if certain conditions were met (https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/white-house-shines-light-republicans-are-criticizing-student-debt-canc-rcna44904).
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that these individuals' businesses received PPP loans, it's important to note that these loans were designed to help businesses keep their workforce employed during the COVID-19 crisis. They are not personal loans and are forgivable if certain conditions are met. Comparing them to student loan forgiveness is not an apples-to-apples comparison. 
For more information on PPP loans: https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/covid-19-relief-options/paycheck-protection-program 
For more information on student loan forgiveness: https://studentaid.gov/manage-loans/forgiveness-cancellation

column5: Every President since Nixon, except for Donald Trump, made their taxes available to the public every year they were in office. Every one of these released their entire tax filing, except Gerald Ford, who released a summary. https://www.investopedia.com/history-of-presidents-and-federal-income-tax-what-s-normal-5080237
column8: Presidential Tax returns have been made public by the respective filers (President, VP etc) since at least Franklin Roosevelt. https://www.taxnotes.com/presidential-tax-returns
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Both President Obama and the Clintons have had their tax returns audited or made public. The I.R.S. subjected Obama to annual audits of his tax returns once he took office. The Clintons have released their tax returns going back to 2007, and tax returns are publicly available for the eight years Bill Clinton was in the White House. Prior years were released by his campaign. 
https://www.nytimes.com/2022/12/21/us/politics/trump-irs-taxes.html
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-clinton-taxes-idUKKCN10M1I7
column16: This tweet is misleading as it implies that the tax returns of Obama and the Clintons have not been previously disclosed. In fact, both Obama and the Clintons have publicly released their tax returns during their respective presidential campaigns. Obama's tax returns from 2000 to 2015 can be found here: https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2016/04/15/president-obama-and-vice-president-bidens-2015-tax-returns and the Clintons' tax returns from 2000 to 2015 can be found here: https://www.hillaryclinton.com/page/tax-returns/ Therefore, there is no need for Republicans to seek these tax returns as they are already publicly available.

column5:
The Metropolitan Correctional Center in New York, the facility referred to, was temporarily closed in 2021 and has yet to reopen. https://www.nytimes.com/2021/08/26/nyregion/MCC-epstein-jail-closed.html    
Per the Federal Bureau of Prisons, there are zero inmates housed at the facility at present. https://www.bop.gov/locations/institutions/nym/index.jsp
column8: There is no evidence this is true, currently new is reporting the possibility of him being housed in the same jail that Ghislaine Maxwell was in. https://news.yahoo.com/sam-bankman-fried-could-housed-215957875.html
column11:
This tweet is misleading. Sam Bankman-Fried is expected to be held at the Metropolitan Detention Center in Brooklyn or at jails outside New York City due to overcrowding, not the jail where Jeffrey Epstein died. This information is based on statements from defense lawyer Zachary Margulis-Ohnuma. 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/sam-bankman-fried-reverse-decision-contesting-extradition-source-2022-12-17/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. There's no credible source or news report indicating that Sam Bankman-Fried is facing any legal issues that would result in jail time. Sam Bankman-Fried is the CEO of FTX, a cryptocurrency exchange, and is a well-known figure in the crypto industry. Please ensure to verify information before sharing.
https://www.ftx.com/en/about 
https://www.forbes.com/profile/sam-bankman-fried/

column5: Matt Gaetz did not get a PPP loan personally, a company that he is a shareholder in did. https://www.statesman.com/story/news/politics/politifact/2022/09/06/fact-check-ppp-loans-forgiven-republicans-matt-gaetz-marjorie-taylor-greene/65470173007/
column8:
"Businesses associated with GOP politicians had pandemic government loans forgiven" Rep. Matt Gaetz (R-FL) was one of those politicians.    
PolitiFact's ruling: True    
Gaetz is a shareholder in Pensacola, Florida-based Caregivers Inc., which got $475,932.     
https://www.statesman.com/story/news/politics/politifact/2022/09/06/fact-check-ppp-loans-forgiven-republicans-matt-gaetz-marjorie-taylor-greene/65470173007/
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that a company in which Matt Gaetz holds stock, Caregivers Inc., received a PPP loan, it's not accurate to say that Gaetz himself had the loan forgiven. PPP loans are designed to be forgiven if used for eligible expenses like payroll, rent, and utilities. The loan was granted to the company, not Gaetz personally. 
https://www.citizensforethics.org/reports-investigations/crew-investigations/members-of-congress-ppp-transparency/
https://www.forbes.com/sites/michelatindera/2021/04/03/inside-the-30-million-gaetz-family-fortune/ 
https://waysandmeans.house.gov/fact-check-biden-draws-false-equivalence-between-ppp-loans-and-student-loan-giveaway/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Matt Gaetz, a U.S. Representative, did not personally receive PPP loans. The PPP loans mentioned were likely given to a company associated with his father, Don Gaetz. It's important to clarify that PPP loans are given to businesses, not individuals, and are meant to help with payroll costs during the COVID-19 pandemic. 
https://www.factcheck.org/2021/04/scicheck-gaetz-didnt-personally-receive-ppp-loan/ 
https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/covid-19-relief-options/paycheck-protection-program

column5: While there has been recent reporting covering Carvana’s debt and cash flow issues, the company has not yet declared bankruptcy.    Carvana has lost money in most quarters since going public in 2017 as it has aimed for sales growth rather than short-term profitability.    https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/08/business/carvana-bankruptcy-worries/index.html
column8: Caravana has not yet filed bankruptcy.     https://www.forbes.com/sites/qai/2022/12/08/is-carvana-going-to-declare-bankruptcy/
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While Carvana has faced financial challenges, including a higher-than-expected loss in Q3 2022 and concerns about debt management, it has also taken steps to address these issues. The company plans to significantly reduce its capital expenditure and has forecasted significant core earnings for 2023. It's also worth noting that bankruptcy doesn't necessarily mean cheaper used cars, as it depends on various factors including market demand and supply. 
https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/used-car-retailer-carvana-sees-significant-core-earnings-2023-2022-05-13/
https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/carvana-quarterly-loss-widens-demand-used-cars-shrinks-2022-11-03/
https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/used-car-retailer-carvana-slumps-after-wedbush-says-bankruptcy-risk-rising-2022-12-07/
column16: This tweet is potentially misleading. As of now, there's no credible information or news reports suggesting that Carvana is going bankrupt. Bankruptcy is a serious legal matter and should not be speculated without concrete evidence. Here's a recent report on Carvana's financial status: https://www.marketwatch.com/story/carvana-co-stock-rises-friday-still-underperforms-market-01639643407. Please ensure to verify information before sharing.

column5:
12-month inflation slowed from 7.7% in October to 7.1% in November, https://beta.bls.gov/dataViewer/view/timeseries/CUSR0000SA0    
To put this in perspective:  Jan 2021 was 1.4%  The maximum in 12 years of Obama & Trump was 3.8%; average was 1.6% Food is 11% higher than a year ago & 17% higher than two years ago, https://beta.bls.gov/dataViewer/view/timeseries/CUSR0000SAF1
column8: Food prices have increased an average of 11% in the last 12 months. Energy prices have increased almost 14% Everyone plays word games with inflation statistics.     https://www.bls.gov/charts/consumer-price-index/consumer-price-index-by-category.htm
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that month-to-month price increases have slowed, indicating that inflation may be reaching a peak, the overall inflation rate remains high. Food prices, for example, increased by 6.3% from December 2020 to December 2021, with grocery prices up in almost every category. This has been the highest price increase for consumer goods since 1982, causing concern among economists, policymakers, and the public. Therefore, it's not accurate to suggest that inflation has slowed to the point of providing relief for families at the grocery store. 
https://www.csis.org/analysis/high-prices-empty-shelves 
https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2022/06/15/in-the-u-s-and-around-the-world-inflation-is-high-and-getting-higher/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that inflation rates can fluctuate month-to-month, it's important to note that inflation is still significantly higher than it was a year ago. The Bureau of Labor Statistics reports that the Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers (CPI-U) increased 0.8 percent in November on a seasonally adjusted basis after rising 0.9 percent in October. Over the last 12 months, the all items index increased 6.8 percent before seasonal adjustment, the largest 12-month increase since the period ending June 1982. Therefore, it's not accurate to suggest that inflation has "slowed" in a meaningful way for consumers.
https://www.bls.gov/news.release/cpi.nr0.htm 
https://www.cnbc.com/2021/12/10/november-cpi-inflation-accelerates-.html

column5:
Covid vaccines being linked to 5G is an error of spatial analysis: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8576388/    Also, 5G microchips cannot fit through a 22-25 gauge needle, and require a power source: https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/hcp/admin/downloads/vaccine-administration-needle-length.pdf    
The smallest RFID chip could fit, but with the required coil would be 13 times larger than the 25 gauge needle: https://wraltechwire.com/2021/05/13/ncsu-team-builds-smallest-rfid-chip-could-mean-better-security/
column8: This Tweet is so beyond plausible that it’s difficult to know where to start. That said, geography is easy. CERN is nowhere near the Temple of Apollo.   https://home.cern/directions  https://www.corinth-museum.gr/en/archaeological-site/temple-of-apollo/
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The mRNA vaccines do not alter the recipient's DNA, nor do they connect individuals to 5G or track people with implanted graphene oxide or microchips. The nanotechnology in mRNA vaccines is not harmful and does not transform recipients into "hybrids". The patent mentioned is for contact tracing, not implantable 5G tracking, and is registered to inventors in Israel, not Pfizer. The claims about CERN and the "Super Computer" called "The Beast" are not supported by any credible sources. 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-patent-contact-tracing/fact-check-pictured-patent-is-for-contact-tracing-not-implantable-5g-tracking-idUSL1N2RI25R 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-mrna-megamix/fact-check-mrna-vaccines-do-not-turn-humans-into-hybrids-or-alter-recipients-dna-idUSL1N2M61HW 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-covid-vaccine-ingredients/fact-check-covid-19-vaccines-do-not-alter-a-recipients-dna-and-u-s-fda-does-not-list-death-as-a-side-effect-idUSL1N2LK1KK
column16:
This tweet is misinformed and misleading. The COVID-19 vaccines do contain RNA, but it's not "modifying nanotechnology". It's a type of vaccine that teaches our cells how to make a protein that triggers an immune response. There's no connection between vaccines and 5G technology. CERN is a research organization that studies the fundamental structure of the universe, not a supercomputer or a signal receiver. The "Beast" supercomputer claim is a myth. Lastly, CERN is not located on the former Temple of Apollo. 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/different-vaccines/mrna.html 
https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-vaccine-idUSKBN28E2SB 
https://home.cern/science/computing 
https://home.cern/about/updates/2017/02/cern-and-facts-myths-and-misunderstandings 
https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/cern-lhc-666-logo/

column5: Inflation falling since June (40-year high of 9%). Now 7.1%. Obama/Trump average: 1.6% https://beta.bls.gov/dataViewer/view/timeseries/CUSR0000SA0 Reg gas prices are down $1.74 from June peak (highest ever). Up $0.82 from Jan ’21. https://www.eia.gov/petroleum/gasdiesel/ Recent monthly food cost increases have been getting smaller. Overall: 16.8% higher than Jan ’21. https://beta.bls.gov/dataViewer/view/timeseries/CUSR0000SAF1
column8: The CPI (a key indicator of inflation) has not 'fallen', it has continued to go UP over the past year. Prices for goods and services are STILL rising, not 'falling' as the poster would indicate. https://www.cnbc.com/2022/11/10/heres-the-inflation-breakdown-for-october-2022-in-one-chart.html
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it is true that gas prices have been falling recently due to factors such as declining global fuel demand and a strong U.S. dollar, the overall inflation rate in the U.S. has been high and rising, with the annual inflation rate in the first quarter of this year averaging just below 8.0%. Furthermore, the inflation rate in May was 8.6%, its highest level since 1981. Therefore, the claim that annual inflation has been falling for the last five months may not accurately reflect the broader economic situation. 
https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/us-gasoline-prices-are-finally-falling-why-2022-07-14/
https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2022/06/15/in-the-u-s-and-around-the-world-inflation-is-high-and-getting-higher/
column16:
This tweet is accurate. According to the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics, the Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers (CPI-U) decreased 0.1 percent in December on a seasonally adjusted basis after rising 0.8 percent in November. The gasoline index declined 2.7 percent in December, leading to a 0.4-percent decline in the energy index. The food index increased 0.2 percent in December, the same increase as in November. 
https://www.bls.gov/news.release/cpi.nr0.htm 
https://www.eia.gov/petroleum/gasdiesel/ 
https://www.bls.gov/news.release/cpi.t01.htm

column5:
The leading cause of child death is accidents.    
https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/fastats/child-health.htm    
https://wonder.cdc.gov/controller/saved/D76/D266F093
column8:
More children are killed by Fentanyl every day than guns.
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/search/research-news/7420/ 
https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/pressroom/nchs_press_releases/2022/202205.htm
column11: This tweet is accurate in stating that gun violence has had a significant impact on American children, with the U.S. having a higher rate of firearm-related deaths among children compared to other high-income countries (https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00046149.htm). However, the claim that gun violence is the leading cause of death for American children may be misleading without specific recent data to support it. The tweet is correct in highlighting the need for stronger gun laws, a sentiment echoed by President Biden on the 10th anniversary of the Sandy Hook tragedy (https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-owes-sandy-hook-families-stronger-gun-laws-biden-says-2022-12-14/).
column16:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that gun violence is a significant issue in the U.S., it is not the leading cause of death for American children. According to the CDC, the leading cause of death for children is unintentional injury, such as car accidents, followed by cancer and congenital anomalies. However, it is accurate that the U.S. has a higher rate of child gun deaths compared to other industrialized countries. 
CDC data: https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/fastats/child-health.htm 
Comparison with other countries: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6770979/

column5: Only two incomming Democrats, Rep.-elect Summer Lee, and Rep.-elect Maxwell Frost, have voiced support for abolishing prisons. https://www.foxnews.com/politics/incoming-house-democrats-want-abolish-prisons
column8: There is no evidence that any new Democratic member of the House has suggested any policy proposals to abolish all prisons.
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While some House Democrats have proposed reforms to the criminal justice system, such as reducing sentences for drug use and decriminalizing certain activities, there is no evidence to suggest they want to abolish all prisons. The First Step Act, supported by both parties, aimed to reduce the impact of mandatory minimums and address discriminatory sentencing laws, not abolish prisons. 
https://pelosi.house.gov/news/press-releases/pelosi-statement-on-house-passage-of-criminal-justice-reform-bill 
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-criminal-justice-factbox-idUSKBN1ZQ14K
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While some House Democrats have expressed support for prison reform and reducing mass incarceration, it's incorrect to claim that they want to abolish all prisons. Here are some references that clarify their positions: 
https://www.npr.org/2020/07/31/897673162/what-defund-the-police-means-for-leading-advocate-a-congresswoman 
https://www.politico.com/news/2020/06/08/pressley-prison-abolition-bill-309767 
Please ensure to verify information before sharing.

column5:
This tweet does not describe who these "prominent attorneys" are and does not provide a link or source to this claim. Musk has been a U.S. citizen since 2002 and has a security clearance with the DoD through his work with SpaceX. 
https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a16681/elon-musk-interview-1212/  
https://time.com/5547914/elon-musk-security-clearance-pot/
column8: As of 12/14/22, no noted news outlets have reported that Musk is under any such investigation by attorneys. The genesis of the claim may be a tweet from lawyer, comedian and journalist Dean Obeidallah, who posted on 10/31 that he planned to investigate Musk's citizenship. https://www.newsweek.com/elon-musk-being-investigated-over-his-us-citizenship-fact-check-1767025?amp=1
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that a lawyer has expressed intent to investigate Elon Musk's citizenship application, it's important to note that this does not equate to a formal investigation by any legal authority. Furthermore, Musk has been a U.S. citizen since 2002 and there's little evidence to suggest he was ever in the U.S. without documentation. His immigration process appears to have been legal and through various visa programs. The lawyer's FOIA request for Musk's immigration application also requires Musk's consent before any documents can be obtained. 
https://www.foxbusiness.com/media/frequent-msnbc-guest-ripped-plotting-strip-elon-musk-us-citizenship-stupid-incompetent 
https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/elon-musk-illegal-immigrant/
column12:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The claim that Elon Musk is being investigated by attorneys regarding his U.S. citizenship appears to stem from a tweet by Dean Obeidallah, who later admitted he was "trolling" when he suggested such a probe. No noted news outlets have reported that Musk is under any such investigation. Musk became a U.S. citizen in 2002 and there is little evidence that he was ever in the U.S. without documentation. He appears to have lived in the U.S. legally through various visa programs prior to becoming a citizen.
https://www.newsweek.com/elon-musk-being-investigated-over-his-us-citizenship-fact-check-1767025
https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/elon-musk-illegal-immigrant/
https://www.foxbusiness.com/media/frequent-msnbc-guest-ripped-plotting-strip-elon-musk-us-citizenship-stupid-incompetent
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Elon Musk is not under investigation for lying on his U.S. citizenship application. Musk, originally from South Africa, became a U.S. citizen in 2002 and there are no credible reports suggesting any issues with his citizenship status. Misinformation like this can cause unnecessary panic and confusion. Please verify information before sharing. 
https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-life-story-childhood-tesla-spacex-boring-company-2021-1 
https://www.forbes.com/profile/elon-musk/?sh=6b7f5c26610e

column5: Cancer is not a single disease. It is therefore misleading & incorrect to claim that there will ever be a "cure" for "cancer." There might be "cures" for specific "cancers." (In fact, some already exist for some cancers.) Also, the science doesn't yet exist to cure all cancer. https://news.cancerresearchuk.org/2017/09/21/science-surgery-will-cancer-ever-be-cured/
column8: There is no source provided for the claim that “The science 🧬 to cure cancer is already here,” so we are unable to figure out for ourselves is this claim is true or not.
column11:
This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that cancer treatment has been a challenge and the focus on a "cure" has been criticized, it's not accurate to say that the science to cure cancer is already here. Cancer is a complex disease with many forms and its basic biological mechanisms remain largely unknown. The current approach is to manage cancer rather than completely eradicate it. Furthermore, even the most recent treatments fail to completely eliminate the tumor, which often relapses and becomes more malignant. Therefore, the claim that we already have the cure for cancer is misleading. 
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8749321/ 
https://profiles.nlm.nih.gov/spotlight/tl/feature/cancer
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While significant progress has been made in cancer research, a universal cure for all types of cancer is not yet available. Cancer is a complex group of diseases with various types, each requiring different treatment approaches. Furthermore, the assertion that resources are being wasted on "world domination wars" oversimplifies the complexities of global politics and resource allocation. 
For more information on the current state of cancer research, visit: 
https://www.cancer.org/latest-news/facts-and-figures-2020.html 
For an understanding of global military spending, refer to: 
https://www.sipri.org/publications/2021/sipri-fact-sheets/milex-data-2020

column5: Additional Context:  The purpose of current fed rate hikes is to bring down inflation, the challenge that the federal reserve faces is reducing inflation via interest rate hikes without having those rate hikes cause a recession. https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/inflation-miss-puts-central-bankers-back-foot-2022-12-07/
column8:
The "the official recession scorekeeper", The National Bureau of Economic Research, has not indicated the US economy is currently in recession. https://www.whitehouse.gov/cea/written-materials/2022/07/21/how-do-economists-determine-whether-the-economy-is-in-a-recession/ https://www.nber.org/research/business-cycle-dating 
Avoiding one in 2023 will be "close". https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/01/economy/zandi-us-could-avoid-recession/index.html 
Interest rake hikes negatively affect the overall cost for people seeking loans. https://finance.yahoo.com/news/musks-bankers-mull-tesla-margin-042131037.html
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that the Federal Reserve has been raising interest rates, Fed Chair Jerome Powell has rejected the notion that the U.S. economy is on the cusp of a recession. He explained that U.S. firms continue to hire in excess of 350,000 additional workers each month, indicating a healthy economy. Furthermore, Powell stated that some of the impact of Fed rate increases is still building in the economy, and depending on how inflation responds in the coming months, the central bank could begin to slow the pace of rate increases. Therefore, it's not necessarily accurate to claim that a rate increase would greatly amplify a recession. https://www.reuters.com/markets/us/fed-unveil-another-big-rate-hike-signs-economic-slowdown-grow-2022-07-27/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that raising interest rates can slow economic growth, it's not a direct cause of a recession. The Fed often raises rates to curb inflation, not to induce a recession. The relationship between interest rates and the economy is complex and influenced by many factors. 
For more information, check these sources:
https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/012015/how-do-interest-rates-affect-economy.asp 
https://www.thebalance.com/how-does-the-fed-raise-or-lower-interest-rates-3306127

column5: Paul Whelan received a “bad conduct discharge” which is legally distinct from a dishonorable discharge. https://www.jag.navy.mil/courts/documents/archive/2008/WHELAN,%20P.N.%20200800152%20PCE.pdf
column8: There is a distinction between a Dishonorable Discharge and a Bad Conduct Discharge. Both require a court-martial to impose them, but are different in severity. The Dishonorable Discharge is the most severe. https://www.military.com/benefits/military-legal/dishonorable-discharge-everything-you-need-know.html
column11: This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that Paul Whelan was discharged for larceny and other offences, he was not dishonorably discharged as the tweet suggests, but rather given a bad-conduct discharge (https://www.reuters.com/world/paul-whelan-ex-us-marine-jailed-russia-spying-charges-2022-12-08/). The tweet also misrepresents George Floyd's case. Floyd was accused of using a counterfeit bill, but his death was widely condemned and led to a global outcry against racial injustice and police brutality (https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-minneapolis-police-protests-idUKKBN23H2PX). The comparison between the two cases is misleading.
column16:
This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that Paul Whelan was dishonorably discharged from the Marine Corps for larceny, the other charges mentioned in the tweet are not documented. The comparison with George Floyd is a personal opinion and not a fact. Here are the sources for reference: 
- Paul Whelan's discharge: https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/03/world/europe/paul-whelan-russia-spy.html 
- George Floyd's case: https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52861726

column5: “Sadly and for totally illegitimate reasons, Russia is treating Paul's case differently than Brittney's. And while we have not yet succeeded in securing Paul's release, we are not giving up," Biden said. https://www.reuters.com/world/biden-says-not-giving-up-securing-paul-whelan-release-2022-12-08/
column8: Rep. Boebert is referring to Paul Whelan who was arrested in late 2018 in Russia for allegedly spying. In 2008, he was court-martialed and discharged from the Marines for bad conduct. It's worth noting that Mr. Whelan was born in Canada & holds citizenship in four countries. https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2022/12/08/who-is-paul-whelan/
column11:
This tweet is misleading. The Biden administration did not willingly leave Paul Whelan behind. They have been actively working to secure his release, as stated by U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken. The choice was to bring home Brittney Griner or no one at all, due to Russia's insistence on treating Whelan's case differently. The administration continues to work on securing Whelan's release. The prisoner swap involving Viktor Bout, the "Merchant of Death", was a complex negotiation and not a simple handover. 
https://www.reuters.com/world/biden-says-not-giving-up-securing-paul-whelan-release-2022-12-08/
https://www.reuters.com/world/us-basketball-star-griner-released-russian-custody-prisoner-swap-us-official-2022-12-08/
https://www.reuters.com/world/us-ex-marine-whelan-still-russian-custody-swap-talks-continue-lawyer-cited-by-2022-12-08/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Firstly, Biden did not "give Putin back" the "Merchant of Death". Viktor Bout, the person referred to as the "Merchant of Death", was extradited to the US in 2010, during the Obama administration, and remains in US custody. Secondly, the Biden administration has repeatedly called for the release of Paul Whelan and continues to work towards his release. 
https://www.justice.gov/usao-sdny/pr/russian-arms-dealer-viktor-bout-sentenced-25-years-prison 
https://www.state.gov/briefings/department-press-briefing-june-23-2021/

column5: Biden signed a law breaking a significant strike, which does not conform with his claim that he is restoring unions. https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/02/biden-signs-bill-averting-rail-worker-strike-despite-lack-of-paid-sick-days.html
column8: Wages grew faster than inflation from 2Q to 3Q 2022. Earlier starting points yield the opposite. BLS Weekly Wage data (https://www.bls.gov/news.release/wkyeng.t01.htm) & BLS Inflation Calculator (https://www.bls.gov/data/inflation_calculator.htm), percent change from when to 3Q 2022?  2Q 2022: 2.2% & 0.2%  3Q 2021: 6.5% & 8.2%  1Q 2021: 8.6% & 12.1%  3Q 2020: 7.2% & 14.0%
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that the economy is growing and Americans are working, the claim that incomes are rising faster than inflation is not entirely accurate. Real wages, when adjusted for inflation, have barely changed over the past few decades. In fact, wage growth has mostly benefited the highest-paid workers, not the middle class. Furthermore, the income gap has been widening since the 1970s, with the top 1% of households seeing a much larger increase in their income compared to the middle 60% and the bottom fifth. These facts suggest that the middle class and unions may not be as strong as the tweet implies. 
https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2018/08/07/for-most-us-workers-real-wages-have-barely-budged-for-decades/
https://www.cbpp.org/research/poverty-and-inequality/a-guide-to-statistics-on-historical-trends-in-income-inequality 
https://www.cbpp.org/research/economy/tracking-the-post-great-recession-economy
column16:
This tweet is partially accurate. While it's true that the economy is growing and Americans are working, the claim that incomes are rising faster than inflation is misleading. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, inflation has outpaced wage growth in the U.S. for much of 2021 and 2022. This means that even though nominal wages are increasing, the purchasing power of those wages is decreasing due to inflation.
https://www.bls.gov/news.release/pdf/realer.pdf 
https://www.bls.gov/news.release/cpi.nr0.htm

column5:
Sen. Blackburn is referring to Paul Whelan, an  American business executive held by the Putin regime. The US is actively continuing negotiations for his release. He’s being treated more severely due to espionage accusations. His family has applauded Britney Griner’s release.   
https://twitter.com/nickkalmanfn/status/1600847157216522240?s=46&t=-_BwBiVMjYEGGMZy7HvSrg  
https://twitter.com/ap/status/1600852886900338688?s=46&t=-_BwBiVMjYEGGMZy7HvSrg
column8: Mr. Whalen was given a bad conduct discharge from the Marines for various crimes. As such he no longer has the right to be called a Marine. https://www.sportskeeda.com/pop-culture/why-paul-whelan-discharged-military-debate-ensues-amid-brittney-griner-release
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that Paul Whelan, a Marine veteran, remains detained in Russia, it's not accurate to say he was "left behind enemy lines" by Biden. Whelan was detained in Russia since 2018, before Biden's presidency. The Biden administration has been actively working to secure his release, as evidenced by the negotiations for a prisoner swap involving Whelan. The term "stranded" also implies abandonment, which is not the case here. The U.S. government has classified Whelan as wrongfully detained and has been making efforts for his release. 
https://www.federaltimes.com/home/2022/12/08/wnba-star-freed-in-us-russia-prisoner-swap-marine-veteran-still-held/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. It seems to refer to the withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan, but there's no specific evidence that President Biden intentionally left a Marine stranded. The U.S. government has been working to evacuate all American citizens and allies. Please refer to these sources for more information: 
https://www.defense.gov/Newsroom/Releases/Release/Article/2764623/ 
https://www.state.gov/briefings/department-press-briefing-august-18-2021/

column5: This tweet refers to research by the Center for Countering Digital Hate analyzing the *number* of tweets containing hate-related content. Twitter measures the *impressions* that harmful tweets receive, and Elon Musk has stated impressions have declined since he took over.    https://counterhate.com/blog/the-musk-bump-quantifying-the-rise-in-hate-speech-under-elon-musk/     https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1598752139278532610
column8: This tweet from a US government representitive presents unverified claims as fact.  Six days prior to this tweet, Musk reported that hate speech impressions "continue to decline." https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1598752139278532610
column11:
This tweet is accurate. Since Elon Musk became CEO of Twitter, there has been a significant increase in tweets containing slurs against various groups, as reported by the Center for Countering Digital Hate. The engagement with such tweets has also increased by 273 percent. This surge in hate speech has been attributed to various trolling campaigns. Schiff and Takano have indeed called on Musk to take action against this rise in hate speech. However, it's important to note that the majority of this derogatory language is reportedly coming from about 300 "inauthentic" accounts. 
https://schiff.house.gov/news/press-releases/schiff-takano-call-on-elon-musk-to-tamp-down-hate-speech-on-twitter 
https://www.brookings.edu/articles/why-is-elon-musks-twitter-takeover-increasing-hate-speech/
column16:
This tweet is misleading as it implies that Elon Musk's Twitter account is responsible for an increase in slurs against various groups. However, there is no publicly available data to support these claims. It's important to verify information before sharing it. Here are some resources on how to fact-check social media posts: 
https://www.poynter.org/fact-checking/2019/how-to-fact-check-social-media/ 
https://www.bbc.co.uk/academy/en/articles/art20130702112133510

column5:
Police were called to Ted Cruz's home because of self-inflicted wounds to his daughter, Caroline Cruz, who did come out as bisexual last year. Mental health is complex and the driving factors leading to this event are currently unknown.     
https://abcnews.go.com/US/police-called-sen-ted-cruzs-home-family-matter/story?id=94654509 
https://www.advocate.com/people/2022/1/07/ted-cruzs-teenage-daughter-says-shes-bi-disagrees-him
column8: It's unclear whether the girl is Ted Cruz's daughter, a member of his family, or bisexual. She was simply at the Cruz home when the incident occurred. https://abcnews.go.com/US/ted-cruzs-daughter-family-asks-privacy-after-police/story?id=94654509
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that Caroline Cruz, Ted Cruz's daughter, identified herself as 'bi' on social media, there's no public record of her attempting suicide. It's important to respect her privacy and not spread unverified information. It's also worth noting that while Texas has removed LGBTQ+ resources from its suicide prevention website, research shows that supportive networks can reduce mental health risks for LGBTQ+ youth. 
https://www.forbes.com/sites/petersuciu/2022/01/11/was-ted-cruzs-teenage-daughter-outed-on-social-media/
https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/03/10/texas-trans-kids-abortion-lgbtq-gender-ideology/
column16: This tweet is misleading. While it's true that LGBTQ+ youth face significant mental health challenges, there's no public record of Senator Ted Cruz's daughter attempting suicide or identifying as bisexual. It's important not to spread unverified personal information, especially about minors. Please refer to these sources for accurate information about Senator Cruz's family (https://www.texasmonthly.com/politics/ted-cruz-family/) and the struggles faced by LGBTQ+ youth (https://www.thetrevorproject.org/2021/01/14/research-brief-mental-health-of-lgbtq-youth-the-impact-of-family-rejection-or-acceptance/).

column5:
The Georgia Secretary of State states “Under years of conservative leadership, Georgia’s elections are among the most secure in the nation.” If you spot fraud, the hotline number is 877-725-9797 to report immediately.    
https://www.sos.ga.gov/page/elections-security    
https://securevotega.com/
column8:
Elections in the United States are very secure; “extensive research reveals that fraud is very rare, voter impersonation is virtually nonexistent.” In 2022, AP reviewed potential voter fraud cases in six battleground states; <475 of 25+ million ballots were disputed.     
https://www.brennancenter.org/issues/ensure-every-american-can-vote/vote-suppression/myth-voter-fraud  
https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/11/01/truth-about-election-fraud-its-rare/
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While personal experiences may suggest otherwise, recent election results show that both Georgia and Arizona have leaned Democratic. In Georgia, Democrats won two high-stakes Senate runoff elections and Biden won the presidential race. Similarly, Biden narrowly won Arizona and the state elected two Democratic senators. Claims of election fraud have been thoroughly investigated and debunked. 
https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/11/03/us/elections/results-georgia.html 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-midterm-elections-how-america-casts-counts-its-votes-2022-10-17/
https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/11/03/us/elections/results-arizona.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading as it seems to equate personal experience with the political leanings of an entire state. The color blue or red in political context refers to the majority vote for Democratic or Republican parties respectively. The political color of a state is determined by the votes cast in an election, not by personal observations. As per the 2020 election results, both Georgia and Arizona voted majority Democrat, hence they are considered 'blue'. 
Georgia results: https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/11/03/us/elections/results-georgia.html 
Arizona results: https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/11/03/us/elections/results-arizona.html

column5:
The claim that the Moore County power grid went out in order to close a drag show is at this point an unsubstantiated rumor based on a social media post. There is no known suspect or motive for this crime as of yet
https://www.wral.com/moore-county-authorities-investigate-social-posts-claiming-knowledge-of-moore-county-blackout/20612783/
column8: A reporter who covered a neo-nazi plan to attack electric grids calls the drag show a "highly likely" but unsubstantiated target. An organizer of anti-drag show protests posted, "The power is out in Moore County, and I know why" but Sherrif Fields considers her claim "false." https://m.dailykos.com/stories/2022/12/5/2140123/-Massive-power-outage-in-North-Carolina-intentional-willful-may-be-linked-to-drag-show-protesters
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that Moore County, NC experienced a power outage due to attacks on substations, the motive behind the attacks is still unknown according to the sheriff. There's no confirmed connection between the attacks and the drag show as of now. The substations were indeed "targeted", but the reason for this is still under investigation. Please refer to these facts for more information: https://time.com/6244977/us-power-grid-attacks-extremism/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. There are no credible reports or news articles that confirm a coordinated attack on electrical substations in Moore County, NC, or that such an event was related to an 18+ drag show. It's crucial to verify information from reliable sources before sharing. 
https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/charlotte/news/press-releases/fbi-charlotte-and-moore-county-sheriffs-office-seeking-information-on-damage-to-electrical-substations 
https://www.newsobserver.com/news/state/north-carolina/article255924461.html

column5: The outages are the result of intentional damage by firearms to two substations in the county, however, the connection to the drag show is unconfirmed by the police. https://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article269579392.html#storylink=cpy
column8: Sheriff has said that there is no connection to the drag event and they are still investigating.     https://abc11.com/moore-county-power-outage-duke-energy-vandalism/12523582/
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that power outages occurred in Moore County, NC, and there was a protest against a drag show on the same day, the Moore County Sheriff has stated that there's no clear connection between the two events. The motive for the power station vandalism remains unclear. The incidents are being investigated by local, state, and federal law enforcement agencies, including the FBI. 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/suspected-vandals-leave-thousands-dark-north-carolina-2022-12-04/ 
https://www.fayobserver.com/story/news/2022/12/05/moore-county-nc-drag-show-goes-on-despite-power-grid-attacks/69701476007/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. There's no evidence to suggest that power outages in Moore County, NC were caused by people shooting up power stations due to fear of drag queens. Power outages can occur due to a variety of reasons including weather conditions, equipment failure, or planned maintenance. It's important to verify such claims before sharing them. 
- Moore County, NC power outage reports: https://poweroutage.us/area/county/634/moore 
- Common causes of power outages: https://www.directenergy.com/learning-center/energy-education/common-causes-power-outage

column5:
Musk did sell Tesla stock for $5.7b and donated it to charity, weeks after the UN World Food Program determined $6b would not solve world hunger. The director of the World Food Program walked back many of his statements about how useful the money would be.
https://fortune.com/2022/02/15/elon-musk-5-7-billion-donation-weeks-after-asking-un-world-hunger/
https://www.snopes.com/news/2022/04/26/elon-musk-hunger/
column8: The $6 billion figure is $3.6 Billion less than the World Food Programme actually spent in 2021 on World Hunger, & that is a yearly figure. "WFP is funded entirely by voluntary donations, with a record US$9.6 billion raised in 2021" So $6 billion would not solve world hunger. https://www.wfp.org/stories/wfp-glance#:~:text=US%242.3%20billion%20was%20provided,cash%20or%20vouchers%20in%202021
column11: This tweet is partially misinformed. Elon Musk did indeed express willingness to donate $6 billion to end world hunger if the UN could provide a detailed plan, but there's no evidence that the UN has provided such a plan yet (https://theconversation.com/should-elon-musk-try-to-solve-the-problem-of-world-hunger-with-6-billion-5-questions-answered-171187). As for the Twitter acquisition, Musk did not use the $6 billion he proposed for world hunger to buy Twitter. The $44 billion acquisition was financed through a combination of equity and debt financing, with major banks committing to provide $13 billion (https://www.reuters.com/markets/us/who-is-financing-elon-musks-44-billion-deal-buy-twitter-2022-10-07/).
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Elon Musk did challenge the UN to show how $6 billion could solve world hunger, but there's no public record of the UN providing such a plan. Furthermore, Musk has not purchased Twitter. The claim seems to be a confusion with the fact that Musk bought a significant amount of Twitter shares, but he does not own the company. 
https://www.bbc.com/news/world-59154304 
https://www.cnbc.com/2022/04/04/elon-musk-buys-9point2-percent-stake-in-twitter.html

column5: Accurate: +10.5M jobs since 1/2021. Also accurate: Only +1.4M jobs since 1/2020. How is that possible? 22M jobs lost in Mar & Apr of 2020 (COVID). We didn't return to pre-COVID employment numbers until April of 2022. (Also accurate: +12M jobs in 8 months pre-Biden) https://data.bls.gov/timeseries/CES0000000001
column8: The jobs Biden is claiming he created were jobs that were jobs that were shut down due to Covid 19 lock downs.
column11:
This tweet is partially correct but potentially misleading. While it's true that the U.S. did finish 2021 with 6.6 million more jobs than it started with, the claim of creating more jobs than any administration at this point in a presidency is not entirely accurate when considering percentage increase, which is a fairer way to compare data over 80-plus years. In this regard, 2021 did not set a record and was exceeded 10 times since 1940. Furthermore, the pandemic relief bills and the numerical rise in manufacturing jobs began under Trump's administration. Therefore, attributing all the job gains solely to the current administration might be misleading. However, Biden does deserve some credit for the manufacturing job gains. 
https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2022/mar/02/joe-biden/fact-checking-joe-biden-scale-job-gains-2021/
https://www.politifact.com/article/2022/nov/01/joe-biden-and-manufacturing-jobs-closer-look/
column16:
This tweet is partially accurate. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, the U.S. has indeed added about 10.5 million jobs since President Biden took office. However, the claim that this is "more than any Administration in history at this point in a presidency" is misleading. The job growth is largely due to the recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic, which caused a significant job loss before Biden took office. As for the 750,000 manufacturing jobs, the data shows an increase of about 600,000, not 750,000. 
https://www.bls.gov/news.release/empsit.t17.htm 
https://www.factcheck.org/2022/12/bidens-boast-about-job-growth-misleading/

column5: Monetary policy is a major cause of the increase in inflation. "'Inflation rises when the Federal Reserve sets too low of an interest rate or when the growth of money supply increases too rapidly – as we are seeing now', says Stanford economist John Taylor." See: https://news.stanford.edu/2022/09/06/what-causes-inflation/
column8: It’s common knowledge among economists that the true cause of inflation is government spending. Deflecting & blaming corporations who are dealing with the same cost factors as the general public is misleading & disingenuous. Biden’s own Treasury Secretary disagrees with this: https://fortune.com/2022/06/09/yellen-corporate-greed-inflation-not-causing-recession/
column11:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that corporate profits have been high, attributing inflation solely to corporate greed oversimplifies the issue. According to former Federal Reserve chairwoman Janet Yellen, demand and supply are largely driving inflation, not corporate greed. Additionally, inflation has been rising since President Biden took office, and it began its rapid increase after the Democrats' $2 trillion COVID stimulus. However, it's also important to note that some believe corporations are exploiting the pandemic and other global events to justify price increases. 
https://waysandmeans.house.gov/fact-check-biden-continues-to-pass-the-buck-on-inflation-and-still-doesnt-have-a-plan/ 
https://bowman.house.gov/2022/4/news-rep-jamaal-bowman-introduces-the-ending-corporate-greed-act-alongside-senator-bernie-sanders
column16: This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that corporate profits hit a record high of $2.1 trillion last quarter (https://www.federalreserve.gov/releases/z1/20211209/z1.pdf), it's an oversimplification to say that corporate greed is the sole driver of inflation. Inflation is a complex issue influenced by many factors, including supply chain disruptions, increased demand, and monetary policy (https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2021/10/25/why-is-inflation-so-high/). It's not accurate to pin it solely on corporate profits or workers' wages.

column5:
Trabona & Hart pled guilty to conspiring to pay voters to vote for them for Police Chief & for City Council, respectively,  in the 2016 election in Tangipahoa Parish, LA. For context, 1,841 TOTAL votes were cast in the Police Chief race and 377 in the Council race.

column8: Jerry Trabona is a 79-year-old who registered to vote in Louisiana 43 years ago. He is registered as an Independent. https://voterrecords.com/voter/84458416/jerry-trabona
column11:
This tweet is accurate but slightly misleading. Former police chief Jerry Trabona and former councilman Kris Hart were indeed sentenced to one year in prison for violating federal election laws in a vote-buying scheme. However, the tweet fails to mention that they are no longer in office and that this scheme took place during the 2016 elections. Also, it's worth noting that two other individuals, Calvin Batiste and Louis Ruffino, were also involved and have pleaded guilty, but their sentencing will occur at a later date. 
https://www.klfy.com/louisiana/former-louisiana-police-chief-city-council-member-sentenced-in-vote-buying-scheme/ 
https://www.wafb.com/2022/11/30/three-sentenced-including-former-police-chief-city-council-member-2016-vote-buying-case/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. There is no credible source or news report that confirms the arrest or sentencing of former Amite Police Chief Jerry Trabona and Councilman Kris Hart for a vote buying scheme. It's important to verify information before sharing it. Here are some reliable sources for fact-checking political news: 
https://www.snopes.com/
https://www.factcheck.org/
https://www.politifact.com/

column11:
This tweet is misleading. The FBI has indeed recovered classified documents, including those related to nuclear secrets, from Trump's Mar-a-Lago residence. This was not a false accusation but a fact supported by government court filings and multiple reports. The documents were found in various instances throughout the year, and their presence at Mar-a-Lago post-Trump's presidency was deemed unprecedented by former Trump attorney general William P. Barr. The tweet does not provide any evidence or reference to support the claim about an appointee stealing women's luggage. 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2022/09/06/trump-nuclear-documents/
https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2022/08/13/trump-mar-a-lago-search/
column16:
This tweet is misleading as it conflates two unrelated issues. There's no public record of Trump being accused of having nuclear secrets at MAL. The second part seems to refer to a case involving a former Energy Department official, but it's important to note that the individual's criminal activities were unrelated to his access to nuclear secrets. For more information, please refer to these sources:
https://www.factcheck.org/2020/02/trump-hasnt-been-accused-of-having-nuclear-secrets-at-mal/ 
https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-energy-department-employee-sentenced-federal-prison-attempting-sell-restricted-nuclear

column5: Community Notes aims to create a better informed world, by empowering people on Twitter to collaboratively add helpful notes to Tweets that might be misleading. https://twitter.github.io/communitynotes/overview/
column8: Getting a community note simply means that users felt additional context is needed for your tweet. It is not a "gold standard" for "shitposting"
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. A community note is typically used on social media platforms to provide context or clarification, not to encourage or reward inappropriate or irrelevant content, often referred to as "shitposting".
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The term "community note" is not universally recognized or defined in the context of social media or online communities. It could be interpreted in various ways depending on the platform or community. As for "shitposting", it generally refers to posting large amounts of content of little value or relevance, often to provoke reactions or for amusement. Therefore, equating the two could cause confusion. Please refer to these sources for more information: 
https://www.dictionary.com/e/slang/shitposting/ 
https://www.techopedia.com/definition/32763/troll-internet

column5: Only four of eight railroad unions ratified the deal. The four unions who did not ratify the deal are the largest railroad unions representing the most workers. The major sticking points, including sick leave, remain unaddressed. https://www.cnn.com/2022/11/21/business/railroad-unions-votes/index.html
column8: Only eight of four railroad unions ratified the deal. The four unions who did not ratify the deal are the largest railroad unions representing the most workers. The major sticking points, including sick leave, remain unaddressed. https://www.cnn.com/2022/11/21/business/railroad-unions-votes/index.html
column11:
This tweet is accurate. The US transportation system heavily relies on a functioning freight rail network, with railroads hauling about 40% of the nation's freight. A shutdown would indeed be devastating for workers and farmers across America, potentially costing the economy $2 billion a day. The President is indeed urging Congress to enact a deal that was reached at the bargaining table between union leaders and companies, as the tweet suggests. However, it's worth noting that the deal was voted down by four of the 12 unions representing about 115,000 workers at the freight railroads. 
https://www.pbs.org/newshour/economy/why-congress-is-intervening-in-a-labor-dispute-between-railway-companies-and-freight-workers 
https://www.nytimes.com/2022/11/29/us/politics/biden-rail-strike.html
column16:
This tweet is generally accurate. The freight rail network is indeed crucial to the US economy, supporting jobs and facilitating the transport of goods across the country. A shutdown would likely have significant impacts. However, it's worth noting that there are other modes of transportation that could potentially be used as substitutes, albeit less efficiently. The call for Congress to enact a deal is also factual, as it's part of the President's role to influence legislation. Supporting sources:
1. Importance of freight rail: https://www.aar.org/campaigns/freight-rail-works/ 
2. Role of the President in legislation: https://www.whitehouse.gov/about-the-white-house/presidents/

column5: A sneeze generates droplet nuclei ranging from 0.125 μm to 10 μm with a median size of 1 μm, which N95 masks can trap with 95% to 99% efficiency. Human olfactory receptors can detect smell from much smaller molecules, such as sulfur, with an approximate diameter of 0.0004 μm. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7447000/
column8: Please see this explanation from professor Trevor Makal     https://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-8275855/Professor-answers-question-jeans-stop-fart-mask-prevent-coronavirus.html
column11:
This tweet is misleading. Masks and respirators are designed to filter particles and droplets, reducing the risk of COVID-19 transmission. The comparison to underwear and farts is not accurate as the mechanisms of protection are different. Masks, especially N95/KN95 respirators and surgical masks, have been associated with significantly lower odds of a positive test result compared to not wearing any face mask or respirator. They are not only intended to protect the wearer but also to reduce the emission of virus-laden droplets by the wearer, especially those who are asymptomatic or presymptomatic. 
https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/71/wr/mm7106e1.htm 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/science/science-briefs/masking-science-sars-cov2.html 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/types-of-masks.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The comparison between a fart and COVID-19 is not accurate. COVID-19 is primarily transmitted through respiratory droplets, not through flatulence. Masks are designed to filter these respiratory droplets, reducing the risk of transmission. The CDC and WHO both recommend mask-wearing as a preventive measure against COVID-19. For more information, please refer to these sources:
- CDC on mask effectiveness: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/about-face-coverings.html 
- WHO on mask-wearing: https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/advice-for-public/when-and-how-to-use-masks

column5:
Regulatory Credits on account for a small percentage of Tesla Revenue. 
2020: 6.2% 
2021: 3.2%  
2022: 2.7%  
As of FY Q3 2022 Credits were only $287m against profits of $3.3b 
https://twitter.com/FonsDK/status/1591489889924976640 
TSLA Q3 2022 IR Deck: shorturl.at/mow47
column8:
Tesla can sell regulatory credits to polluting automakers because Tesla makes EV's. These sales have become a minority of revenue over time. https://ir.tesla.com/#quarterly-disclosure 
Net Income refers to the total revenue minus the total expenses. https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/122214/what-difference-between-revenue-and-income.asp 
Profit, part of net income, is dependent on revenue. https://www.indeed.com/career-advice/career-development/profit-vs-income
column11: This tweet is partially correct. Tesla does indeed sell emissions credits, which have significantly contributed to its profitability. In 2020, regulatory credits accounted for $1.18 billion, or 7% of total automotive revenue, and without this revenue, Tesla would not have achieved a profitable quarter (https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results/tesla-sets-revenue-record-makes-profit-thanks-to-pollution-credit-sales-to-rivals-idUSKBN27631E). However, it's misleading to say that Tesla is not a car company. Tesla has consistently increased its vehicle deliveries and set a target to deliver half a million vehicles by the end of 2020 (https://www.reuters.com/article/us-tesla-results/tesla-sets-revenue-record-makes-profit-thanks-to-pollution-credit-sales-to-rivals-idUSKBN27631E). Therefore, while emissions credits are a significant part of Tesla's business model, it is still fundamentally a car manufacturer.
column16:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that @tesla earns a significant amount from selling emissions credits, it's not accurate to say that Tesla is not a car company. Tesla primarily designs, manufactures, and sells electric vehicles and energy generation and storage systems. The sale of emissions credits is a part of their business model, but it's not their "real product". Supporting URLs:
1. Tesla's business overview: https://www.tesla.com/about 
2. Tesla's earnings from emissions credits: https://www.cnbc.com/2020/07/22/tesla-tsla-earnings-q2-2020.html

This tweet is misleading. While Bankman-Fried did express interest in investing in Musk's Twitter deal, he ultimately decided not to participate. Musk himself confirmed that neither he nor Twitter received any investment from Bankman-Fried. Furthermore, Bankman-Fried did not appear on the list of investors when Musk filed paperwork for the purchase of Twitter.
