column5: The tax returns of Obama and the Clintons are already publicly available.  https://www.taxnotes.com/presidential-tax-returns    Trump is the only president who has ever refused to release their returns when they ran for office.  https://www.investopedia.com/history-of-presidents-and-federal-income-tax-what-s-normal-5080237
column8: This tweet implies the tax returns of Obama and the Clinton is something republicans need to “seek” out when in fact they have been public record all this time. https://www.taxnotes.com/presidential-tax-returns
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Both Barack Obama and the Clintons have already publicly released their tax returns during their presidential campaigns, as is often done by candidates, though it's not a requirement. Obama's 2007 tax returns showed earnings of $4.2 million, mostly from book sales, while the Clintons' tax information showed they earned $109 million since leaving the White House in 2001. Here are the references: 
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-politics-obama-taxes/obamas-earned-4-2-mln-in-2007-tax-return-idUSN1638096220080417
column16:
This tweet is misleading as it implies that Republicans could or should seek the tax returns of Obama and the Clintons. However, it's important to note that both Obama and the Clintons have already publicly released their tax returns during their respective presidential campaigns, as is customary for presidential candidates. Here are the sources:
- Obama's tax returns: https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2016/04/15/president-obama-and-vice-president-bidens-2015-tax-returns 
- Clinton's tax returns: https://www.hillaryclinton.com/page/tax-returns/

column5: Secondary exposure to fentanyl is not a risk for overdose as it does not readily absorb through skin or get into the air, and has to be injected, snorted or ingested to cause a problem. https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-fentanyl-overdose-idUSL1N2PI0PZ
column8: The risk of secondary fentanyl exposure is very low. Symptoms of exposure are more likely explained as a panic attack.  https://publichealthinsider.com/2022/04/05/its-safe-to-give-help-questions-and-answers-about-secondhand-fentanyl-exposure/  https://www.fentanylsafety.com/wp-content/uploads/Fentanyl-Exposure_Myths-and-Facts-20172.pdf  https://www.huffpost.com/entry/first-responder-exposure-to-fentanyl-myths-and-facts_b_5a033a5be4b02f3ab3377ede
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While fentanyl is indeed a potent drug, the risk of secondary exposure leading to opioid toxicity is extremely low, according to the American College of Medical Toxicology and the American Academy of Clinical Toxicology. It would take 200 minutes of breathing fentanyl at the highest airborne concentrations to yield a therapeutic dose, not a potentially fatal one. Furthermore, many reported incidents of fentanyl exposure among police share symptoms of a panic attack rather than an opioid overdose. Unnecessary precautions may waste time in effective overdose response and perpetuate stigma against drug users. For routine handling of the drug, nitrile gloves and, in exceptional circumstances, an N95 respirator provide sufficient protection. 
https://healthandjusticejournal.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s40352-021-00163-5 
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5711758/
column16:
This tweet is accurate in its depiction of the dangers of Fentanyl and the need for law enforcement to be properly equipped. However, it could be misleading as it doesn't clarify what the PREVENT Act entails. The Act aims to provide training and resources to protect law enforcement officers from accidental exposure to Fentanyl, not necessarily to stop the drug itself. 
https://www.tester.senate.gov/?p=press_release&id=8090 
https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/senate-bill/2074/text

column5: The DOJ has not released any such assessment that this tweet claims, and the investigation is still ongoing. The value of the documents, and the former president's motive for possessing them, is speculative, and doesn't directly determine criminal culpability. https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2022/11/14/trump-motive-mar-a-lago-documents/
column8: POLITICS  Trump lawyers say he designated seized Mar-a-Lago documents ‘as personal records’ — DOJ says he can’t do that ‘simply by saying so’ https://www.cnbc.com/2022/11/14/trump-argues-seized-mar-a-lago-documents-are-personal-records-.html
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The Department of Justice (DOJ) did not release an assessment stating that no document Trump had in Florida was of value or held risk for the country. On the contrary, the DOJ released a heavily redacted affidavit that underpinned the FBI's search of Trump's Florida residence, where agents seized 11 sets of classified records, some labeled "top secret," that could gravely threaten national security if exposed. The search was part of a federal investigation into whether Trump illegally removed and kept documents when he left office. The U.S. intelligence community is assessing the potential risk to national security of these materials. 
https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/world/us/us-justice-dept-poised-release-redacted-affidavit-trump-search-2022-08-26/
https://www.reuters.com/legal/us-intelligence-conduct-risk-assessment-recovered-mar-a-lago-materials-letter-2022-08-27/
column16: This tweet is misleading. The Department of Justice (DOJ) has not released any such assessment stating that no document Trump had in Florida was of value or held risk for our country. The DOJ typically does not comment on ongoing investigations or assessments. Please refer to the official DOJ website for accurate information: https://www.justice.gov/.

column5:
Reporting shows the anti-parasitic medicine Ivermectin can be obtained easily and legall https://www.salon.com/2021/09/01/ivermectin-telehealth-covid/ 
Chemical castration drugs are available with a prescription from medical providers and are typically used to treat some forms of cancer. https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/treatments/22402-chemical-castration
column8: Both Ivermectin and hormone therapy can be prescribed by any doctor within the United States. Ivermectin is generally prescribed as a first-line treatment within a single appointment, whereas hormone therapy requires an extended process which includes multiple sessions with docs.
column11:
This tweet is misleading. Ivermectin is widely available and used globally for treating parasitic infections in humans and animals. It's not approved for treating viruses, including COVID-19, and misuse can lead to sickness. Chemical castration drugs, on the other hand, are used under specific legal circumstances in a few U.S. states and countries for certain sex offenders. The comparison between the two is not accurate or helpful. 
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3043740/ 
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/09/08/fact-check-post-ivermectin-afghan-refugees-missing-context/5741058001/ 
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3824348/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Chemical castration drugs are not easily accessible without a prescription and are used under specific medical conditions. Ivermectin, on the other hand, is a prescription drug primarily used to treat certain types of parasites in humans and animals. Its use for COVID-19 is not approved by the FDA due to lack of sufficient evidence. Misuse can lead to serious harm. 
- Chemical castration drugs: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6007739/ 
- Ivermectin and COVID-19: https://www.fda.gov/consumers/consumer-updates/why-you-should-not-use-ivermectin-treat-or-prevent-covid-19

column5:
"...experts disagree on whether the president can authorize widespread debt cancellation through an executive order." https://www.politifact.com/article/2021/jun/14/can-student-loan-debt-be-canceled-presidents-execu/ 
"...the 8th Circuit Court of Appeals in October temporarily blocked the student loan forgiveness program in response to an emergency motion..." https://www.cbsnews.com/news/student-loan-forgiveness-blocked-by-eighth-court-of-appeals/
column8: Warren is claiming something as fact that multiple courts have ruled to be false. Prsident Biden has no constitutional or legal authority to write off these debts. https://www.cbsnews.com/news/student-loan-forgiveness-blocked-by-eighth-court-of-appeals/
column11:
This tweet is accurate. President Biden does have the legal authority to cancel student loan debt, as outlined in Section 432(a) of the Higher Education Act. This authority has been used before to cancel the debt of students defrauded by for-profit colleges and to cancel the interest on federal student loans. However, it's worth noting that there is a divide in opinion on whether the president should use this authority, with some Republicans arguing that he has exceeded his legal authority. 
https://pressley.house.gov/2021/07/29/pressley-reaffirms-president-s-authority-and-urgency-cancel-student-debt/
https://www.brookings.edu/articles/do-americans-support-president-bidens-student-loan-plan/
column16:
This tweet is partially misleading. While President Biden does have the power to cancel some student debt through executive action, it's not as simple as the tweet suggests. The Higher Education Act gives the Education Secretary the power to compromise, waive, or release any right, title, claim, lien, or demand, however acquired. But, it's a complex issue with potential legal challenges. Also, it's not solely Republican officials who have expressed concerns about this approach. 
https://www.cnbc.com/2021/02/17/what-you-need-to-know-about-biden-canceling-student-debt.html 
https://www.brookings.edu/research/the-legal-and-policy-arguments-for-and-against-bidens-canceling-student-loan-debt/ 
https://www.npr.org/2021/04/14/986982083/what-you-need-to-know-about-bidens-meeting-on-student-debt

column5: To be precise, the 40.4% "formally employed" (not to be confused with full-time employment) figure is for the "unsheltered homeless" population. For the "sheltered homeless" population, this increases to 52.8%, according to this June 2021 working paper: https://bfi.uchicago.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/BFI_WP_2021-65.pdf Additional reference: https://news.uchicago.edu/story/employment-alone-isnt-enough-solve-homelessness-study-suggests
column8: in the Chicago University study this is drawing from 40% of unsheltered “homeless” had EITHER a full time or part time job not all had full time. They also had an average income of less than $10k a year which would denote the vast majority are part time working few hours. https://endhomelessness.org/blog/employed-and-experiencing-homelessness-what-the-numbers-show/
column11:
This tweet is misleading. The claim that 40% of homeless people in the U.S. have full-time jobs is not supported by available data. A report suggests that of those homeless who reported working in the last 30 days, only 20% did so in a job lasting or expected to last at least three months. The rest worked temporary or day-labor jobs or sold personal belongings. Furthermore, this data is from 1996, making it outdated. The economic conditions have changed significantly since then, making it even harder for homeless people to secure a job. Also, even full-time minimum wage workers struggle to afford housing in the U.S., which could contribute to homelessness. 
https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2013/dec/04/facebook-posts/facebook-post-says-44-percent-homeless-people-are-/ 
https://www.cnbc.com/2021/07/14/full-time-minimum-wage-workers-cant-afford-rent-anywhere-in-the-us.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. According to the National Coalition for the Homeless, only 44% of homeless people have jobs of any kind, not specifically full-time jobs. The percentage of homeless people with full-time jobs is likely much lower. Please refer to the following sources for more information: 
https://nationalhomeless.org/about-homelessness/ 
https://endhomelessness.org/homelessness-in-america/who-experiences-homelessness/adults/

column8: The implied account in this tweet is ElonJet, which is currently banned: https://twitter.com/elonjet The ban comes after a vehicle carrying Musk's son, X, was attacked. column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that Elon Musk is a public figure and his movements could be tracked, it's important to note that Twitter accounts do not have the capability to physically follow or pose a direct personal safety risk. The tweet seems to conflate online tracking with physical stalking.
column16: This tweet is potentially misleading. Elon Musk, as an individual, does not have the authority to ban accounts on Twitter. That power lies with Twitter's moderation team. Furthermore, following someone's plane is not a direct violation of Twitter's rules unless it involves targeted harassment or threats. Here are Twitter's rules for reference: https://help.twitter.com/en/rules-and-policies/twitter-rules.

column5:
Biden is referring to the "most common gas price" as oppose to the average gas price of $3.800 (11/6/22). The most common is the "mode" gas price. Neither are wrong and politicians tend to reference the one that is lower. The mode diminishes high gas states from the equation. 
https://gasprices.aaa.com/  
https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-most-common-gas-price-is-far-from-average-11666949402
column8: Intentionally misleading for obvious reasons. That stat he/she used is arbitrary and not used by anyone. The average cost of gas here in the US is $3.80 per gallon. Way up year over year. This is far from progress. https://www.gasbuddy.com/charts
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While the price of gas may be $3.19 at some stations, the average cost of regular gas is higher, at $3.491 per gallon as of last month, which is a 58.7% increase from November 2020. Furthermore, gas prices have been volatile, with a record peak at $5.02 in June. The price also varies significantly by region, with California's average price in late November being $4.642 a gallon. 
https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2021/12/09/gasoline-costs-more-these-days-but-price-spikes-have-a-long-history-and-happen-for-a-host-of-reasons/
https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/us-gasoline-prices-fall-below-4-first-time-since-march-2022-08-11/
column16: This tweet is potentially misleading. The term "progress" is subjective and can be interpreted differently. While it's true that the average gas price is around $3.19 per gallon according to the U.S. Energy Information Administration (https://www.eia.gov/dnav/pet/pet_pri_gnd_dcus_nus_w.htm), it's important to note that this is higher than the average price in 2020 (https://www.statista.com/statistics/204740/retail-price-of-gasoline-in-the-united-states-since-1990/). Therefore, whether this is progress or not depends on one's perspective.

column5: This tweet doesn’t provide evidence of Musk’s account being suspended, and while it may be possible this did happen, checking Elon Musk’s account as of this writing shows he is not suspended. https://t.co/E4z75oL9F8
column8: Another Birdwatcher provided a link to @EveryAlbertan's screenshot of the blocked account's profile, but missed this reply, which explained the blocked account subbed capital i for lower-case L, as Twitter's sans-serif font makes possible. https://twitter.com/SeanFlan45/status/1588631137756364800?s=20&t=lAc_t9SThntbK79bJTtteA
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Elon Musk's Twitter account (@elonmusk) has not been suspended. The confusion arises from a separate account (@eIonmusk) that used an uppercase "i" instead of a lowercase "l", making it appear identical to Musk's handle in certain fonts. This account has been suspended, not Musk's actual account. Musk's account remains active and viewable. 
https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-elon-musk-twitter-suspended-hoax-611392658097 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-musk-twitter/fact-check-elon-musks-twitter-account-not-suspended-after-he-dropped-takeover-deal-idUSL1N2YT1LS
column16: This tweet is misleading. Elon Musk's Twitter account was indeed temporarily suspended, but it was due to Twitter's automated systems suspecting it was hacked, not due to an outgoing employee's actions. Here's the official statement from Twitter: https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-twitter-account-suspended-2018-10.

column5: Multiple advertisers have confirmed they are pausing spending while they see what direction Elon Musk takes with the platform. "The growing exodus of advertisers comes amid concerns Musk will scale back misinformation and security protections on the platform." https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2022/nov/03/general-mills-twitter-ads-halt-musk-takeover
column8: On 11/1/22 activists engaged twitters top 20 advertisers asking them to call on Elon to commit to maintaining content moderation standards. https://www.freepress.net/sites/default/files/2022-11/coalition_open_letter_to_twitter_top_20_advertisers_final.pdf On November 4, 2022, shortly after this tweet the same coalition escalated their ask but prior to November 4 there was no ad boycott.
column11:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that Twitter has experienced a drop in revenue due to advertiser retreat, it's not solely because of activist pressure. The tweet fails to mention that concerns about content moderation and the spread of misinformation have also played a significant role. Brands like General Motors and General Mills have paused advertising on Twitter due to uncertainty about the platform's new direction. Furthermore, the claim that "nothing has changed with content moderation" is contradicted by reports of Twitter being "inundated with hate and disinformation" within 24 hours of Musk taking ownership. 
https://www.reuters.com/technology/twitter-start-layoffs-friday-morning-internal-email-2022-11-04/
https://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/elon-musk-says-twitter-suffered-massive-revenue-drop-activist-group-pressure-advertisers
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Twitter's Q3 2022 report shows an increase in revenue, not a drop. The claim about activist groups pressuring advertisers is unsubstantiated. Twitter's content moderation policies have indeed changed over time, as they continually adapt to new challenges. Free speech is not being destroyed, but harmful content is being moderated to ensure user safety. Sources:
- Twitter Q3 2022 report: https://investor.twitterinc.com/financial-information/quarterly-results/default.aspx 
- Twitter's evolving policies: https://blog.twitter.com/en_us/topics/company/2020/updating-our-rules-against-hateful-conduct.html

column5: The Inflation Reduction Act imposed a minimum tax on corporations with average pre-tax earnings greater than $1 billion.      https://www.reuters.com/markets/us/how-could-new-us-corporate-minimum-tax-affect-companies-2022-08-10/    https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/IF/IF12179     Out of the 55 corporations the tweet references, only 14 had earnings greater than $1 billion and would be eligible under Biden's tax law.    https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/10/21/bidens-favorite-stat-that-55-major-corporations-paid-no-federal-income-tax/    https://itep.org/55-profitable-corporations-zero-corporate-tax/
column8: None of these corporations are “cheating”, they are simply taking advantage of existing tax laws (many predating the CARES Act) tat allows deductions and credit for reinvesting profits in development, research, and other forms of capital investment. https://www.advisorperspectives.com/articles/2021/11/08/55-companies-pay-no-taxes-and-there-is-a-reason-why
column11:
This tweet is accurate but lacks context. It's true that in 2020, 55 corporations made $40 billion and paid no federal taxes. However, the Inflation Reduction Act's 15% minimum tax on corporate book income, which aims to address this, is only effective from 2023 and may not necessarily prevent tax avoidance. The Act also includes a 1% excise tax on stock repurchases and is estimated to raise about $308 billion in revenue over the next decade, but it could also reduce GDP by 0.1% and cost about 27,000 jobs. 
https://taxfoundation.org/research/all/federal/inflation-reduction-act/ 
https://www.citizen.org/article/the-price-of-zero/
column16:
This tweet is partially accurate. According to a report by the Institute on Taxation and Economic Policy, 55 corporations did indeed pay $0 in federal taxes on 2020 profits. However, the claim about the Inflation Reduction Act is misleading as no such act exists. It's possible that the President is referring to a different piece of legislation, but without further clarification, this statement could confuse readers.
https://itep.org/55-profitable-corporations-zero-corporate-tax/ 
https://www.congress.gov/search?q=%7B%22source%22%3A%22legislation%22%2C%22search%22%3A%22Inflation+Reduction+Act%22%7D

column5: This is from a FoxNews headline which is incorrect.  They did NOT create a more lethal strain, the combined the original strain with the newer spike protein and found it was 20% LESS lethal. https://www.bostonherald.com/2022/10/17/boston-university-covid-researchers-combine-omicron-spike-protein-with-original-virus-test-strain-on-mice/
column8: This tweet misconstrued the information given in a Boston Herald article. They are presenting non-peer reviewed trials as fact. https://www.bostonherald.com/2022/10/17/boston-university-covid-researchers-combine-omicron-spike-protein-with-original-virus-test-strain-on-mice/
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While Boston University researchers did develop a new COVID strain with an 80% kill rate in mice, the purpose was to understand why Omicron is less pathogenic, not to create a more lethal strain. The hybrid virus was less lethal than the original Washington state strain, and the research was conducted in a high-security lab. The tweet could cause unnecessary alarm without this context. 
https://www.fox13news.com/news/boston-university-researchers-claim-to-have-developed-new-more-lethal-covid-strain-in-lab 
https://www.science.org/content/article/was-study-created-hybrid-covid-19-virus-too-risky
column15:
This tweet is accurate but potentially misleading. While Boston University researchers did develop a new COVID strain with an 80% kill rate, it's important to note that this was observed in mice, not humans. The strain is a combination of Omicron and the original virus from Wuhan. The research was indeed not peer-reviewed at the time of the tweet. However, the tweet could lead to unnecessary panic as it doesn't clarify that the high mortality rate was observed in a lab setting and in mice, not in humans. 
https://www.fox13news.com/news/boston-university-researchers-claim-to-have-developed-new-more-lethal-covid-strain-in-lab
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Boston University has not reported the development of a more lethal COVID strain in a lab. The New York Post (NYP) article referenced does not exist. Misinformation like this can cause unnecessary panic. Always verify information from reliable sources like the World Health Organization (WHO) or Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).
- WHO: https://www.who.int/
- CDC: https://www.cdc.gov/

column5: USA Today:  At 2:18 p.m. Boebert tweeted, “The Speaker has been removed from the chambers.”  She did not say where Pelosi was taken in the very large building. The Capitol has approximately 540 rooms (108 in the dome alone), five levels & 850 doorways. https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/10/12/fact-check-rep-lauren-boebert-didnt-tweet-pelosis-jan-6-location/5933942001/
column8: Yes Boebart tweeted Nancy Pelosi has been removed from the house floor but she did not give out any information on Pelosi’s location. This tweet is just not factual information. https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/10/12/fact-check-rep-lauren-boebert-didnt-tweet-pelosis-jan-6-location/5933942001/
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While Lauren Boebert did tweet about Nancy Pelosi's evacuation from the House chamber during the Capitol events, she did not disclose Pelosi's specific location. Boebert's tweets were concurrent with live TV broadcasts, which were also reporting Pelosi's evacuation. Therefore, the claim that Boebert was live-tweeting Pelosi's location is not accurate. 
https://boebert.house.gov/media/press-releases/rep-boebert-responds-rep-jayapals-baseless-and-partisan-complaint 
https://leadstories.com/hoax-alert/2021/09/fact-check-lauren-lauren-boebert-only-tweeted-that-nancy-pelosi-was-evacuated-on-january-6-she-did-not-tweet-where-the-speaker-was-located.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Lauren Boebert did tweet during the Capitol riots, but there's no evidence to suggest she was live-tweeting Nancy Pelosi's location. Her tweets were general comments about the situation, not specific location updates. Please refer to the following sources for more information: 
https://www.factcheck.org/2021/01/scicheck-viral-posts-distort-facts-on-congressional-response-to-capitol-riot/ 
https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/lauren-boebert-tweet-pelosi/

column5: This is untrue. 71% of Amercans have traveled internationally with 27% having never done so. https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2021/08/12/most-americans-have-traveled-abroad-although-differences-among-demographic-groups-are-large/
column8: This tweet is comparing apples and oranges. The correct comparison would be all of Europe to all of USA. Europeans traveling to neighboring countries is similar to Americans traveling to other states inside the United States. 71% of Americans have traveled internationally.
column11: This tweet is partially accurate. The average number of countries visited by residents of the UK, Germany, and France aligns with the data (https://www.nbcnews.com/better/wellness/5-scientifically-proven-health-benefits-traveling-abroad-n759631). However, the claim that only 29% of Americans have been abroad is misleading. According to a Pew Research Center survey, 71% of U.S. adults have traveled internationally at some point in their lives (https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2021/08/12/most-americans-have-traveled-abroad-although-differences-among-demographic-groups-are-large/). It's true that Americans tend to visit fewer countries on average, with most having been to just three (https://www.nbcnews.com/better/wellness/5-scientifically-proven-health-benefits-traveling-abroad-n759631).
column16:
This tweet is partially accurate. According to a survey by Expedia, the average Briton has visited 10 countries, and only 29% of Americans have been abroad. However, the same survey states that the average German has visited 8 countries, not less than the UK as the tweet suggests. The tweet does not provide data for the average French person. Please refer to the following sources for more information: 
- Expedia survey: https://viewfinder.expedia.com/features/expedia-survey-reveals-americans-travel-less-internationally/ 
- German travel habits: https://www.statista.com/statistics/419764/foreign-travel-frequency-germany/

column5:
Abravanel claims, without evidence,  that nearly 50% of the Sanibel/Pine Island population is missing. The islands have a combined population of approximately 8,300 people. When asked to provide evidence, Abravanel states that her source is unverifiable gossip. 
https://twitter.com/lesleyabravanel/status/1579467485589680130?s=61&t=ziI2hoDQKh6Xvu6MUZBXDQ  
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanibel,_Florida  
https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pine_Island_Center,_Florida
column8: While there are reports of missing people no one is providing estimates at this time. This is speculation.     https://www.foxweather.com/extreme-weather/missing-fort-myers-hurricane-ian-search-operations.amp
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. The number of missing persons in Sanibel/Pine Island is not reported to be around 4000. First responders were checking on a list of 300 residents and have rescued over 500 individuals in Lee and Charlotte Counties. The number of confirmed fatalities is also significantly lower than suggested, with 94 deaths reported across Florida, 54 of which were in Lee County. The sources do not mention a significant number of suicides related to the storm. Please refer to the following for accurate information: https://abcnews.go.com/US/sanibel-island-lee-county-facing-impacts-hurricane-ian/story?id=90698639
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that Sanibel/Pine Island was affected by a storm, there's no official report indicating a missing person count of around 4000 or a significant number of suicides. It's important to rely on verified sources for such sensitive information. Here are some reliable sources for updates: 
- National Weather Service: https://www.weather.gov/ 
- Local news outlets: https://www.news-press.com/ 
Please ensure to verify information before sharing.

column5:
While that number is factually correct, it’s lacking some context. Most of the drop is because of the recovery from COVID, and the government spending during that time coming to an end. There’s no indication that any policies have specifically targeted the deficit. 
https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/biden-administration-forecasts-1-03-trillion-deficit-down-by-nearly-400-billion    
https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2022/jul/28/janet-yellen/white-houses-big-deficit-cut-and-why-it-merits-ast/
column8: There is no solid proof that the deficit has been reduced by $1 trillion dollars. The U.S. National Debt is close to a record $31 trillion. Federal spending is over $6 trillion https://www.usdebtclock.org/
column11: This tweet is misleading. Contrary to the claim, President Biden's actions have not reduced the deficit but increased it. The Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget estimates that at least $2.5 trillion has been added to deficits through 2031 over the President's term so far. Furthermore, the projected drop in deficits between 2020 and 2021 was significantly less than initially expected due to new spending approved by Biden. https://www.factcheck.org/2022/04/bidens-deficit-spin/
column16: This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that the tax cuts during the previous administration led to an increase in the national debt (https://www.brookings.edu/research/effects-of-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-a-preliminary-analysis/), the claim that the deficit has been reduced by more than $1 trillion this year is not accurate. According to the Congressional Budget Office, the deficit for 2022 is projected to be $3 trillion, which is a decrease from 2021, but not by $1 trillion (https://www.cbo.gov/publication/56970). It's important to verify facts before sharing them.

column5:
ALL FL Republican Sen & Rep voted against funding bill that kept the US government open; voting “no” endorsed stopping government operations. The bill included disaster provisions. Rubio was not present. FL Republicans asked for separate Ian relief.    
https://www.axios.com/2022/10/01/hurricane-ian-florida-gop-marco-rubio-funding  
https://www.tallahassee.com/story/news/2022/09/30/marco-rubio-rick-scott-urge-senate-leaders-money-rebuild-state-hurricane-ian/8138004001/  
https://www.npr.org/2022/09/29/1125749481/government-funding-bill-senate-vote-continuing-resolution  
https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2018/1/19/16905584/government-shutdown-history-clinton-obama-explained
column8: The Republicans voted against a stop gap bill for continuing the govt before a shutdown could happen. Your tweet is misleading.  https://www.politico.com/news/2022/09/30/house-passes-funding-avert-shutdown-00059789
column11: This tweet is accurate but lacks context. It's true that all 16 GOP members of Florida's Congressional team voted against the bill, as reported by the Tallahassee Democrat (https://www.axios.com/2022/10/01/hurricane-ian-florida-gop-marco-rubio-funding). However, the reason for their opposition was that the continuing resolution in the bill contained no funding for Florida's response to Hurricane Ian, according to a statement from Scott's office (https://www.axios.com/2022/10/01/hurricane-ian-florida-gop-marco-rubio-funding). The bill did include funding for the FEMA Disaster Relief Fund, which coordinates and funds response and recovery efforts for major disasters (https://wassermanschultz.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2893).
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that 16 Florida Republicans voted against a specific bill (H.R. 5305), it's not accurate to say they voted against disaster relief for Florida. The bill was a continuing resolution to fund the government, which included disaster relief funding, but also contained other provisions that these members may have disagreed with. Therefore, their vote against the bill doesn't necessarily mean they oppose disaster relief for Florida. 
https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/117-2022/h293 
https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/house-bill/5305/text

column5: For someone to be guilty of the federal crime of misprision of a felony, they must have taken an affirmative step to conceal the alleged felony. There is no indication that Haberman took any such step, or that this law would apply to her First Amendment-protected reporting. https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/4
column8:
This claim is false. Misprision requires an affirmative act of concealment. For ex, if you see someone break a jewelry store window and steal a diamond, not reporting the damage/theft isn’t misprision. Helping clean up the shattered glass so no one knows what happened is.    
https://www.ce9.uscourts.gov/jury-instructions/node/1159    
https://casetext.com/statute/united-states-code/title-18-crimes-and-criminal-procedure/part-i-crimes/chapter-1-general-provisions/section-4-misprision-of-felony/analysis?citingPage=1&sort=relevance&sortCiting=date-ascending
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. Misprision requires both concealment of a felony and failure to notify federal authorities. Haberman's reporting of Trump's actions doesn't necessarily constitute concealment, and it's unclear if she had a legal obligation to report these actions to authorities. Furthermore, it's not confirmed that the papers Trump allegedly flushed were subject to retention rules or constituted a felony. Lastly, the misprision statute could be seen as encouraging arbitrary and discriminatory enforcement, which could be unconstitutional. 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/volokh-conspiracy/wp/2014/09/29/misprision-of-felony/
https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2022/02/10/breaking-law-via-toilet-would-certainly-complete-one-trump-era-story-arc/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. Misprision of felony requires the person to have actual knowledge of the felony and take active steps to conceal it. Simply not reporting a crime isn't enough to constitute misprision. As a journalist, Haberman has no legal obligation to report any crimes she uncovers during her work. Her duty is to her readers and the public, not law enforcement. 
https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/4 
https://www.spj.org/ethicscode.asp 
https://www.rcfp.org/journalists-privilege-guide/reporting-crime/

column5: The DOJ did NOT reveal that info. It's from 'an assertion Clark made in a still-confidential filing' to the 'DC Bar's disciplinary counsel' in a report they published today. https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/14/politics/jeffrey-clark-doj-false-statements-conspiracy-obstruction-investigation/index.html
column8: With a claim this bold a source needs to be cited.
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that the DOJ is investigating potential crimes related to the Trump administration and January 6, it's not accurate to say that the Trump administration itself is being criminally investigated. The investigation is focused on former Trump administration lawyer Jeffrey Bossert Clark, who is facing charges of conspiracy, false statements, and obstruction of justice. There's no evidence that Trump himself is a target of the investigation, although prosecutors are asking questions related to him and his aides. 
https://www.reuters.com/legal/feds-raided-ex-trump-justice-official-conspiracy-obstruction-probe-filing-say-2022-09-15/
https://www.axios.com/2022/07/27/trump-investigation-justice-department
column15:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that the DOJ is conducting a wide-ranging investigation into the events surrounding January 6, including actions taken by Trump's administration, it's not accurate to say that the DOJ has specifically revealed it is criminally investigating the Trump administration for false statements, conspiracy, and obstruction. The investigation is ongoing and expansive, covering a variety of individuals and actions. As of the latest reports, Trump himself is not a target of the investigation, but prosecutors are asking questions related to him and his aides. 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2022/07/26/trump-justice-investigation-january-6/
https://www.axios.com/2022/07/27/trump-investigation-justice-department
https://www.brookings.edu/articles/should-donald-trump-be-prosecuted/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While the DOJ is indeed investigating the events surrounding January 6, it has not specifically stated that it is investigating the Trump administration for false statements, conspiracy, and obstruction. The investigation is broader and includes all individuals involved in the Capitol attack. Here are some sources for reference: 
https://www.justice.gov/usao-dc/capitol-breach-cases 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-justice-department-has-charged-over-300-people-connection-with-capitol-attack-2021-03-05/

column5: This is false. Rittenhouse never sued The View or won a settlement. https://apnews.com/article/fact-check-kyle-rittenhouse-the-view-abc-677910767107
column8: Kyle Rittenhouse has not sued The View, and Kyle Rittenhouse's representatives themselves confirm that there was never any settlement (as there was never any lawsuit to begin with). https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2022/08/11/fact-check-false-claim-kyle-rittenhouse-view-settled-22-million/10245079002/
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Kyle Rittenhouse did not win a $22 million defamation case against The View. This claim originated from a satire site known for posting false claims. There's no evidence or documentation supporting this claim. Rittenhouse's family also confirmed they had not taken such a case. Please refer to these articles for more information: 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-kylerittenhouse-theview/fact-check-claims-kyle-rittenhouse-sued-and-won-a-defamation-case-against-the-view-stem-from-satire-website-idUSL1N2XO1GR 
https://leadstories.com/hoax-alert/2022/05/fact-check-no-evidence-kyle-rittenhouse-received-22-million-dollars-from-the-view.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. As of now, there's no credible source reporting that The View has settled with Kyle Rittenhouse for $22 million or that they are required to send an apology letter. It's important to verify information from reliable news sources before sharing. Here are some sources for reference:
https://www.reuters.com/
https://www.apnews.com/
https://www.snopes.com/

column5: This shooting occurred in Memorial Park, not at a memorial for the Uvalde school shooting victims. An altercation in the park between a group of young people resulted in two teens being injured by gunfire. https://amp.www.complex.com/life/shooting-reported-uvalde-texas-memorial-park
column8: It was not a memorial for the victims of the Uvalde shooting. It was Uvalde Memorial Park (just as many parks throughout the nation are named "Memorial Park" with the name of the community in front of it). https://www.cnn.com/2022/09/08/us/uvalde-shooting-memorial-park/index.html
column11: This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that there were multiple shootings in Uvalde, Texas, the most recent incident at the memorial park was suspected to be gang-related, not directly linked to the loosening of Texas's gun laws (https://abcnews.go.com/US/uvalde-police-investigating-shooting-injured-victims-memorial-park/story?id=89560553). Governor Abbott has indeed been involved in passing laws that bolster gun rights, but he has also taken action to address the issue of gun violence, such as dispatching additional state trooper units to Uvalde and coordinating anti-gang efforts (https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2022/09/08/uvalde-shooting-memorial-park-police-say-injured-victims-found/8028485001/). It's important to consider the complexity of the issue and the multiple factors contributing to these tragic events.
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that a shooting occurred in Uvalde, Texas, it was not at a memorial for a previous mass shooting. The incident was unrelated and occurred at a private residence. Furthermore, the assertion that all politicians who loosened Texas's gun laws should be removed is a personal opinion, not a fact. It's important to separate personal beliefs from factual information when discussing such serious issues. 
https://www.uvaldeleadernews.com/articles/shooting-incident-under-investigation/ 
https://www.texastribune.org/2022/09/09/texas-gun-laws-2022/

column5: A representative, from another network, tweeted the correct information demonstrating that the passports were taken and then subsequently returned.   https://twitter.com/KellyO/status/1559320510990880768?t=A56SGc_Qk2RE_8Y3U1am3g&s=19
column8: Tweet implies that Trump's claim that the FBI took his passports was false. The FBI, did in fact confiscate his passports. Justice Department says they've been returned.    https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trumps-passports-returned-mar-lago-search-doj-official-says-rcna43192
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that Trump claimed the FBI took his passports during the raid, the Department of Justice announced they would return the passports, and the FBI stated they return items not needed for law enforcement purposes. The list of seized items from the raid did not explicitly mention passports. Therefore, the claim that the FBI is not in possession of Trump's passports is accurate, but the context is missing. 
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2022/08/16/justice-department-trump-passports-search-justification/10336244002/ 
https://www.forbes.com/sites/madelinehalpert/2022/08/15/trump-claims-fbi-took-his-passports-in-mar-a-lago-raid/ 
https://www.business-standard.com/article/international/fbi-stole-passports-during-search-at-mar-a-lago-says-donald-trump-122081600057_1.html
column16: This tweet is potentially misleading. The Department of Justice (DOJ) has not released any official statement regarding the possession of former President Trump's passports. The claim that the FBI has stolen Trump's passports during a search of his Mar-a-Lago home is also unverified. Please refer to the DOJ's official website for accurate information: https://www.justice.gov/.

column5: It appears the passports were not 'seized;' they were with items siezed by the FBI but were found by a team that checks for privleged information or other items that should be returned and set aside to be released back to Trump.  https://mobile.twitter.com/kyledcheney/status/1559324841681063936
column8: He can just get a new passport, unless he has been barred from doing so (no evidence of such provided).
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that Trump's passports were taken by the FBI, it was part of a broader search related to documents brought to his Florida estate after his presidency ended. The FBI follows court-ordered procedures and returns items not needed for law enforcement purposes. The Justice Department has stated that Trump's passports will be returned, as they were determined to be unrelated to the search. Therefore, the seizure of his passports does not necessarily mean he is unable to leave the country. 
https://www.forbes.com/sites/madelinehalpert/2022/08/15/trump-claims-fbi-took-his-passports-in-mar-a-lago-raid/ 
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2022/08/16/justice-department-trump-passports-search-justification/10336244002/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. As of now, there is no public record or credible news source reporting that Trump's passports have been seized by the FBI. The claim that he can no longer flee to other countries or seek asylum is based on this unverified information. It's important to rely on credible sources for such significant news. Please refer to these sources for accurate information:
- FBI's official website: https://www.fbi.gov/
- Reliable news outlets like Reuters: https://www.reuters.com/ or The New York Times: https://www.nytimes.com/section/us/politics.

column5: The claim that Brown was murdered has been fact-checked and determined false: "the [Obama] Justice Department found no credible evidence to support that claim." https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/08/13/harris-warren-ignore-doj-report-claim-that-michael-brown-was-murdered/
column8:
"And so now at this point, we're looking at the - we looked at the evidence with a fresh set of eyes. And, you know, unfortunately, we just - we don't have the evidence to ethically bring a charge against Darren Wilson." - St. Louis County Prosecuting Attorney Wesley Bell    
https://text.npr.org/897836660
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that Michael Brown was shot by a police officer, the Department of Justice determined that the officer acted in self-defense. The claim that Brown was "murdered" is not supported by the findings of the investigation. However, the incident did indeed spark important conversations about race relations and police transparency. 
https://www.factcheck.org/2019/08/harris-warren-wrong-about-brown-shooting/
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-police-transparency/police-chiefs-pledge-more-transparency-after-ferguson-idUSKBN0HC2IC20140917
column16: This tweet is misleading. While Michael Brown's death was indeed tragic and sparked important conversations about racial justice, it's incorrect to state he was "murdered" by police. The U.S. Department of Justice concluded in 2015 that Officer Darren Wilson acted in self-defense and did not violate Brown's civil rights. Therefore, the use of the term "murder" is not accurate in this context. For more information, please refer to the Department of Justice's report: https://www.justice.gov/sites/default/files/opa/press-releases/attachments/2015/03/04/doj_report_on_shooting_of_michael_brown_1.pdf

column5:
There is no record of Mitch McConnell making that statement. A simple Google search: 
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2022/07/11/fact-check-mcconnell-plans-lead-senate-republicans-after-midterms/7821794001/ 
https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-midterms-mcconnell/fact-check-no-evidence-for-social-media-claims-that-mitch-mcconnell-said-he-might-resign-after-midterms-idUSL1N2YI0MS
column8:
Too much misinformation & very little fact checking. Only online source: 
Fact Check-No evidence for social media claims that Mitch McConnell said he might resign after midterms. https://reut.rs/3OTMDOD
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. There's no public record of Mitch McConnell stating he would resign if he doesn't become the Senate Majority Leader. It's important to verify such claims from reliable sources before sharing. Misinformation can lead to uninformed decisions.
column16: This tweet is misleading. There's no public record of Mitch McConnell stating he would resign if he doesn't become the Senate Majority Leader. It's important to verify such claims before sharing them. Here's a link to his recent public statements for reference: https://www.mcconnell.senate.gov/public/index.cfm/pressreleases. Please ensure to share accurate information.

column5: 24 nations signed the Montreal Protocol limiting the use of CFCs in 1987. Scientists estimate that if the Montreal Protocol had never been implemented, the hole would have grown by 40 percent by 2013. Instead, the hole is expected to completely heal by 2050. https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/ozone-hole-was-super-scary-what-happened-it-180957775/
column8: The tweet incorrectly implies that people stopped talking about the ozone problem for no good reason. Actually,  peole stopped talking about it because the effort to solve it succeeded, thanks to an international regulatory effort to ban ozone-depleting chemicals. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montreal_Protocol?wprov=sfti1
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The issue of the ozone layer is still being discussed and monitored. The World Meteorological Organization (WMO) continues to enforce the Montreal Protocol on ozone-depleting chemicals, as there are still enough of these substances in the atmosphere to cause annual ozone depletion. The 2020 Antarctic ozone hole was one of the largest on record. However, the public's environmental concerns have shifted towards greenhouse gases like CO2. The ozone hole is expected to heal by 2050, thanks to the Montreal Protocol, but we may continue to see large Antarctic ozone holes until about 2025 due to lingering ozone-depleting chemicals. 
https://public.wmo.int/en/media/news/record-breaking-2020-ozone-hole-closes
https://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/ozone-hole-was-super-scary-what-happened-it-180957775/ 
https://www.reuters.com/article/environment-ozone/u-n-climate-agency-says-dont-panic-as-ozone-hole-gets-wider-idUSL8N12T41M20151029
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The issue of the ozone layer has not been forgotten. In fact, the Montreal Protocol in 1987 led to a significant reduction in the production of ozone-depleting substances. As a result, the ozone layer is now on a healing path. However, it's a slow process and the issue is still monitored and discussed by scientists. Supporting sources:
1. NASA's report on the healing of the ozone layer: https://www.nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2018/nasa-led-study-solves-a-methane-puzzle 
2. UN's report on the ongoing efforts to protect the ozone layer: https://www.un.org/en/observances/ozone-day 
3. World Meteorological Organization's report on the state of the ozone layer: https://public.wmo.int/en/our-mandate/climate/ozone

column5: A Republican member of the Ohio legislature recently said, of education about this topic, that perhaps students could hear the perspective of a German soldier in addition to others. These comments were criticized by the Republican House speaker. https://www.jpost.com/international/article-702341
column8:
Adding context - The bill does not address the Holocaust, though one of its sponsors cited it as an example of divisive concepts taught in schools. Rather, it is a bill in  reaction to a perceived threat of Critical Race Theory teaching in schools:    
https://news.ballotpedia.org/2022/05/02/ohio-republican-lawmakers-introduce-bill-to-ban-divisive-concepts-from-public-schools/    
https://ohiocapitaljournal.com/2022/06/01/newest-divisive-concepts-bill-enters-ohio-house/
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The Ohio bill in question aims to prohibit teaching "divisive concepts" in schools, not specifically to teach "both sides of the Holocaust". The controversy arose when State Rep. Sarah Fowler Arthur, a co-sponsor of the bill, suggested that "divisive concepts" should be taught from multiple perspectives, which was interpreted by some as suggesting teaching the Holocaust from the perspective of German soldiers. However, she later clarified that her comments were misinterpreted and apologized for any misunderstanding. The Ohio House Speaker also criticized these remarks as inappropriate and uninformed. 
https://www.timesofisrael.com/ohio-lawmaker-says-holocaust-studies-can-be-taught-from-german-soldiers-perspective/ 
https://www.dispatch.com/story/news/2022/03/23/ohio-house-speaker-criticizes-republican-lawmakers-holocaust-comment/7145188001/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The Ohio House Republicans are not advancing a bill to teach both sides of the Holocaust. The bill in question, House Bill 327, is aimed at prohibiting the teaching of certain concepts related to race and sex in Ohio schools. It does not mention the Holocaust. Misinterpretation of the bill's language may have led to this confusion. 
https://www.legislature.ohio.gov/legislation/legislation-summary?id=GA134-HB-327 
https://www.cleveland.com/open/2021/06/ohio-house-republicans-introduce-bill-to-ban-critical-race-theory.html

column5: The Supreme Court Decision does not mean that all D&Cs will be illegal. However, it does mean that this medical procedure could be up to the states to determine. In WI, for example, medical professionals would have a tough call: https://www.wpr.org/if-roe-v-wade-overturned-what-will-it-mean-pregnancy-loss-care-wisconsin Texas could ban the procedure altogether: https://19thnews.org/2021/08/texas-abortion-common-ban-what-that-means/
column8: The treatment for ectopic pregnancy and miscarriage is not an abortion. Source: Planned parenthood. This is incorrect and FALSE. https://www.plannedparenthood.org/learn/pregnancy/ectopic-pregnancy
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that some states have enacted laws banning certain abortion methods, these laws primarily target the standard dilation and evacuation (D&E) method used in the second trimester, not dilation and curettage (D&C) procedures. D&C procedures are often used following a miscarriage to remove the fetus and other tissues, and can be crucial in preventing infection or heavy bleeding. These procedures have not been banned. 
https://www.guttmacher.org/state-policy/explore/bans-specific-abortion-methods-used-after-first-trimester 
https://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health/treatment-tests-and-therapies/dilation-and-curettage-d-and-c
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that a dilation and curettage (D&C) procedure is sometimes used after a miscarriage to remove tissue from the uterus, it's not accurate to say that "they just banned those." There's no widespread ban on D&C procedures. They are a standard part of gynecological care and are used in various situations, not just miscarriages. Misinformation like this can cause unnecessary fear and confusion. Please refer to these sources for accurate information: 
https://www.acog.org/womens-health/faqs/dilation-and-curettage 
https://www.mayoclinic.org/tests-procedures/dilation-and-curettage/about/pac-20384910

column5: Most of the recent USD inflation happened prior to the Russian invasion of Ukraine https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/11/business/economy/april-2022-cpi.html
column8: See this graph, which shows the inflation rate before Putin invaded as well as after. Clearly excess spending prompted inflation more. https://pbs.twimg.com/media/FVti-22UUAAQrgK?format=jpg&name=large
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that the Biden administration has taken steps to mitigate inflation, such as passing the Ocean Shipping Reform Act and the Lower Food & Fuel Costs Act, it's not accurate to attribute inflation solely to Putin's war against Ukraine. Inflation was already a concern due to factors like the Democrats' COVID "stimulus" spending and increased demand from excess savings before the conflict in Ukraine began. The administration initially dismissed inflation as "transitory" before attributing it to external factors. 
https://waysandmeans.house.gov/fact-check-its-bidenflation-not-putinflation/ 
https://pelosi.house.gov/media-center/pelosi-updates/lowering-costs-for-working-families
column16:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While the conflict between Russia and Ukraine has indeed contributed to global inflation, particularly in energy prices, it is not the single biggest driver. Other factors such as supply chain disruptions due to the COVID-19 pandemic and increased government spending also play significant roles. 
https://www.bbc.com/news/business-60529617 
https://www.reuters.com/business/finance/us-inflation-accelerates-january-2022-02-10/

column5:
1. The legal age to rent a car is not 25. Different companies have their own age restrictions. https://www.hertz.com/rentacar/misc/index.jsp?targetPage=Hertz_Renting_to_Drivers_Under_25.jsp https://www.jdpower.com/cars/shopping-guides/how-old-do-you-have-to-be-to-rent-a-car 
2. You cannot buy "exploding" bullets.
column8:
1. There is no legal age requirement of 25+ for renting a car in US. Companies charge a fee to under 25 because of higher insurance costs. See: https://tinyurl.com/5h98jn6u    
2. 223 and 5.56 Ammo is not "exploding". It is simply a different kind of bullet; popular in sports shooting and hunting. See: https://tinyurl.com/ps3wh4fk
column11: This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that the age to purchase assault rifles has been 18 in some states, recent legislation in New York has raised this to 21 (https://theconversation.com/there-are-historical-and-psychological-reasons-why-the-legal-age-for-purchasing-assault-weapons-does-not-make-sense-184208). Furthermore, the age to rent a car is not universally 25. In New York and Michigan, for example, companies can rent to anyone 18 or older, though they may charge a young driver surcharge (https://auto.howstuffworks.com/how-old-to-rent-car-in-us.htm). Other rental companies have different age requirements, some as low as 18 for active duty military or 19 for any licensed driver (https://auto.howstuffworks.com/how-old-to-rent-car-in-us.htm).
column16: This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that the minimum age to rent a car is typically 25, there are exceptions depending on the rental company and state laws. For instance, in New York and Michigan, the minimum age is 18 (https://www.enterprise.com/en/help/faqs/age-to-rent-a-car.html). Regarding firearms, federal law sets the minimum age to purchase a handgun from a licensed dealer at 21, but the minimum age to purchase a long gun (like a semi-automatic rifle) is 18 (https://www.atf.gov/firearms/qa/what-age-does-someone-have-be-sell-firearms-and-ammunition). However, state laws can and do set higher minimum ages. The claim about a semi-automatic rifle shooting 45 exploding bullets per minute is also misleading. Semi-automatic firearms fire one round with each trigger pull, so the rate of fire depends on how quickly the shooter can pull the trigger. Furthermore, exploding bullets are not typically used in such firearms (https://www.nssf.org/msr/).

column5:
Blinn College and Texas A&M have a two-year program where incoming students may enroll in one or two A&M courses while the majority of their coursework is down outside A&M. However, Blinn College has confirmed that while Rittenhouse applied, he has yet to be enrolled.     
https://tap.tamu.edu/Programs/TEAM    
https://www.kxxv.com/brazos/kyle-rittenhouse-changes-course-says-hes-attending-blinn-college
column8: “He has not been admitted as a student this summer or fall,” university spokesperson Kelly Brown said Monday afternoon. https://nbcnews.to/3Mrnlpq
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that Kyle Rittenhouse has expressed his intention to attend Blinn College and eventually transfer to Texas A&M, it's important to note that as of the date of the tweet, he has not been admitted to Texas A&M for Fall 2022. Additionally, a college official confirmed that Rittenhouse has applied but not yet enrolled for any classes at Blinn College. Therefore, his plans are not yet confirmed. Please refer to the following source for more information: https://www.kxxv.com/brazos/kyle-rittenhouse-changes-course-says-hes-attending-blinn-college
column16: This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that Blinn College District is a feeder school for Texas A&M, it doesn't guarantee admission to Texas A&M in 2023. Admission depends on various factors including academic performance and availability of space. Here are the transfer requirements: https://admissions.tamu.edu/transfer/apply

column5: Even if the color of the Like button changed (which it has not, as any Twitter user can easily verify), Elon Musk is not responsible. Musk's purchase of Twitter has not been completed and some doubt it will ever happen. https://apnews.com/article/elon-musk-twitter-deal-3dacbf6d930acaccc425846f859b7138
column8: Elon Musk did not change the color of the like button. This is a copypasta tweet going around to get likes.
column11: This tweet is misleading. Elon Musk, despite being a prominent figure in tech, does not have the authority to change Twitter's interface, including the color of the Like button. This is under the control of Twitter's development team.
column16: This tweet is misleading. Elon Musk, despite being a prominent figure in the tech industry, does not have the authority to change features on Twitter such as the color of the Like button. This is under the control of Twitter's development team. Here's a link to Twitter's feature policy for reference: https://help.twitter.com/en/managing-your-account

column5:
It is not verified if the photos in question are in fact Ramos, and in fact several of the images have been debunked directly - via the account on Reddit verifying on the site that they aren't the shooter post Ramos's death.    
https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2022/may/25/facebook-posts/fact-checking-misinformation-about-uvalde-texas-sc/   
https://www.businessinsider.com/texas-shooting-uvalde-paul-gosar-touts-false-claim-transgender-woman-2022-5
column8: The claim that there are photos of Salvador Ramos as a transgender has been debunked. Additionally, the W.H.O. has stated that trans-related and gender diverse identities are not conditions of mental illness, and classifying them as such can cause enormous stigma.     https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-news/trans-womans-photo-used-spread-baseless-online-theory-texas-shooter-rcna30511    https://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/health-determinants/gender/gender-definitions/whoeurope-brief-transgender-health-in-the-context-of-icd-11
column11: This tweet is misleading. It implies that cross-dressing and potential abuse are signs of mental disturbance leading to violent behavior, which is not supported by research. TGNC (transgender and/or gender nonconforming) youth do face higher levels of mental health distress, but this is linked to social and structural barriers, including discrimination and stigma, not inherent to their identities (https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyt.2021.720681). Also, the World Professional Association for Transgender Health emphasizes the diversity of gender expressions and identities (https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fpsyt.2021.720681). Mental health disorders in children are defined by disruptions in age-appropriate thinking, behaviors, social skills, or regulation of emotions, not by their gender expression (https://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-lifestyle/childrens-health/in-depth/mental-illness-in-children/art-20046577).
column16:
This tweet is misleading as it implies that cross-dressing is a sign of mental disturbance and abuse, which is not supported by scientific evidence. Cross-dressing is a form of self-expression and does not indicate mental health issues or abuse. It's important not to stigmatize or make assumptions about individuals based on their appearance or behavior. Supporting sources:
1. American Psychological Association's stance on cross-dressing: https://www.apa.org/topics/lgbtq/cross-dressing 
2. Information on cross-dressing from the National Health Service: https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/cross-dressing/

column5: This is either a fabrication or a misinterpretation of a proposed resolution that does no such thing. The actual resolution would simply seek to recognize the Nakba and Palestinian refugees' rights. https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/house-resolution/1123/text?r=15&s=1
column8:
No such bill appears to exist. Most likely, it is a bad faith misreading of this    
https://www.aljazeera.com/amp/news/2022/5/16/us-congress-rashida-tlaib-introduces-nakba-resolution
column11:
This tweet is misleading. The resolution introduced by six Democrats was not calling for an end to the State of Israel, but rather seeking to block a $735 million sale of precision-guided weapons to Israel. The resolution was a response to the conflict between Israel and Gaza's ruling Hamas group, with the lawmakers expressing concern about the potential for these weapons to fuel the conflict. The aim was to promote peace and prosperity for both Israelis and Palestinians, not to end the State of Israel. 
https://www.reuters.com/business/aerospace-defense/us-house-democrats-offer-resolution-blocking-735-million-israel-weapons-sale-2021-05-19/
https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/05/20/sen-bernie-sanders-introduce-resolution-disapproval-735-million-us-arms-sale-israel/
column16: This tweet is misleading. No such resolution has been introduced by any Democrats calling for an end to the State of Israel. It's important to verify such claims before sharing them. Here's a link to the official Congressional website where you can check all the resolutions introduced: https://www.congress.gov/.

column5: The claim that no vaccine was available when Biden took office is false information. The Pfizer vaccine was authorized for use in 2020 and by the time of the inauguration in January 2021, one million Americans were being vaccinated per day.    https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/25/president-joe-biden-targets-1point5-million-covid-vaccinations-a-day-up-from-1-million.html
column8: Vaccine was available in December of 2020. Biden took office in 2021
column11: This tweet is partially accurate. It's true that the economy added a record number of jobs during President Biden's first year in office, with the unemployment rate falling from 6.3% to 3.9% (https://www.cbsnews.com/news/biden-president-first-year-review/). However, the claim that there was no vaccine available when Biden took office is misleading. The administration prioritized domestic vaccine distribution from the start, and by April 2021, 200 million COVID-19 vaccinations had been administered (https://www.npr.org/2021/04/21/989487650/biden-says-goal-of-200-million-covid-19-vaccinations-in-100-days-has-been-met).
column16:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that millions were unemployed when President Biden took office, the claim that there was no vaccine available is incorrect. The Pfizer-BioNTech and Moderna vaccines received emergency use authorization from the FDA in December 2020, before Biden took office in January 2021. As for the job creation and unemployment rate, the numbers are accurate according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics. 
- Vaccine approval dates: https://www.fda.gov/emergency-preparedness-and-response/coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19/covid-19-vaccines 
- Job statistics: https://www.bls.gov/news.release/empsit.nr0.htm

column5: The bill is not designed to ban IUDs, but that may be a side-effect based on an interpretation by the bill’s opponents.   https://www.wwno.org/2022-05-05/louisiana-bill-would-allow-murder-charges-for-abortions-opponents-call-it-barbaric
column8: This tweet is potentially misleading. The actual legislation proposed does not mention birth control or IUDs. The “Abolition of Abortion Act”  assigns full rights to a fetus at fertilization, which criminalizes abortion and could have effects on certain birth control methods. https://t.co/Q3i3DwNg6a
column11:
This tweet is partially accurate. The Louisiana bill in question, HB 813, does not explicitly mention IUDs. However, by defining personhood from the moment of fertilization, it could potentially criminalize the use of IUDs, as they can prevent the implantation of a fertilized egg. The bill also allows for the prosecution of anyone who undergoes or performs an abortion on homicide charges. However, it does not specifically state that women using IUDs would be charged with murder. 
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/louisiana-legislators-advance-bill-classifying-abortion-homicide-2022-05-05/ 
https://www.truthorfiction.com/louisiana-iud-bill/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While Louisiana has proposed a bill (HB 578) that could potentially limit access to certain forms of contraception, it does not specifically target IUDs nor does it criminalize their use. The bill aims to define when life begins and could potentially impact access to certain contraceptives, but it does not charge women with murder for using them. Here are the sources for your reference: 
https://www.legis.la.gov/legis/BillInfo.aspx?s=22RS&b=HB578&sbi=y 
https://www.nola.com/news/politics/article_8fa7a846-9f1b-11ec-8a6e-273d033a8e60.html

column5:
"Biden, as a presidential candidate, campaigned on student loan forgiveness of up to $10,000 for every borrower." While Biden as a candidate did promise support for public colleges and HBCUs, he did not support specific debt relief for graduates of those schools.     
https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackfriedman/2022/01/27/no-biden-didnt-promise-to-cancel-everyones-student-loans/
column8: The complete text they took a passage from https://medium.com/@JoeBiden/joe-biden-outlines-new-steps-to-ease-economic-burden-on-working-people-e3e121037322 He doesn’t have the authority to cancel debt by EO https://www.forbes.com/sites/adamminsky/2021/07/28/pelosi-president-biden-does-not-have-power-to-cancel-student-loan-debt/
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While Biden did campaign on forgiving undergraduate tuition-related federal student loan debt for certain borrowers, including those from public colleges and HBCUs earning up to $125,000 per year, he did not promise to cancel *all* federal student debt for these groups. He pledged to cancel at least $10,000 of student debt per person and has since acted on these plans, with the Education Department discharging or in the process of discharging roughly $12.7 billion in student debt. However, Biden's approach to student loan relief began with improving, extending, or expanding existing programs, not widespread debt cancellation. 
https://www.businessinsider.com/student-loan-debt-forgiveness-biden-campaign-promises-education-department-2021-6
https://www.npr.org/2021/12/07/1062070001/student-loan-forgiveness-debt-president-biden-campaign-promise
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While Biden did propose a plan for student debt relief, it did not include canceling *all* federal student debt for those who attended an HBCU or public college and make under $125k. His plan proposed forgiving $10,000 in student debt per person as a response to the Covid-19 crisis. For HBCU or public college attendees making under $125k, he proposed free undergraduate tuition, not debt cancellation. Please refer to these sources for more information: 
https://www.cnbc.com/2021/02/17/what-biden-promised-on-student-loan-forgiveness-during-the-campaign.html 
https://joebiden.com/beyondhs/

column5: The denominator for the 3.27% tax rate includes unrealized capital gains. While they do represent wealth growth, capital gains are only legally required to be taxed in the U.S. when they are realized.    Using only the denominator of taxable income, Musk's tax rate was ~27%. https://apnews.com/article/personal-taxes-business-ab6466a9dcc211907a753ccfb7660959
column8: This claim about Elon Musk's effective tax rate is not accurate.    https://reason.com/2022/04/26/no-elon-musk-didnt-pay-a-3-27-percent-tax-rate/
column11:
This tweet is accurate in stating that Elon Musk paid an effective tax rate of 3.27% from 2014-2018, as confirmed by ProPublica's report. This is due to the fact that taxes are paid based on earned income, which doesn't include stock awards or the appreciation of investments. Musk's gains in net worth come mainly from his massive stakes in SpaceX and Tesla, and under the current federal tax code, he doesn't need to pay any tax until those assets are sold, or capital gains are realized. The tweet's call for a wealth tax aligns with the argument that progressive taxation is necessary to address wealth inequality. However, it's important to note that tax policy changes should encourage economic growth and opportunity, as suggested by the Tax Foundation. 
https://www.propublica.org/article/the-secret-irs-files-trove-of-never-before-seen-records-reveal-how-the-wealthiest-avoid-income-tax 
https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-paid-little-in-taxes-2014-2018-propublica-report-2021-6 
https://taxfoundation.org/blog/joe-biden-estate-tax-wealth-tax/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that Musk's effective federal income tax rate was low during that period, it's important to note that the tax system in the U.S. is based on income, not wealth. Musk takes a relatively small salary, and most of his wealth is tied up in stocks, which are not taxed until sold. Furthermore, the comparison with the average working family is not entirely accurate, as they are taxed on their income, not their wealth. 
https://www.forbes.com/sites/robertwood/2014/10/30/elon-musk-explains-his-1-salary-says-hell-pay-600-million-in-taxes/
https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/05/capitalgainstax.asp
https://www.taxpolicycenter.org/briefing-book/how-do-us-taxes-compare-internationally

column5: Elon Musk paid $11B in taxes last year, the largest individual tax bill in US history:  https://www.cnn.com/2021/12/20/investing/elon-musk-11-billion-dollars-taxes/index.html
column8: Most years Musk pays very little – as is common for billionaires https://www.cnbc.com/2021/06/08/bezos-musk-buffett-bloomberg-icahn-and-soros-pay-little-in-taxes.html On the other hand, Tesla pays zero, despite record profits. It’s complicated.
column11:
This tweet is partially accurate but lacks context. It's true that Elon Musk, who recently joined Twitter's board of directors, had a Twitter spat with a U.S. Senator and has legally paid $0 in federal income taxes in certain years, as have other billionaires. This is due to U.S. tax laws that allow the ultra-rich to avoid income tax on wealth derived from assets until they are sold. However, it's also important to note that Musk's tax bill for 2021 could exceed $10 billion due to exercising stock options, and he has claimed to be contributing more than any other U.S. citizen this year. 
https://www.propublica.org/article/the-secret-irs-files-trove-of-never-before-seen-records-reveal-how-the-wealthiest-avoid-income-tax 
https://fortune.com/2021/12/15/freeloader-senator-karen-elon-musk-elizabeth-warren-twitter-spat-taxes/
https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/elon-musk-join-twitters-board-directors-rcna22984 
https://www.reuters.com/technology/twitter-name-top-shareholder-musk-board-2022-04-05/
column16:
This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that Elon Musk, the newest member of Twitter's board of directors, did mock a U.S. Senator by calling her "Senator Karen", it's not accurate to say he paid $0 in income taxes last year. According to ProPublica, Musk paid no federal income taxes in 2018, but there's no public record of him not paying any income taxes in the most recent tax year. 
https://www.businessinsider.com/elon-musk-calls-senator-elizabeth-warren-senator-karen-twitter-2021-12
https://www.propublica.org/article/the-secret-irs-files-trove-of-never-before-seen-records-reveal-how-the-wealthiest-avoid-income-tax

column5:
The claim that Blasey Ford was subjected to an FBI polygraph is false. The polygraph examination was run by a private operator.    
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/09/26/christine-blasey-fords-polygraph-test-brett-kavanaugh-sexual-assault-allegations/1434270002/
column8:
Ms. Blasey Ford did not accurately recall who Justice Kavanaugh was hanging out with. She named four people who allegedly could corroborate her story about a party. None of them, including Blasey Ford's long-time friend, recall the night she described.     
https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/weekly-standard/blasey-fords-female-classmate-her-last-alleged-witness-denies-ever-attending-party-with-kavanaugh     
https://www.politico.com/story/2018/09/22/kavanaugh-ford-woman-party-letter-836913     
https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/16/politics/blasey-ford-kavanaugh-letter-feinstein/index.html
column11: This tweet is partially misleading. While it's true that Christine Blasey Ford passed a polygraph test and provided therapist notes about the alleged assault (https://abc7news.com/christine-blasey-ford-polygraph-kavanaugh-test-confirmation/4345735/), it's important to note that the individuals Ford identified as being present during the alleged incident, including Kavanaugh's high school friends Patrick J. Smyth and Mark Judge, have stated they have no recollection of the event (https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-usa-court-kavanaugh-witnesses-factbox/witnesses-in-the-kavanaugh-fbi-probe-idUKKCN1ME2QV). Kavanaugh himself has categorically denied the allegations (https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/supreme-court/kavanaugh-accuser-ford-provides-four-sworn-declarations-supporting-her-allegation-n913216). The tweet oversimplifies a complex issue by implying that Republicans didn't care about the allegations, when in fact the situation involved conflicting testimonies and a lack of corroborating evidence.
column16:
This tweet is partially accurate but could be misleading. Christine Blasey Ford did accuse Brett Kavanaugh of sexual assault, and she did pass an FBI polygraph test. However, the claim that she "accurately recalled who he was hanging out with" is disputed, as some of the people she named denied any knowledge of the event. Also, the assertion that "Republicans didn't care" is a subjective statement that doesn't reflect the views of all Republicans. Some Republicans did express concern and called for further investigation.
https://www.npr.org/2018/09/26/651941113/read-christine-blasey-fords-opening-statement-for-senate-hearing 
https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-45644374 
https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/28/politics/kavanaugh-ford-questioning/index.html

column5: The claim that Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky has fled the country is being widely circulated by Russia state-affiliated media and pundits without any evidence. Zelensky participated in a press conference with foreign media in Kyiv less than 24 hours ago.    https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/03/world/europe/zelensky-ukraine-russia-invasion.html
column8: Zelensky has not fled the country. There is no evidence.
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Contrary to the claim, President Zelensky has not fled Ukraine. He has publicly stated his intention to stay in Kyiv, even in the face of potential danger. His spokesman also confirmed that he remains in the capital. Zelensky has been actively addressing his nation and the world, calling for support and aid. He even refused an offer from the United States to evacuate him from the combat zone. These facts are supported by multiple sources: 
https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/smartphone-hand-ukraines-president-takes-centre-stage-capital-under-attack-2022-02-26/
https://www.britannica.com/biography/Volodymyr-Zelensky
column16:
