This tweet is misleading. As of the latest reports, President Zelensky is still in Ukraine, leading the country amidst the ongoing conflict. He has repeatedly stated his commitment to stay in Ukraine. Please refer to the latest news for accurate information: 
https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/ukraines-zelenskiy-says-he-is-staying-kyiv-2022-02-25/ 
https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-60500618

column5: COVID has always had a higher mortality rate among those 60 and older.  Medicare is for those 65 and older, thus it is logical that a greater percentage of deaths would be attributed to those with Medicare as insurance. https://data.cdc.gov/NCHS/Provisional-COVID-19-Deaths-by-Sex-and-Age/9bhg-hcku/data
column8: First author implies MC equals more death from covid. Not true at all.     Republican Party has used argument that MC is an entitlement and should not be continued as part of social safety net because it costs too much.  Hence, the above is no more than political talking point.    https://www.forbes.com/sites/christianweller/2021/04/16/republican-senators-push-social-security-medicare-and-medicaid-cuts-after-supporting-ineffective-tax-cuts/amp/
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While it's true that a significant portion of COVID-19 deaths occurred among Medicare beneficiaries, this is largely because Medicare primarily serves older adults and individuals with high comorbidity burdens, who are at greater risk of adverse outcomes from COVID-19. It's not a reflection on the quality or effectiveness of Medicare itself. The tweet could be interpreted as suggesting that Medicare is somehow responsible for these deaths, which is not supported by the data. 
https://www.bmj.com/content/382/bmj-2023-076222 
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-race/black-americans-hospitalized-for-covid-19-at-four-times-the-rate-of-whites-medicare-data-shows-idUSKBN23T34D 
https://www.factcheck.org/2020/04/hospital-payments-and-the-covid-19-death-count/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that a significant portion of COVID-19 deaths have occurred among the elderly, who are more likely to be on Medicare, this doesn't imply that Medicare is the cause of these deaths. The higher death rate is more likely due to the fact that older people are more vulnerable to severe outcomes from COVID-19. The argument for #MedicareForAll is about expanding access to healthcare, not about the quality of care provided by Medicare. 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/need-extra-precautions/older-adults.html 
https://www.kff.org/medicare/issue-brief/what-share-of-people-who-have-died-of-covid-19-are-65-and-older-and-how-does-it-vary-by-state/ 
https://www.healthaffairs.org/do/10.1377/hblog20200331.77927/full/

column5: Data misinterprets a survey from KFF. It found that 60% of adults that reported being unvaccinated self identified as Republicans, not 60% of republicans being unvaccinated. This tweet is likely pulled from figure 1 at this site https://www.kff.org/coronavirus-covid-19/poll-finding/importance-of-partisanship-predicting-vaccination-status/
column8: This is factually inaccurate. He says 60% of republicans are unvaxxed and 17% of democrats, but that is wrong...by a lot. It is really "of the unvaccinated, 60% are R and 17% are D." It's somewhat understandable, because Twitter's own Trending headline is wrong and misleading.
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. As of September 2021, the percentage of unvaccinated Republicans was 44%, not 60%, and the percentage of unvaccinated Democrats was 8%, not 17%. While it's true that vaccination rates are lower among Republicans than Democrats, the figures provided in the tweet are inflated. It's also worth noting that vaccination rates can be influenced by a variety of factors, including misinformation about vaccine efficacy. 
https://www.brookings.edu/articles/for-covid-19-vaccinations-party-affiliation-matters-more-than-race-and-ethnicity/ 
https://news.gallup.com/opinion/gallup/354938/adults-estimates-covid-hospitalization-risk.aspx
column16:
This tweet is misleading. According to the Kaiser Family Foundation, as of December 2021, 57% of Republicans and 92% of Democrats have received at least one dose of the vaccine, which does not align with the percentages given in the tweet. The politicization of the response to the pandemic is a complex issue and cannot be accurately represented by these figures alone. 
https://www.kff.org/coronavirus-covid-19/dashboard/kff-covid-19-vaccine-monitor-dashboard/ 
https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2021/10/07/partisan-differences-over-vaccine-requirements-but-not-vaccination-rates-are-growing/

column5: The vast majority of missing child cases are resolved quickly,  the vast majority are also runaways who return home rather than abductions.  In fact,  only 79 of that number are true abductions. The number Rep Boebert cites is simply the number of kids reported missing. https://www.missingkids.org/ourwork/impact
column8: Number represents reports of missing children. That means if a child runs away multiple times in a year, each instance would be entered into NCIC separately and counted in the yearly total. https://www.missingkids.org/ourwork/impact
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that many children go missing each year, the number cited includes multiple reports for the same child and runaways who may not be considered missing because their guardians know their whereabouts. Furthermore, media coverage of missing children is not guaranteed and often focuses on cases deemed newsworthy or those that generate high engagement on social media. Therefore, it's not accurate to suggest that the media is ignoring the issue.  
https://publications.aap.org/pediatrics/article/145/2/e20193752/68225/Runaway-Youth-Caring-for-the-Nation-s-Largest 
https://theconversation.com/rolling-media-coverage-of-missing-persons-cases-can-add-to-the-trauma-for-all-families-left-behind-172487
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The number quoted seems to be based on reports made to the National Center for Missing & Exploited Children (NCMEC). However, this figure includes duplicate reports and situations where children ran away multiple times. Also, the media does cover missing children cases, but it's not feasible to cover each one individually due to the sheer volume. 
1. NCMEC data: https://www.missingkids.org/footer/media/keyfacts 
2. Media coverage: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4202243/

column5:
Cancer is not a communicable disease. COVID is a highly contagious emerging virus, that is spread through the air.  Furthermore nobody in the US government is proposing lockdowns.  
https://www.cancer.org/cancer/cancer-causes/is-cancer-contagious.html  
https://www.who.int/news-room/questions-and-answers/item/coronavirus-disease-covid-19-how-is-it-transmitted
column8: Cancer, though tragic, is not contagious. Hence, no need for shutdowns or isolation.  https://www.cancer.gov/about-cancer/causes-prevention/risk/myths
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that cancer causes a significant number of deaths in the US, the comparison to the COVID-19 pandemic is not accurate. Cancer is not a contagious disease that can spread from person to person like a virus. Therefore, shutting down schools or businesses would not prevent its spread. Furthermore, the number of cancer cases and deaths are projected to increase due to population growth and aging, not because of a sudden outbreak. Efforts are needed for primary prevention to mitigate the impact of a growing and aging population. 
https://www.cdc.gov/pcd/issues/2016/16_0211.htm 
https://www.cdc.gov/pcd/issues/2021/21_0006.htm
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that cancer causes a significant number of deaths in the US, comparing it to a contagious disease like COVID-19 is not accurate. Cancer is not contagious and cannot cause a pandemic. The shutdowns and school closures were measures to prevent the spread of a highly contagious virus. 
https://www.cdc.gov/cancer/dcpc/research/articles/cancer_2020.htm 
https://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/coronavirus-disease-covid-19-how-is-it-transmitted 
https://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health/conditions-and-diseases/coronavirus/coronavirus-social-distancing-and-self-quarantine

column5: Data after a holiday almost always under reports actuals. NYC's own dashboard warns about recent data lag (https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page#aboutthedata). 7-day averages are much more reliable. Also, the 90% rate is incorrect. 88.5% of adults and 76.5% of all residents have at least one dose (https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data-vaccines.page#people).
column8: The claim that there were no COVID-19 related deaths on 11/29/21 in New York City can not be stated as fact according to NYC’s Health Dept website. https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page    The claim of 90% vaccination rate for NYC is false https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data-vaccines.page
column11: This tweet is potentially misleading. As of November 2021, the full vaccination rate in New York City is around 70%, not over 90%. While it's great news that there were no reported COVID-related deaths on that day, it's important to accurately represent the vaccination rate to avoid false security.
column16:
This tweet is misleading. As per the latest data from NYC Health, the vaccination rate in New York City is not over 90%. As of November 30, 2021, 72% of NYC residents are fully vaccinated. Also, while it's true that there are days with no reported COVID-related deaths, it's important to note that reporting can lag, especially over weekends and holidays. 
https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data-vaccines.page 
https://www1.nyc.gov/site/doh/covid/covid-19-data.page

column5: Fox News was not banned in the UK. Fox News withdrew and surrendered its broadcasting license due to low viewership.    https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/england-banned-fox-news/    https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/11/19/fact-check-uk-did-not-pull-fox-news-channel-still-airs-canada/8636298002/
column8: This tweet is almost word for word the same as the tweet that is verified as false in this article. This tweet might be propaganda.    https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/england-banned-fox-news/
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The UK did not ban Fox News. The decision to stop broadcasting in the UK was made by Fox News itself in 2017 due to commercial reasons, as it had only a few thousand viewers across the day in the UK. The UK's broadcast regulatory agency, Ofcom, confirmed that Fox News made the decision to discontinue. No record of Ofcom ever bringing sanctions against Fox News or revoking their broadcasting license has been found. 
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/11/19/fact-check-uk-did-not-pull-fox-news-channel-still-airs-canada/8636298002/ 
https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/england-banned-fox-news/ 
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sky-m-a-fox/murdoch-pulls-fox-news-from-sky-platform-as-uk-mulls-takeover-deal-idUSKCN1B91YF
column16:
This tweet is partially misleading. The UK did not ban Fox News for being 'propaganda for right-wing extremism'. Fox News was dropped by Sky, a UK-based broadcaster, in 2017 due to low viewership, not because of its political leaning. However, it's worth noting that Fox News has faced criticism from UK's regulatory body, Ofcom, for breaching impartiality rules. 
https://www.bbc.com/news/business-41151364 
https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/aug/29/fox-news-dropped-sky-uk-low-viewership

column5: This is categorically false - the CPI is up significantly, meaning consumer prices have risen for all Americans across the board. The claim that only the rich are somehow worried is absolutely incorrect, especially given the rich have become richer since the pandemic began.
column8: There are so many fundamental misunderstandings of economics in this single tweet it is nearly impossible to deconstruct. Inflation is, as it has always been, a punitive tax on the poor and those on fixed incomes.
column11:
This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that wage gains have largely gone to the highest earners, it's not accurate to attribute inflation solely to the concerns of the wealthy. Inflation is a complex economic phenomenon influenced by many factors. The impact of unemployment benefits, stimulus checks, a $15 minimum wage, and labor shortages on inflation is not straightforward. For instance, raising the minimum wage could increase the income of low-wage workers, but it could also lead to job losses and higher costs for business owners. Furthermore, not all the increased earnings from a higher minimum wage would go to low-income families. Therefore, it's an oversimplification to say that these factors are causing inflation due to the fears of the rich. 
https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2018/08/07/for-most-us-workers-real-wages-have-barely-budged-for-decades/
https://www.cbo.gov/publication/55681 
https://www.cbo.gov/publication/44995
column16:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. Inflation is a complex economic phenomenon driven by various factors, not just the ones mentioned. It's not solely driven by the rich or their assets. Unemployment benefits, stimulus checks, minimum wage, and labor shortages can contribute to inflation, but they are not the only factors. Other elements like supply chain disruptions, increased demand, and monetary policy also play significant roles. For more information, you can refer to these sources:
- Understanding Inflation: https://www.investopedia.com/terms/i/inflation.asp
- Causes of Inflation: https://www.brookings.edu/blog/up-front/2021/10/25/the-causes-and-consequences-of-inflation/
- How stimulus checks and minimum wage could impact inflation: https://www.cnbc.com/2021/03/17/how-stimulus-checks-and-a-15-minimum-wage-could-impact-inflation.html

column5: This tweet falsely makes the claim “17 yr old that crossed state lines illegally carrying an AR-15 and shot 3 white protesters?” The following article shows that the firearm did not cross state lines: https://www.npr.org/sections/live-updates-protests-for-racial-justice/2020/10/14/923643265/kyle-rittenhouse-accused-kenosha-killer-wont-face-gun-charges-in-illinois
column8: Everyone involved in this case is white. We should be advocating for equal justice under the law based on the facts of the case, not on the color of a persons skin.
column11: This tweet is partially misinformed. While systemic racism is a pervasive issue, the specific details of the Rittenhouse case are misrepresented. Rittenhouse did not cross state lines with a firearm; the gun belonged to a friend and never left Wisconsin (https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/crime/2020/08/26/wisconsin-open-carry-law-kyle-rittenhouse-legally-have-gun-kenosha-protest-shooting-17-year-old/3444231001/). He is also claiming self-defense, asserting he feared for his life during the incident (https://abcnews.go.com/US/kyle-rittenhouse-trial-ahmaud-arbery-case-expected-hinge/story?id=80687642). The trial's outcome will be determined by a jury, not the justice system as a whole (https://www.reuters.com/world/us/prosecutors-face-tough-test-trial-us-teenage-protest-shooter-rittenhouse-2021-10-28/). It's important to separate the specifics of this case from the broader issue of systemic racism.
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. The #RittenhouseTrial is a complex case with many factors at play, and it's not accurate to simplify it as a clear-cut example of systemic racism. Rittenhouse did not cross state lines with a firearm; it was given to him in Wisconsin. Also, the racial identities of the victims were not as stated in the tweet. They were white. It's crucial to base discussions on accurate information to address real issues in our justice system. 
https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2021/nov/08/facebook-posts/no-kyle-rittenhouse-didnt-cross-state-lines-ar-15/ 
https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2021/11/10/fact-check-kyle-rittenhouse-shot-three-white-men-kenosha/6361745001/

column5: The Congressional Budget Office estimated the plan would add $256 billion to the federal budget deficit over 10 years,     https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/09/28/bidens-claim-that-his-spending-plan-costs-zero-dollars/
column8: “The most credible nonpartisan review of the agenda, from the Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget, estimated it could raise the debt to anywhere between 119% and 129% of Gross Domestic Product by 2031.“    https://checkyourfact.com/2021/09/30/fact-check-joe-biden-build-back-better-agenda-cost-zero-dollars/
column11: This tweet is partially accurate. The Build Back Better Agenda does aim to raise taxes on the wealthiest and large corporations to fund its initiatives, protecting 97% of small businesses from income tax increases and delivering tax cuts to millions of entrepreneurs (https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2021/08/19/fact-sheet-the-build-back-better-agenda-will-provide-greater-tax-fairness-for-small-businesses/). However, the claim that the agenda costs $0 is misleading. The proposal is estimated to raise around $2.9 trillion, which would partially cover the $3.5 trillion legislation, with the rest expected to be made up from long-term economic growth (https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/democrats-seek-corporate-wealthy-tax-hikes-for-3-5-trillion-plan). Furthermore, the final cost of the bill is still under negotiation, with some suggesting it may need to be reduced to $1-1.5 trillion to gain necessary support (https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/democrats-seek-corporate-wealthy-tax-hikes-for-3-5-trillion-plan).
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that the Build Back Better Agenda is intended to be funded by tax increases on corporations and the wealthy, saying it costs "$0" is not accurate. The plan is estimated to cost around $3.5 trillion over 10 years. The assertion that it won't raise taxes on anyone making under $400,000 a year is also debatable, as some economists argue indirect costs could impact lower income brackets. 
https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-58675463 
https://www.cnbc.com/2021/09/28/bidens-tax-plan-could-lead-to-more-indirect-taxes-for-middle-class.html

column5: The COVID vaccine does not contain Luciferase. https://www.reuters.com/article/factcheck-moderna-luciferin/fact-check-modernas-covid-19-vaccine-does-not-contain-luciferin-or-luciferase-idUSL1N2MT265
column8: LUCIFERASE is not an ingredient in Covid  vaccines.   https://tinyurl.com/IngredientsInCovid19vaccines
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. The COVID-19 vaccines do not contain the "Mark of the Beast" as stated by Hennepin Healthcare and supported by Pastor Jamie Strickler. The idea that the mark of the beast is the vaccination is not scripturally rooted anywhere in the valid translation of Christian history. Luciferase, which the tweet mentions, is a harmless enzyme used to study cell activities and does not cause significant changes to cell metabolism. It's also important to note that mRNA vaccines do not alter human DNA. These facts are supported by multiple sources: 
https://theconversation.com/no-the-covid-19-vaccine-is-not-linked-to-the-mark-of-the-beast-but-a-first-century-roman-tyrant-probably-is-158288 
https://www.wowktv.com/news/health/coronavirus/is-the-covid-19-vaccine-equal-to-biblical-end-times-and-mark-of-the-beast/ 
https://www.poynter.org/tfcn/2020/fact-check-will-a-covid-19-vaccine-alter-your-dna/
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Luciferase is an enzyme used in medical and scientific research for its light-emitting properties, not a sinister substance. It's named after the Latin word for light-bringer, "lucifer", not the biblical figure. It's used in various tests, including some COVID-19 tests, but it's not injected into the body as part of a vaccine or treatment. Here are some sources for further reading: 
https://www.factcheck.org/2020/05/conspiracy-theory-misinterprets-goals-of-gates-foundation/ 
https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-factcheck-vaccine-idUSKBN22U2BZ 
https://www.health.com/condition/infectious-diseases/coronavirus/luciferase-covid-vaccine

column5: Per WPLG-TV (CBS Miami): "Those deaths did not all happen over the past day and span back weeks." https://www.local10.com/news/florida/2021/09/09/florida-adds-another-1296-covid-19-deaths-12k-more-cases/
column8: The 1292 deaths where from august 11th to September 9th not one day, closer to one month and daily deaths are falling rapidly   https://www.miamiherald.com/news/coronavirus/article254138753.html
column11: This tweet is misleading. According to the Florida Department of Health, the highest single-day death toll was 276 on August 11, 2021. The number mentioned seems to be a cumulative total over several days, not a single day count. Always refer to official health department data for accurate information.
column16:
This tweet is misleading. According to the Florida Department of Health's COVID-19 Data and Surveillance Dashboard, the highest single-day death toll in Florida was 272 on August 5, 2021. The figure of 1200 deaths in a single day is not accurate. Please refer to the official data for accurate information.
1. Florida Department of Health's COVID-19 Data and Surveillance Dashboard: https://floridahealthcovid19.gov/ 
2. Worldometer's Florida COVID-19 data: https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/usa/florida/

column5: Hitler was imprisoned for several months as a result of his attempted coup. This tweet seems to suggest there were no consequences at all, when in fact there were- just grossly inadequate consequences.     https://www.history.com/topics/germany/beer-hall-putsch
column8: There was no coup attempt. Calling it a coup attempt is using inflammatory language to inflame his follower base. We still need to have a trial so we can bring the evidence to light.
column11: This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that Hitler's attempted coup in 1923 failed and he later took over Germany, it's not accurate to say that no one was held accountable. Hitler was jailed for his failed Beer Hall Putsch in 1923 and used legal channels to attain power later on (https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/true-story-reichstag-fire-and-nazis-rise-power-180962240/). As for Trump, he was impeached for a second time by the House of Representatives for incitement of insurrection following the January 6 attack on the Capitol (https://adamsmith.house.gov/2021/1/rep-smith-statement-on-passage-of-article-of-impeachment-charging-trump-with-incitement-of-capitol-insurrection). However, the Senate did not convict him, which is likely what the tweet is referring to when it says Trump faces no consequences.
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that Hitler's 1923 coup attempt failed and he later took over Germany, it's not accurate to say that no one was held accountable. Hitler was arrested, tried, and sentenced to prison, where he wrote Mein Kampf. As for Trump, hundreds have been charged in connection with the January 6th Capitol riot, and investigations are ongoing. Trump himself was impeached for a second time by the House of Representatives, though he was acquitted by the Senate. 
https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/hitler-sentenced-for-role-in-beer-hall-putsch 
https://www.justice.gov/usao-dc/capitol-breach-cases

column5: Vaccines make it far less likely one will be infected with COVID, and as a result, far less likely they can spread it to others. It is true that if a vaccinated person gets a "breakthrough infection" they can spread COVID to others, but these breakthrough infections are rare. https://www.yalemedicine.org/news/covid-breakthrough-infection-transmission
column8: If you're vaccinated you're less likely to get COVID, therefore less likely to spread it. People with breakthrough infections are infectious for a shorter period of time. So if they were asymptomatic and spreading COVID, they would be doing so for less time if vaccinated.    https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/keythingstoknow.html    https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/vaccine-benefits.html
column11:
This tweet is misinformed. Vaccines do more than just reduce symptoms; they are effective against severe disease, hospitalization, and death. They also reduce the risk of infection and transmission. While no vaccine is 100% effective, the benefits of vaccination extend beyond personal health to community protection. Therefore, vaccine mandates are based on scientific evidence, not against it. 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/effectiveness/work.html 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/science/science-briefs/fully-vaccinated-people.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Vaccines do indeed reduce the risk of getting and spreading COVID-19. While breakthrough infections can occur, they are less common and typically less severe in vaccinated individuals. Vaccines also help to protect those who cannot get vaccinated, such as immunocompromised individuals, by reducing overall transmission rates. Therefore, vaccine mandates are based on scientific evidence and public health considerations, not anti-science sentiment.
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/effectiveness/why-measure-effectiveness/breakthrough-cases.html 
https://www.who.int/news-room/q-a-detail/coronavirus-disease-(covid-19)-vaccines 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/fully-vaccinated.html

column5: While the Supreme Court did allow the CDC’s moratorium to remain in place until it expired on July 31, Justice Brett Kavanaugh wrote one his concurrence that any future extension of the program would have to be approved by Congress    https://www.npr.org/2021/06/29/1003268497/the-supreme-court-leaves-the-cdcs-moratorium-on-evictions-in-place
column8: The sources in the 1st review were detailed & linked to further information. SCOTUS said no more extensions, CDC was improper agency to rule & congress must create new legislation. So few days before Aug recess - nothing happened. There's $ to but paperwork is tedious. Wait.
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misinformed. While the CDC has previously extended the eviction moratorium as a measure to control the spread of COVID-19, recent legal interpretations suggest that the CDC may have exceeded its authority in doing so. Justice Brett Kavanaugh, for instance, warned that he might change his mind about the legality of the CDC's actions if the moratorium were extended again. The CDC has stated that it does not plan to extend the moratorium further. Therefore, it's not a matter of the CDC choosing not to extend the moratorium, but rather a question of legal authority. 
https://reason.com/2021/07/08/if-the-cdc-can-impose-a-nationwide-eviction-moratorium-why-cant-it-impose-a-nationwide-vaccine-mandate/
https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2021/01/30/962390180/cdc-issues-sweeping-new-mask-mandate-for-u-s-travelers-extends-eviction-moratori
https://www.healio.com/news/infectious-disease/20210201/cdc-mandates-masks-on-public-transit-extends-eviction-moratorium-to-slow-covid19
column16:
This tweet is misleading. The CDC does not have the power to extend the eviction moratorium. This power lies with Congress. The Supreme Court ruled in June that any further extension would require legislative approval. The CDC's role is to provide public health guidance, not to make legislative decisions. 
https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/20pdf/20a169_7m58.pdf 
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/covid-eviction-declaration.html 
https://www.npr.org/2021/08/03/1024345226/cdc-eviction-moratorium-legal-politics

column5: There are pronouns in the Bible, whether you read it in English, Hebrew, or Greek. You can check out Strong's Concordance to look up every time a given word appears in the Bible. For example, here's a list of every single time the Hebrew word for "he" is used in the Bible. https://biblehub.com/hebrew/1931.htm
column8: A pronoun is a word that refers to a noun, including he/she/they/it/them. For example, the first verse in Esther says “and it was in the day of Ahauserus — he is Ahauserus”
column11: This tweet is misinformed. The Bible does contain pronouns, including those referring to God. For instance, the 2011 translation of the New International Version Bible refers to God as "He" and "the Father" (https://www.nbcnews.com/id/wbna42138347). Moreover, the Bible uses both masculine and feminine language to describe God, as seen in Exodus 3 where God's name, Yahweh, combines both female and male grammatical endings (https://theconversation.com/what-the-early-church-thought-about-gods-gender-100077). The Bible also uses gender-neutral language in some translations (https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/06/southern-baptists-embrace-gender-inclusive-language-in-the-bible/529935/).
column16: This tweet is incorrect. The Bible, in its original languages and in translations, uses pronouns extensively. For example, in Genesis 1:27 (NIV), "So God created mankind in his own image, in the image of God he created them; male and female he created them." Here, 'his', 'he', and 'them' are all pronouns. https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Genesis+1%3A27&version=NIV

column5: CDC director R. Walensky: "Right now we have no information to suggest that you need a second shot after J&J, even with the Delta variant". Source: https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/30/well/live/delta-variant-vaccines-masks.html
column8: No details on taking multiple covid vaccines. No studies have been published
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. As of the tweet's date, the CDC was not recommending boosters, stating there was not yet significant evidence of declining protection from the vaccines. Experts also advised J&J recipients to wait for more data unless Delta variant-driven infections and hospitalizations increase significantly. While some individuals may be taking an additional dose, it's important to note that this is without published data on the safety and effectiveness of combining different vaccines. The FDA has approved mRNA vaccines for use, but this does not imply a recommendation for J&J recipients to take an additional dose. The CDC considers people fully vaccinated two weeks after receiving the J&J vaccine. 
https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/booster-may-be-needed-jj-shot-delta-variant-spreads-some-experts-already-taking-2021-06-25/
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/science/science-briefs/fully-vaccinated-people.html
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. As of now, the CDC and FDA have not recommended mixing vaccines or getting a booster shot. The J&J vaccine has shown efficacy against the Delta variant. It's important to follow official guidelines and consult with healthcare professionals for personalized advice. 
- CDC: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/different-vaccines/janssen.html 
- FDA: https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/coronavirus-covid-19-update-fda-authorizes-revisions-modify-dose-volume-and-update-fact-sheets 
- J&J efficacy: https://www.jnj.com/johnson-johnson-single-shot-covid-19-vaccine-phase-3-data-published-in-new-england-journal-of-medicine

column5: Despite recent state laws that have passed this year targeting Critical Race Theory, none of these laws in any way would criminalize the teaching of Juneteenth to students.
column8: There is no state that bans the teaching of Juneteenth. The tweet conflates the commemoration of Juneteenth with state laws banning teaching CRT.
column11:
This tweet is misleading. While there are indeed debates and controversies surrounding the teaching of systemic racism and critical race theory, there is no law specifically banning the teaching of Juneteenth in any state. The importance of teaching the history behind Juneteenth, including the context of slavery, is widely recognized and advocated for. 
https://www.insider.com/as-schools-ban-critical-race-theory-teaching-juneteenth-key-to-fight-2021-6 
https://www.inquirer.com/opinion/commentary/juneteenth-schools-education-us-history-20210613.html
column16:
This tweet is misleading. While it's true that some states have passed laws limiting how certain concepts related to race and history can be taught, none specifically outlaw teaching about Juneteenth. These laws are more about how to teach about systemic racism, not about banning the teaching of specific historical events. 
https://www.edweek.org/leadership/map-where-critical-race-theory-is-under-attack/2021/06 
https://www.npr.org/2021/06/21/1008855892/what-critical-race-theory-is-really-about

column5: Reed v Reed in 1971 sets the precedent that the 14th amendment applies to biological sex. Therefore a women cannot be discriminated against.  https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/404/71/
column8: The United States Constitution protects "the people." Women are people, therefore women are protected.
column11: This tweet is partially accurate. Women's rights are indeed not explicitly recognized in the US Constitution, as the Equal Protection Clause in the 14th Amendment prohibits states from denying any person equal protection under the law, but does not explicitly guarantee women's rights (https://theconversation.com/in-2019-womens-rights-are-still-not-explicitly-recognized-in-us-constitution-108150). However, the claim that 8 in 10 U.S. adults support adding the ERA to the Constitution may be slightly overstated. While a majority of Americans do support adding the Equal Rights Amendment to the Constitution, the exact percentage is not specified in the provided references (https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2020/07/14/most-americans-support-gender-equality-even-if-they-dont-identify-as-feminists/).
column16: This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that the U.S. Constitution does not explicitly mention women's rights, the 14th Amendment provides equal protection under the law to all persons, which includes women (https://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution/amendmentxiv). As for the ERA, a 2020 survey by the Associated Press-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research found that 3 in 4 Americans support the ERA, not 8 in 10 (https://apnorc.org/projects/equal-rights-amendment/). It's important to use accurate data when advocating for change. #FactCheck

column5: Juneteenth is a holiday celebrating the emancipation of African-Americans who had been enslaved in the United States. It has been recognized by the State of Texas as an official state holiday since 1980.    https://www.tsl.texas.gov/ref/abouttx/juneteenth.html
column8: This is just Charlie’s personal opinion. A cursory search for “Juneteenth” shows it’s a commemoration of the day the last slaves were told they were free.
column11:
This tweet is misleading. Juneteenth commemorates the day when slaves in Texas were informed of their freedom, not a day based on race. It's a celebration of the end of slavery, not an affront to the unity of July 4th. These two holidays represent different aspects of America's history. The GOP's support for Juneteenth is not a shame but a recognition of a significant event in American history. 
https://news.gallup.com/poll/351041/americans-know-juneteenth-holiday.aspx 
https://www.npr.org/2021/06/17/1007551309/14-house-republicans-voted-against-making-juneteenth-a-federal-holiday
column16:
This tweet is misleading. Juneteenth is not an affront to the unity of July 4th, but rather a recognition of a significant event in American history - the emancipation of enslaved African Americans in Texas on June 19, 1865. It's not based on race, but on a historical event. The GOP's support for this is not a shame, but a recognition of an important part of American history. 
https://www.history.com/news/what-is-juneteenth 
https://www.npr.org/2021/06/17/1007315228/congress-approves-making-juneteenth-a-national-holiday-sending-bill-to-biden

column8: The statistic posted is factually incorrect. Opinions are not facts as much as Mr. Reiner would like them to be.
column11:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that a CBS News poll showed high approval for Biden's address, it's important to note that the audience was more likely to be Democrats (54%) which could skew the results. Furthermore, a Pew Research survey found that fewer than half of Americans (44%) agree with Biden on most important issues. Therefore, the 85% approval rate may not accurately represent the views of all Americans. 
https://www.cbsnews.com/news/cbs-news-poll-most-viewers-approve-of-bidens-speech/ 
https://www.pewresearch.org/politics/2021/04/15/biden-nears-100-day-mark-with-strong-approval-positive-rating-for-vaccine-rollout/
column16:
This tweet is potentially misleading. While it's true that President Biden's address was well-received, the 85% approval rating comes from a CBS News poll that surveyed viewers of the speech, not all Americans. This group is more likely to be Biden supporters. Also, the assertion that Republicans "stand for nothing" is a subjective opinion, not a fact. 
https://www.cbsnews.com/news/biden-speech-poll-viewers-85-percent-approve/ 
https://www.factcheck.org/2021/04/scicheck-bidens-speech-to-congress/

column5: It’s a Shakespearean phrase from Macbeth and it’s easily searchable ~ https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/56964/speech-tomorrow-and-tomorrow-and-tomorrow and https://www.sparknotes.com/shakespeare/macbeth/quotes/page/5. It’s perhaps one of the most important quotes from Macbeth.
column8: It’s a quote from Act 5, Scene 5 of Shakespeare’s Macbeth
column11:
This tweet is partially misinformed. While it's true that "The Sound and the Fury" is a novel by Faulkner, the phrase "full of sound and fury, signifying nothing" is originally from a soliloquy in Shakespeare's play Macbeth, which Faulkner used as the title of his novel. Therefore, Senator Cruz's reference to Shakespeare is accurate. 
https://www.britannica.com/topic/The-Sound-and-the-Fury-novel-by-Faulkner 
https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1985/07/21/faulkner-and-the-bridge-to-the-south/f7ac3ba1-8159-4b83-8259-6c2984264245/
column16:
This tweet is misinformed. While Faulkner did use the phrase "sound and fury signifying nothing" in his novel, the phrase originally comes from Shakespeare's play "Macbeth." Therefore, Senator Cruz's comparison is accurate. Here are the references: 
- Shakespeare's Macbeth: https://www.sparknotes.com/nofear/shakespeare/macbeth/page_176/ 
- Faulkner's usage: https://www.cliffsnotes.com/literature/s/the-sound-and-the-fury/summary-and-analysis/chapter-4

column5: This is an opinion and not a fact. Memes do not have expiration dates. They may, in fact, become irrelevant, but that is not an expiration date. People should be allowed to see memes and decide for themselves if they are relevant.
column8: Memes do not have expiration dates.
column11:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While individual memes may lose popularity over time, they don't have a set "expiration date". The lifespan of a meme can vary greatly, with some lasting years and others only a few weeks. This is often dependent on cultural context and trends at the time. For example, memes inspired by The Office have remained popular due to the show's continued relevance and popularity on Netflix. However, to effectively use a meme, it's important to be aware of what's currently trending. 
https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2017/12/a-unified-theory-of-meme-death/546866/
https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesagencycouncil/2018/07/19/more-than-a-trend-meme-marketing-is-here-to-stay/
https://time.com/5763852/best-the-office-memes/
column16:
This tweet is somewhat misleading. While memes do not have literal expiration dates, they can become less popular or relevant over time due to changes in internet culture and trends. However, some memes have proven to be timeless and continue to be used years after their creation. 
https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/08/the-lifespan-of-a-meme/401813/ 
https://www.vox.com/culture/2018/12/27/18137571/what-is-a-meme-dank-meme-explained
